## Preface to the Paperback Edition

### The Efficient Market Hypothesis Challenged

- **Efficient market hypothesis (EMH)**: Markets cannot be beat because prices reflect all known information and adjust instantly to new information
- Three forms of EMH:
  - **Weak efficiency**: Past price data cannot beat the market (technical analysis worthless)
  - **Semi-strong efficiency**: Public information cannot beat the market (fundamental analysis worthless)
  - **Strong efficiency**: Even private information cannot beat the market (insider trading rules pointless)

> "Corollary: The readers of this book are delusional."

### Fundamental Flaws in EMH

- EMH assumes everyone uses information with equal effectiveness—but equal information doesn't imply equal skill
- **Chess analogy**: All players know same rules and have access to same chess books, yet only a small minority excel—skill matters
- Markets are more complex than chess—a few highly skilled participants can exploit mistakes of weaker players and drive prices to incorrect levels

### Emotions and Market Inefficiency

- EMH proponents correct that markets are difficult to beat, but **wrong reason**
- Difficulty stems from **impact of emotions on price**, not instantaneous information incorporation
- Emotions cause **market bubbles** (prices wildly overshoot fair value) and **market panics** (prices plunge below fair value)
- Example: **October 19, 1987** — S&P futures fell 29% in one day. If EMH correct, probability = 10^-160 (equivalent to randomly picking same atom twice in universe)
- Emotions can temporarily outweigh informed traders (hedgers, governments trade for non-profit motives)

### Evidence Against EMH

- Some market participants achieve track records that are statistical impossibilities under EMH
- Market prices completely out of line with plausible valuations are common
- Price moves often occur well **after** fundamental news is known
- Everyone having same information ≠ everyone using it equally efficiently
- EMH fails to incorporate human emotions as key price driver

### Example: NASDAQ Bubble (1999-2000)

- Trader who shorted NASDAQ at 3,000 in late 1999 would be fundamentally correct (eventually traded 1,100-2,900 range in following decade)
- But market soared additional 68% to 5,048 by March 2000 before collapsing
- **Timing problem**: Being right about value but early can still destroy you

> "There is certainly no need to resort to the assumption of market perfection to explain why winning in the markets is difficult."

### Trading: Innate Talent vs. Hard Work

- **Marathon analogy**: Most people can run a marathon with training, but only small minority can run 2:15 (men) or 2:30 (women) time regardless of effort
- Trading proficiency achievable with hard work, but **elite-level performance requires innate talent**
- Market Wizards possess "some innate skill, or some inner radar" that gives better-than-even probability of sensing market direction
- Not about devotion or hours—it's about having skill most people lack

## Preface

### Overview of the Market Wizards

- Trader who turned $30,000 into $80 million after early wipeouts
- Fund manager with five consecutive years of triple-digit percentage returns
- Small-town trader who became one of world's largest bond traders
- Former securities analyst averaging **25% monthly return** (over 1,400% annualized) for seven years, primarily trading stock index futures
- **MIT electrical engineering graduate**: 250,000% return over sixteen years via computerized approach

### Common Denominator: Attitude Over Approach

- Success stems from **attitude, not methodology**
- Some use only fundamental analysis, others only technical, still others combine both
- Time horizons vary from minutes to years
- Trading methodologies widely varied, but **important commonalities in attitudes and principles**

### Trading as Opportunity

- One of last great frontiers where individual can start with small bankroll and become multimillionaire
- Only handful succeed (like those interviewed), but opportunity exists
- Goal: Help serious, open-minded readers improve trading performance; may help select few become super-traders

> Written in Goldens Bridge, NY, May 1989 — **Jack D. Schwager**

## Acknowledgments

- **Stephen Chronowitz**: Edited every chapter, provided multitude of suggestions
- **Jo Ann Schwager**: "Book widow" for nine months, brutal honesty as sounding board (excised worst material)
- Traders interviewed were altruistic—already successful, participated to help new traders
- **Elaine Crocker**: Friendly persuasion made some chapters possible
- Three traders granted lengthy interviews not incorporated: **Irv Kessler**, **Doug Redmond**, **Martin Presler** (first two too esoteric/technical; latter due to deadlines)

## Prologue

### The Big Board — Kurt Vonnegut Analogy

- **Slaughterhouse Five** reference: Earthlings kidnapped by aliens, put in zoo on **Zircon-212**
- Zoo habitat had big board with stock/commodity quotes, news ticker, telephone to Earth brokerage (all fake)
- Captives told they had $1 million invested—stimulants made them react vividly to fake market moves
- Earthlings prayed during National Prayer Week after bad week in olive oil futures—olive oil went up

### Random Walk Theory vs. Trader Skill

- **Random walk theorists**: Traders are like Kilgore Trout's zoo inhabitants—success is luck, not skill
- **Kilgore Trout**: Ubiquitous science fiction writer in Vonnegut's novels
- If markets truly efficient and random, traders attributing success to skill are deluded
- After interviewing traders, hard to believe some can win with such consistency over vast numbers of trades and many years
- Traders themselves have no doubt: **skill, not luck** determines long-run winners

## My Own Story (Jack D. Schwager)

### Early Career and Initial Trades

- Commodity research analyst out of graduate school
- Economic/statistical analysis correctly predicted commodity price moves
- Frustrated department didn't permit analysts to trade
- **Michael Marcus** (first interviewee) introduced him to broker willing to open account
- Earned less than department secretary—brother opened $2,000 account, Schwager acted as advisor
- Kept account secret, had to use basement pay phone to place orders (nerve-wracking delays)

### First Major Trade: Cotton Analysis

- Detailed analysis of cotton market throughout post-WWII period
- Discovered only two seasons since 1953 were **free markets** (without government support programs)
- Concluded only these two seasons valid for forecasting
- Cotton trading at 25 cents/lb, forecast peak around 32-33 cents

### The Wipeout

- Cotton initially rose as predicted (28 to 31 cents in one week)
- News seemed unimportant—went short near projected top
- Market moved slightly higher then broke back to 29 cents (seemed to confirm analysis)
- Instead of taking profit, held short position
- Cotton rebounded to new highs: 32, 33, 34, 35 cents
- Account equity wiped out, forced to liquidate
- **Luckiest break**: Not having much money prevented bigger loss
- Cotton eventually soared to **99 cents**—more than double century's previous high!

> "That trade knocked me out of the box for a while."

### Pattern of Failure and Breakthrough

- Tried trading several more times over next few years
- Each time started with not much more than $2,000, eventually wiped out by single large loss
- **Two breakthroughs**:

**1. Meeting Steve Chronowitz** (precious metals analyst at Hornblower & Weeks)
- Shared office, became friends
- **Steve**: Strictly technical analyst (vs. Schwager's pure fundamental approach)
- **Fundamental analyst**: Uses economic data to forecast prices
- **Technical analyst**: Uses internal market data (price, volume, sentiment) to project prices
- Initially skeptical of technical analysis, but noticed Steve's calls were often right
- Realized fundamental analysis alone insufficient—needed technical analysis for **timing**

**2. Risk Control Epiphany**
- **Risk control absolutely essential** to successful trading
- Decided never to lose everything on single trade, regardless of conviction
- Turning point trade: **Deutsche mark** long position with good-till-cancelled stop just below recent low
- Market started falling, stopped out at small loss
- Previously this type of trade would have wiped him out—instead, suffered only minor loss

### Building Success

- Went long **Japanese yen** after technically bullish consolidation
- Felt reasonably able to define risk at only 15 ticks per contract
- Put on **three-contract position** (unusual confidence due to defined risk)
- Market never looked back—held one contract long enough to triple small account
- **Synthesis of technical and fundamental analysis + risk control** allowed building small stake to over $100,000

### The Second Wipeout

- Began trading impulsively, failing to follow rules
- Losing trade in **soybeans**: Instead of taking loss, convinced decline was bull market reaction and substantially increased position
- Mistake compounded by adding in front of important government crop report
- Report bearish—equity took dramatic decline
- Surrendered over one-quarter of cumulative profits within days

### Recovery and Current Status

- Cashed in chips to buy house, took year-long sabbatical to write book
- Savings depleted—deferred reentry to trading nearly five years
- Started again with $8,000 (most lost over a year)
- Added another $8,000, eventually scored big winning trades
- Within two years rebuilt account to over $100,000
- Subsequently stalled out—past year account equity fluctuated below peak

### Emotional Perspective and Book Motivation

- Objectively successful, but emotionally views as failure
- Feels given market knowledge and experience, should have done better
- **Frustration**: "Why have I been able to multiply sub-$10,000 account more than tenfold twice, yet unable to expand equity beyond that level?"
- Motivation for writing book: Ask successful traders for answers
  - What are key elements to success?
  - What approach do you use?
  - What trading rules do you adhere to?
  - What were early trading experiences?
  - What advice for other traders?
- Search for answers both personal (surpass own barriers) and universal (Everyman asking what others would ask)

## Part I: Futures and Currencies

### Taking the Mystery Out of Futures

**Futures Market Growth**
- 1988: Dollar value of futures contracts traded in U.S. exceeded **$10 trillion**
- Trading volume expanded twentyfold over twenty years
- Least understood by most investors, yet one of fastest growing markets

**Major Market Groups**
- **Interest rates** (T-bonds)
- **Stock indexes** (S&P 500)
- **Currencies** (Japanese yen)
- **Precious metals** (gold)
- **Energy** (crude oil)
- **Agricultural commodities** (corn)

**Shift from Agricultural to Financial**
- Origins in agricultural commodities
- Now only ~10% of total futures trading
- Financial markets (currencies, interest rates, stock indexes) = ~60% of trading
- Energy and metals = nearly half of remaining 40%
- Term "commodities" increasingly a misnomer—many actively traded futures (financial instruments) not truly commodities

**Essence of Futures**
- Trading involves standardized contract for commodity or financial instrument for **future delivery date** (vs. present time)
- **Hedging example**: Automobile manufacturer concerned copper prices will rise in six months can lock in costs by buying copper futures now
- If copper climbs, futures hedge profit offsets higher copper cost at actual purchase
- If copper declines, futures loss offset by buying copper at lower levels than willing to lock in

**Seven Advantages of Futures Markets**

1. **Standardized contracts**: Don't need to find specific buyer/seller to initiate or liquidate position
2. **Liquidity**: All major futures markets provide excellent liquidity
3. **Ease of going short**: Equal ease going short as long (no uptick restriction like stocks)
4. **Leverage**: Tremendous leverage—initial margin usually 5-10% of contract value
   - **Margin** in futures = good-faith deposits (NOT partial payments like stocks)
   - Undisciplined use of leverage = single most important reason most traders lose money
   - Futures prices no more volatile than underlying cash prices or many stocks
   - High-risk reputation largely consequence of leverage factor
5. **Low transaction costs**: Far less expensive for stock portfolio manager to reduce exposure via index futures than selling individual stocks
6. **Ease of offset**: Position can be offset anytime during market hours (not locked at limit-up/limit-down)
7. **Guaranteed by exchange**: No concern about financial stability of counterparty

**Connection to Underlying Markets**
- **Arbitrageurs** ensure futures prices closely parallel underlying cash markets (deviations minor and short-lived)
- Majority of futures trading in financial instruments
- **Futures traders often really trading stocks, bonds, currencies**
- Comments of futures traders in following chapters have direct relevance to investors who never ventured beyond stocks and bonds

## The Interbank Currency Market Defined

**24-Hour Global Market**
- Literally follows sun around world: U.S. → Australia → Far East → Europe → back to U.S.
- Banking centers provide continuous trading

**Purpose: Hedge Exchange Rate Risk**
- Companies need to hedge exchange risk in world of fluctuating currency values
- **Example**: Japanese electronics manufacturer negotiates export sale to U.S., payment in dollars six months hence
- Vulnerable to dollar depreciation vs. yen during interim
- To lock in profit, can hedge by selling equivalent U.S. dollars in interbank market for anticipated payment date
- Banks quote exchange rate for precise amount required, for specific future date

**Speculation**
- Speculators trade to profit from anticipated shifts in exchange rates
- All interbank market transactions denominated in U.S. dollars
- Example speculation: Decline in British pound vs. dollar → sell forward British pounds
- Example cross-currency: British pound decline vs. Japanese yen → buy specific dollar amount of yen, sell equivalent dollar amount of British pounds

## Michael Marcus: Blighting Never Strikes Twice

### Background
- Began as commodity research analyst for major brokerage
- Near-compulsive attraction to trading led him to abandon salaried position for full-time trading
- Brief stint as floor trader, then joined **Commodities Corporation** (firm hiring professional traders for company funds)
- Became one of most successful traders—profits exceeded combined total of all other traders for number of years
- **Ten-year period: Multiplied company account by incredible 2,500-fold!**

### First Meeting
- Schwager met Marcus when joining Reynolds Securities as futures research analyst
- Marcus accepted similar job at competing firm (position Schwager assumed)
- Early careers overlapped—though usually found own analysis more persuasive, Marcus ultimately proved right about market direction
- Eventually Marcus accepted job as trader, became very successful, moved to West Coast

### Interview Setting
- Seven years since last contact when interview conducted
- Marcus's home: Two-house complex on cliff overlooking private beach in Southern California
- Enter through massive gate ("amazing gate" per assistant—could hold up through panzer division attack)
- First greeting: Marcus seemed aloof, almost withdrawn—quiet side of personality
<!-- pp. 31-50 -->

## Michael Marcus (continued)

### First Trading Experiences — The Disasters

- 1969: Graduated **Johns Hopkins**, Phi Beta Kappa, near top of class. Had Ph.D. fellowship in psychology at **Clark University**, expected professor life
- Met "John" through mutual friend who claimed he could **double money every two weeks**
- Hired John as commodity advisor at $30/week (plus free potato chips and soda)
- Started with **$1,000 saved**

#### The Brokerage Visit

- First visit to **Reynolds Securities** in Baltimore felt reverent — mahogany, hushed tones
- Old-fashioned **commodity board** clicking prices at front of office
- Had to use binoculars to see prices from gallery — "like watching a horse race"

#### Early Losing Trades

- First realization John knew nothing: loudspeaker recommended buying soybean meal, John looked uncertain and asked "Do you think we should do it?"
- **Soybean meal** trading 78.30, 78.40 — as soon as they bought, prices clicked down. Lost ~$100
- Next trade in **corn** — same result
- Neither knew contract sizes, only knew cost per tick
- **Measuring success by days it took to lose** — took three days to lose money on winning wheat trade (bought wheat, held too long)

#### The "Can't Lose" Pork Belly Trade

- Down to $500, John proposed buying **August pork bellies** and selling **February pork bellies** because spread wider than **carrying charges** (cost of taking delivery, storing, redelivering)
- John said "can't lose on that trade" — but August pork bellies weren't deliverable against February contract
- **The logic was fundamentally flawed**
- John went to quote board shouting "Doesn't anyone want to make a guaranteed profit?" — pounding his fist
- Marcus wiped out entirely

> "You are making the greatest mistake of your life!" — John's response when Marcus fired him

- John said he was going to Bermuda **to wash dishes** to make a trading stake, then become a millionaire
- Marcus never heard from John again
- **First eight trades** (five with John, three alone) — all losers

### Learning the Basics — Early Wins

- Despite losses, Marcus figured it was "question of getting the knack of it"
- Father died when Marcus was 15, left $3,000 life insurance — Marcus cashed it in against mother's objections
- Knew he needed to learn before trading again
- Read **Chester Keltner's** books on wheat and soybeans, subscribed to his market letter with trading recommendations

#### First Real Win

- Followed Keltner recommendation to buy wheat — made **4 cents per bushel ($200)**
- Market fell back to original buying price, bought again on own intuition — made another profit
- "Beginning to develop a sense for trading. Liked doing things on my own."
- Summer 1970: Bought three contracts **December corn** based on Keltner recommendation
- **Corn blight** devastated crop that summer

> "That was the summer that blight devastated the corn crop."

- Accumulated **$30,000** by end of summer — "princely sum" for middle-class background
- "Thought it was the best thing in the world."
- Took profits on way up and when markets started coming down — "cashed in very well"
- "Instinctively doing the right thing even then"

### Graduate School and the Blight Trade

- Fall 1970: Attended graduate school in **Worcester, Massachusetts**
- Couldn't focus on thesis — would sneak down to **Paine Webber** office to trade
- Realized "handwriting was on the wall" — dropped out December 1970, moved to New York
- Stayed at YMCA briefly, told people pompously "I was a speculator"

#### Spring 1971 — The Corn Blight Returns

- Theory circulating that **blight had wintered over** and would attack corn crop again
- Borrowed **$20,000** from mother, added to $30,000 — bet everything on the blight
- Bought maximum corn and wheat contracts possible for **$50,000 in margin**
- Markets held steady initially due to blight fear
- **Wall Street Journal** headline: "More Blight on the Floor of the Chicago Board of Trade Than in Midwest Cornfields"
- Corn market opened sharply lower, went **limit-down**

#### Paralyzed in a Collapsing Market

- Watched board as prices fell, felt he should get out but "totally paralyzed"
- "Hoping market would turn around. Watched and watched and then after it locked limit-down, I couldn't get out."
- Had all night to think but "really had no choice. Didn't have any more money."
- Liquidated entire position next morning on opening
- Lost **$30,000 of own money + $12,000 of mother's loan** = $42,000 total loss

> "That was my lesson in betting my whole wad."

### Getting a Real Job — Research at Reynolds

- Really upset, decided had to go to work
- During recession, thought couldn't get good job — should settle for lesser position
- Found **commodity research analyst** slot at **Reynolds Securities**
- Easier to get because they could tell he really wanted it
- "If you shoot for what you want, you stand a much better chance of getting it because you care much more."

#### Secret Trading While Working

- Glass partition between his office and main office where brokers sat
- Analysts strictly forbidden to trade
- Borrowed from mother, brother, girlfriend — opened account at another firm
- Worked out **intricate code system** with broker to hide violations — "sun was out" meant one thing, "weather is cloudy" meant something else
- While writing market reports, kept peering through glass partition to see prices on trading board
- "In manic-depressive state throughout that time. Felt tortured because wanted to be free to trade."
- Was losing money — "same old cycle of borrowing money and consistently losing it"

### Meeting Ed Seykota — The Turning Point

- October 1971: Met **Ed Seykota** at broker's office
- "Genius and great trader who has been phenomenally successful"
- Recently graduated **MIT**, developed one of first **computer programs for testing and trading technical systems**
- Seykota told Marcus: "I think you ought to work here. We are starting a research group and you can trade your own account."
- Research director refused to hire Marcus

> "I can't hire you because you already know too much and I want to train somebody." — Research director's rejection

- Marcus convinced him: "Look, I will do anything you want."

#### Seykota's Lessons

- **Trend follower** utilizing classic trading principles
- Taught Marcus **how to cut losses** and **importance of riding winners**
- Example: Short silver, market kept eking down half penny a day. Everyone seemed bullish, talking why silver had to go up, but Seykota stayed short
- "The trend is down, and I'm going to stay short until the trend changes."
- Marcus "learned patience from him in the way he followed the trend"

### Continued Struggles Despite Mentorship

- Not initially successful even with Seykota's guidance — continued to lose
- "I think I wasn't patient enough to wait for a clearly defined situation"
- Couldn't bring himself to just tailcoat Seykota despite his success
- Sometimes thought of giving up — very painful to keep losing

> "Am I really that stupid?" — Marcus looking up, referencing *Fiddler on the Roof* scene where lead talks to God

- Seemed to hear clear answer: "No, you are not stupid. You just have to keep at it."

#### Second Mentor — Amos Hostetter

- Befriended by **Amos Hostetter**, kind, knowledgeable, successful semi-retired broker at **Shearson**
- Hostetter reinforced many things Seykota taught
- "Getting the same principles from two people"

### Building Back Up — The Plywood Trade

- Making firm recommendations, improved because more patient
- Totally out of money and lenders by late 1971/early 1972
- "Stubborn confidence that I could somehow get back on the right track again"
- Making $12,500/year, managed to save $700
- Opened **joint account** with friend who put up $700

#### Nixon's Price Freeze

- July 1972: Trading under **Nixon price controls**
- Futures market supposedly also under price controls (gray area)
- **Plywood** price theoretically frozen at **$110 per 1,000 square feet**
- Marcus analyzed plywood for firm — price edged close to $110
- Put out bearish newsletter: "Since prices couldn't go beyond $110, there was nothing to lose by going short at $110"
- Illegal for prices to go higher by law

#### The Price Control Arbitrage

- Price kept artificially low created **economic shortage** (basic principle)
- One day at quote board: price hit $110, then $110.10, then $110.20
- **Futures price trading 20 cents over legal ceiling**
- Called around to see what was happening — nobody knew
- Next day opened ~$110.80
- Reasoning: "If they let it trade over $110 today, they might let it trade anywhere"
- Bought one contract
- **Plywood went to $200** — ultimately a pyramiding/riding the position trade
- "First really big trade after had been wiped out in corn market"

#### Did Cash Market Stay at $110?

- **Futures market functioned as supply of last resort** for users who couldn't get supplies elsewhere
- Created **two-tiered market** — "sort of legal black market"
- Those frozen out of longstanding producer relationships could get plywood at higher price in futures
- Producers angry they had to sell at legal price ceiling
- Most producers not sophisticated enough to sell futures and deliver against contract
- Some weren't sure it was legal; lawyers may have warned against it

#### Government Intervention in Lumber

- Marcus got idea same shortage situation going to occur in **lumber**
- Bet everything on one trade expecting lumber to go through ceiling price
- Lumber did nothing — just watched plywood go $110 to $200
- Since both wood products and lumber in short supply, reasoned lumber could go way up
- After Marcus bought lumber around $130, **government announced crackdown on speculators in lumber**
- Lumber market crashed on that statement
- Down to point "close to being wiped out again"
- **Two-week period** of government issuing statements — market stabilized just above where he would have been wiped out
- "Had just enough money left to hang on to my position"
- "Worst two weeks in my whole life. Went to office each day just about ready to give up."
- So upset couldn't stop hands from shaking

#### Holding On

- $12,000 had shrunk to under $4,000
- "Never did it again. That was the last time I bet everything on one trade."
- Managed to hold on, market finally turned around
- Shortage real, government didn't have will to stop futures market
- By end of that year (1972), $700 which ran up to over $12,000 and back to under $4,000, was now worth **$24,000**
- "After that scary experience, I never really overtraded again"

### The Great Commodity Bull Market of 1973

- 1973: Government began lifting price controls
- Price controls had created numerous artificial shortages
- When lifted, **tremendous run-up in many commodities**
- "Just about everything went up. Prices doubled in many markets."
- Able to take advantage of tremendous leverage offered by low futures margins
- Lessons learned from Seykota about staying in markets with major trends really paid off
- **Account grew from $24,000 to $64,000** in 1973

#### Understanding Why Prices Could Rise Further

- Even after prices gone up only 10% of eventual advance, seemed like very large price move historically
- Marcus politically **right wing**, fit with being **inflation-alarmist**
- Theory: "evil government constantly debasing currency" — perfect perspective for trading inflationary markets of mid-1970s
- "It was the right theory for the right time"
- Markets so fertile for trading could make plenty of mistakes and still do well
- Trading strictly on long side

#### The Soybean Bull Market Mistake

- Did very well but made "one terrible mistake"
- Great soybean bull market went from **$3.25 to nearly $12**
- Impulsively took profits and got out of everything
- "Trying to be fancy instead of staying with the trend"
- Ed Seykota never would get out unless trend changed
- Seykota was out, Marcus watched in agony as soybeans went **limit-up for twelve consecutive days**
- "Real competitive" — every day came to office knowing Seykota was in and he was out
- "Dreaded going to work, because I knew soybeans would be bid limit again and I couldn't get in"

#### The Thorazine Incident

- Experience of not being in runaway market "more so" aggravating than actually losing money
- So aggravating one day "felt I couldn't take it anymore and I tried tranquilizers to dull the mental anguish"
- Took **thorazine** at home, then got on subway to work
- Subway doors started to close as getting on, started to fall down
- Didn't connect it with thorazine at first
- Wandered back home, fell through doorway — "it was that strong"
- Knocked out, missed work that day
- "That was the low point in my trading career"
- Afraid of losing, but never threw in towel

### The Cotton Exchange

- Around that time would occasionally go to **Cotton Exchange**
- Adrenalin rush when heard traders yelling and screaming — "seemed like the most exciting place in the world"
- Learned needed to show **$100,000 net worth** to get in
- Since had virtually no assets outside commodity account, couldn't qualify
- Continued to make money in markets
- After several months, surpassed $100,000 mark
- Ed Seykota recommended go long **coffee**, put close stop in under market
- Market turned down, Marcus stopped out quickly
- Ed, major trend follower, had no stop and ended up **locked in limit-down market for several days** in succession

#### Competitive Joy in Others' Pain

- Each day Seykota locked in losing position while Marcus out of market
- Opposite of soybean trade situation — Seykota in winning trade, Marcus out
- "Couldn't help it, but I felt a sense of joy"
- Asked himself: "What kind of place is this that one's greatest joy is to be found when somebody else is getting screwed?"
- Realized what he was doing was **too competitive**
- Decided to become **floor trader at New York Cotton Exchange**

### Becoming a Floor Trader

- Concerned about reducing field of opportunity to one market
- "Should have been very worried" — floor would be even more competitive
- Truth: "trading in ring was very exciting to me"
- Good at picking trades, **total bust at execution**
- Very shy, too timid to yell loud enough to be heard on floor
- Ended up **slipping orders to floor trader friend** who handled them
- Went on for few months until realized what he was doing
- Still approaching markets as position trader even on floor — just out of timidity
- Many days not even trading

#### What He Learned on the Floor

- Developed **almost subconscious sense of market on floor**
- Learn to gauge price movement by **intensity of voices in ring**
- When market active and moving, then gets quiet — often sign not going much further
- When ring moderately loud and suddenly gets very loud — instead of sign market ready to blast off, actually indicates market **running into greater amount of opposing orders**

#### Applying Floor Lessons Off-Floor

- Learned importance of **intraday chart points** (e.g., earlier daily highs)
- At key intraday chart points, could take much larger positions than could afford to hold
- If didn't work immediately, would get out quickly
- At critical intraday point: take twenty-contract position instead of three-to-five could afford to hold, using extremely close stop
- Market either took off and ran, or was out
- Sometimes would make **300-400 points or more with only 10-point risk**
- Because on floor, became familiar with how market responded to intraday points
- "Trading in those days was a little bit like being a surfer. Trying to hit crest of wave just at right moment."
- If didn't work, just got out
- "Getting shot at making several hundred points and hardly risking anything"
- Later used that surfing technique as desk trader
- "Although that approach worked real well then, I don't think it would work as well in today's markets"

### Why Markets Changed — Loss of Trend-Following Edge

- Markets have become **choppier**
- In those days, if market reached intraday chart point, might penetrate, take off, never look back
- Now often comes back
- Secret is **cutting down number of trades**
- Best trades: all three things going for you — **fundamentals, technicals, market tone**
- Fundamentals: imbalance of supply/demand could result in major move
- Chart must show market moving in direction fundamentals suggest
- When news comes out, market should act in way that reflects right psychological tone
  - Bull market should shrug off bearish news and respond vigorously to bullish news
- "If you can restrict your activity to only those types of trades, you have to make money, in any market, under any circumstances"

#### Why Markets Are Less Trending Now

- More restrictive trading style not approach Marcus eventually adopted
- Enjoyed the game too much
- Knew should only be in optimum trades, but trading was release and hobby
- Replaced lot of other things in life
- Placed fun of action ahead of own criteria
- Thing that saved him: **when trade met all criteria, would enter 5-6x the position size** doing on other trades
- All profits came from trades that met criteria
- Other trades broke even and kept him amused

#### Market Sophistication

- Fewer optimum trades because **marketplace gotten more sophisticated**
- Many more professional traders than in early days
- In early years, had edge just knowing angles Seykota and Hostetter taught
- Now everybody knows those principles
- Trading rooms filled with bright people and computers

##### The Lag Effect

- In those days: watched board, bought corn when moved above key chart point
- Hour later grain elevator operator would get call from broker and might buy
- Next day brokerage house would recommend trade, pushing market up more
- Third day would get short covering from people wrong, then fresh buying from "dentists of the world" who finally got word it was right time to buy
- At that time, Marcus was **one of first ones to buy** because one of few professional traders playing game
- Would wind up selling out to dentists several days later

##### The Instant Reaction

- Dentists not going to keep positions, buying at wrong time
- When market would fall back, Marcus would go back in
- Nowadays, moment market breaks key chart point, **perceived by whole universe of traders**
- Grain elevator operator has already bet
- Dentists don't count because trading participation infinitesimal
- Even if dentists still there, trading one-lots — meaningless position when fund managers trading thousand at a clip
- "Now you almost have to be contrary. You have to ask, 'Isn't it true that all my fellow professional traders are already in, so who is left to buy?'"
- Before didn't have to worry — always somebody left to buy (people getting information or reacting slower)
- Now everybody just as decisive, just as fast

### False Breakouts and Central Bank Intervention

- **Markets more prone to false breakouts now** — much more
- **Trend-following systems doomed to mediocrity** — believes so
- Era of trend following over until and unless particular imbalance in market overrides everything else
  - Example: 1988 drought in grain belt (developed shortly after interview)
  - Another exception: major inflationary or deflationary environment

#### Professional Money Managers Changed Markets

- Proof: **Richard Dennis** done well for many years, lost over 50% on funds managing in 1988
- Trend-following systems approach doesn't work anymore
- Problem: once defined trend and taken position, everyone else has taken position as well
- Since no one left to buy, market swings around other direction and gets you out

#### Central Banks Preventing Currency Trends

- Another reason don't have many good trends: **central banks preventing currency moves from getting out of hand** by taking other side of trend
- In recent years, if look at chart of Treasury debt held by foreign central banks, risen astronomically
- Foreign banks taking over from private foreign investors in financing trade debts

### Marcus's Currency Trading

- At one time traded heavily in currencies
- Years after Reagan first elected, dollar very strong
- Would take positions as large as **600 million Deutsche marks** between own account and company account
- At the time, about **$300 million worth** — "pretty good line"
- Probably one of bigger currency traders in world, including banks

#### The 24-Hour Market Problem

- Very exhausting because **twenty-four-hour market**
- When went to sleep, would have to wake up almost every two hours to check markets
- Would tune in every major center as opened: Australia, Hong Kong, Zurich, London
- "It killed my marriage"
- Nowadays tries to avoid currencies — "totally political situation"
- Have to determine what central banks going to do

#### Getting Caught on Wrong Side

- When trading currencies actively, getting up through night because worried about getting caught on wrong side of major move before markets opened in U.S.
- Happened enough times to make him leery

#### There Would Be Big Gap Moves Overseas

- For example, late 1978, dollar getting battered, falling to new lows every day
- Period when cooperating and trading as colleague with **Bruce Kovner**
- Used to talk hours every day
- One day noticed dollar got mysteriously strong — intense price movement couldn't be explained by known information
- Just bailed out of long currency positions like crazy
- That weekend, **President Carter announced dollar support program**
- If had waited until next U.S. trading session, would have been annihilated

#### The Principle of Big Players Tipping Their Hand

- Situation illustrates principle believed in: **big players, including governments, always tip their hand**
- If saw surprise price move against them that didn't understand, often got out and looked for reason later

> "I remember that market well. The currency futures markets were locked limit-down for several days in a row after that announcement. You must have gotten out right near the top of that market."

- Made great exit on that trade
- Point: believes as courtesy, **European central banks notified about major changes going to make**, they often act ahead of U.S. policy announcements
- Consequently, price move shows up in Europe first, even if because of something U.S. initiates
- If action initiated by Europeans, price move certainly going to occur there first
- "I think the best hours to trade are often in Europe. If I had a period in which I was going to devote my life to trading, I would want to live in Europe"

### Joining Commodities Corporation

- Got call from **Amos Hostetter**, who befriended at Shearson
- At time, also trading some money for **Commodities Corporation**
- Amos told Marcus would be well advised to consider joining Commodities Corporation as trader
- At time, their theory: going to hire all these great **econometricians** to be traders
- Had people like **Paul Samuelson** on board
- Brought up idea of hiring Marcus at meeting
- First question: "What articles has he written; in what journals has he been published?"
- Had B.A. in **liberal arts** and that was it
- Punch line: "He just trades." Everyone thought very funny

#### But Weren't They in Business to Make Money Trading?

- Didn't think possible to really make money unless had Ph.D.
- Amos convinced them to give Marcus a chance
- Believes was **first non-Ph.D. trader** they ever hired
- Started him out with **$30,000 in August 1974**
- After about ten years, had turned that account into **$80 million**
- "Those were some very good years"

#### Company Fee Structure

- After first few years, gave another $100,000 to trade
- After that, always taking money out
- In those years, in expansionary phase
- **Taxed traders 30% a year** to pay for expenses
- Had to make 30% a year just to keep account level
- "Must have had some incredible return years, given the growth of your account—particularly under that handicap"
- Making at least **100% a year for years and years**

#### Best Year — 1979 Gold Trade

- Best year must have been **1979** — "incredible year"
- **Caught gold when went up to over $800**
- In and out, but caught big chunks — **$100 per ounce at a time**
- Wild time
- In those days would buy gold in **Australia**, **Hong Kong** would push it up $10 higher, would go up another $10 in **London**, by time **New York** opened able to sell out at **$30 profit**

##### Enormous Advantage Buying Gold Overseas

- Had advantage by being in **California** — up trading in Hong Kong when New York colleagues asleep
- Heard about **invasion of Afghanistan** on television news
- Called Hong Kong to see if anybody knew about it — nobody seemed to; price wasn't changing
- Able to buy **200,000 ounces of gold** before anybody knew what was happening
- **2,000 contracts** — any liquidity problems taking on that size position in Hong Kong?
- No, they gave the stuff, but got fried doing it
- Told on last visit to Hong Kong shouldn't visit gold floor
- Some people still remember that episode
- They knew who was on other side of trade
- They probably thought Marcus was just crazy coming in and buying all that gold
- When news broke five to ten minutes later, everybody started scrambling
- Had immediate **$10 per ounce profit on 200,000 ounces**

> "It's hard to believe you could trade off the television news."

- Had never done before — "first, last, and only time, but I did do it"

#### Getting Out of Gold

- That particular gold market ended in **near-vertical rise and fall**
- Got out around **$750 on way up**
- Felt sick when saw gold go up to nearly $900
- But later when back down to $400, felt much better about it

##### Rule: Get Out When Volatility Becomes Insane

- At that time, had many wild markets
- One of rules: **get out when volatility and momentum become absolutely insane**
- One way of measuring: **limit days**
- In those days, used to have lot of situations when market would go **limit-up for number of consecutive days**
- On **third straight limit-up day**, would begin to be very, very cautious
- Would almost always get out on **fourth limit-up day**
- If somehow survived with any part of position that long, had mandate to get out on **fifth limit-up day**
- "Just forced myself out of the market on that kind of volatility"

### Luck vs. Skill in the 1970s

- Transition from being losing trader to very successful coincided with big bull phase in commodity markets during early to mid-1970s
- How much of early success due to skills as trader vs. just the markets?
- Honestly thinks **markets were so good**, by buying and holding just couldn't lose
- Lot of other success stories — fortunes being made

#### But Lot of Those People Didn't Keep Fortunes

- True, but Marcus very fortunate
- By time markets got difficult again, was good trader
- By then, had really learned craft

#### Specializing in Cocoa

- By that time, had advantage of having become **very knowledgeable in one market: cocoa**
- For almost two years, traded almost nothing but cocoa
- Because of information and help got from **Helmut Weymar** (founder of Commodities Corporation)
- **Helmut incredible expert on cocoa**
- Wrote book so deep Marcus couldn't understand cover
- Also had all kinds of friends in business
- With knowledge and information got from Helmut and his friends, "felt that I knew the universe of cocoa in a way that I had never"


<!-- pp. 51-70 -->

## Michael Marcus Interview (continued)

### The End of Cocoa Trading
- Marcus's cocoa trading phase ended when **Helmut** retired from cocoa trading
- Marcus traded significantly better on Helmut's information than Helmut did himself

### Traumatic Trades and Risk Management

#### The Deutsche Mark Disaster
- During heavy currency trading period, Marcus held large position in **Deutsche marks**
- **Bundesbank** intervened to punish speculators
- Marcus was down $2.5 million in five minutes
- Got out rather than let it become $10 million loss
- Market recovered entire fall within half an hour

> "Yes, but it still hurt to realize that if I had sat it out and done nothing, I would have been OK instead of losing $2½ million."

### Poor Investment Decisions
- Made multiple bad investments, losing a large chunk of trading profits
- Owned about ten houses, lost money on all of them (some sold before spending a single night)
- Had a plane charter service that lost money
- Calculated 30% of trading income went to taxes, 30% to support planes, 20% to real estate
- Lost more than half the money he made trading

> "Out of a fairly large number of real estate transactions—many in California—I lost money on all but one of them. I am probably the only person alive that can claim that dubious distinction."

- Investment failures were emotional decisions without analysis
- Pattern: repeating early trading mistake of getting involved in things he knew nothing about

### Key Advice for Beginning Traders

#### Position Sizing
- **Never bet more than 5 percent of money on any one idea**
- Can be wrong more than twenty times before losing all money
- 5 percent applies to ONE IDEA (e.g., long positions in two related grain markets = one idea)

#### Always Use Stops
- Actually put stops in—commits you to getting out at a certain point
- Have exit point determined BEFORE entering position

#### Mental Flexibility
- If position doesn't feel right soon after entry, change your mind and get out immediately
- Don't worry about broker thinking you're an idiot
- When in doubt, get out and get a good night's sleep
- Often go back in next day after thinking clearly

> "If you become unsure about a position, and you don't know what to do, just get out. You can always come back in."

#### Hold Winners, Cut Losers
- Most important rule: **hold on to winners and cut losers**
- Both equally important
- If you don't stay with winners, you won't have profits to pay for losers

#### Follow Your Own Light
- Don't try to trade someone else's way or on their ideas—will lose
- Every trader has strengths and weaknesses
- Stick to your own style—incorporating someone else's approach often yields worst of both styles
- Need confidence to hold position and take risk
- If in a trade only because someone else is in it, won't have courage to stick with it

### Market Psychology and Sentiment

#### Evaluating Market Discounting
- Markets are sophisticated—always ask: "How many people are left to act on this idea?"
- Consider whether market has already discounted your idea
- Use **momentum indicators** and observe **market tone**
- How many days has market been up/down in a row?
- What are **sentiment indexes** showing?

#### Classic Example: Late 1970s Soybean Bull Market
- Extreme soybean shortage developing
- Weekly government reports showed strong **export commitments and sales**
- Marcus held heavy long position in soybeans
- Contact from **Commodities Corporation** called with export figures: "Good news and bad news"
- Good news: export commitment figure was fantastic
- Bad news: "You don't have a **limit position**" (maximum permissible speculative position size)
- Market expected to limit-up for next three days

Marcus actually felt depressed not having a larger position, so bought more contracts on opening. Market opened limit-up as expected, then ticks showed trading at limit-up, then prices eased off limit-up as broker called to report fills. Market started trading down.

> "Soybeans were supposed to be limit-up for three days, and they can't even hold limit-up the first morning."

- Marcus frantically sold everything
- Accidentally ended up short substantial soybeans, which he bought back 40-50 cents lower
- **Only time he made a lot of money on an error**

#### Cotton Bull Market Example
- Cotton approaching $1/pound
- Export figure showed half million bales exports to China—most bullish figure ever seen
- Expected opening limit-up next day
- Market opened only 150 points higher, then traded off
- **Proved to be the exact high**

#### Inflationary Period Example
- Very inflationary period, commodity markets trading in lockstep fashion
- On particularly powerful day, almost all markets went limit-up
- Cotton opened limit-up, fell back, finished marginally higher for day
- That was the market peak
- Everything else stayed locked limit-up, but cotton never saw light of day again

**Implied rule**: If you find common behavior between markets, sell the one lagging as soon as it starts heading down. When news is wonderful and market can't go up, be sure to be short.

### Common Misconceptions

#### Relying on Experts
- Leading cause of financial disablement: believing you can rely on experts
- Exception: if you know the right expert (e.g., **Paul Tudor Jones's** barber talking about markets might be worth listening to)
- Typically, "experts" are not traders
- Average broker couldn't be a trader in a million years
- More money lost listening to brokers than any other way
- Trading requires intense personal involvement and doing your own homework

#### Conspiracy Theories
- Foolish belief that there is conspiracy in markets
- Marcus has known many great traders worldwide
- 99% of the time, market is bigger than anybody
- Market goes where it wants to go eventually
- Exceptions don't last too long

### Teaching Trading: Bruce Kovner

#### Marcus's Best Student
- **Bruce Kovner** became best trader Marcus ever worked with and close friend
- When Marcus first met Bruce, he was writer and professor doing some trading in spare time
- Marcus was staggered by breadth of trading knowledge Bruce had accumulated in short time
- First day meeting Bruce, Marcus tried to impress him with complicated concepts
- Bruce was professional trader spending fifteen hours a day analyzing markets
- Bruce could understand everything Marcus couldn't

#### What Made Kovner Special
- **Objectivity**—a good trader can't be rigid
- Open to seeing anything
- Marcus saw Bruce would be great trader from first meeting

#### Collaboration Success
- Marcus conveyed principles **Ed Seykota** and **Amos Hostetter** taught him, plus acquired skills
- Best trading occurred when Bruce and Marcus were collaborating—phenomenal results
- Years when Marcus was up 300%, Bruce was up 1,000%
- Bruce had very great gift

### Marcus's Personal Philosophy

#### Gut Feel and Courage
- **Gut feel is very important**
- Don't know any great professional trader without it
- Successful trading requires multiple types of courage:
  - Courage to try
  - Courage to fail
  - Courage to succeed
  - Courage to keep going when going gets tough

#### Current Life Balance
- Around 1983, began tapering off trading to recharge batteries
- Taken **karate** for many years, already at high level, wants black belt
- Studied **spiritual traditions**, wants to do more work with that
- Question Marcus finds important (per **Albert Einstein**): whether the universe is friendly
- Important for everybody to reach point where they feel inside that universe is friendly
- Marcus started feeling universe was unfriendly place
- Now much closer to feeling it's friendly

#### Long-Term Trading Plans
- Too much fun to give up
- Doesn't want to make a lot more money (would probably lose it in real estate again)
- If trading thirteen hours a day: torturous kind of excitement
- If keeping life in balance: fun
- All successful traders who lasted eventually got to that point—balanced life with fun outside trading
- Without other focus, wind up overtrading or getting excessively disturbed about temporary failures

#### Handling Losing Streaks
- Past: sometimes tried fighting back by trading heavier after losses—usually doesn't work
- Then cuts down very fast, stopping completely if bad enough
- But usually never gets that bad
- Most of time would have been better off just stopping
- Trouble bringing himself to stop because natural fighter
- Typical pattern: Lose, fight like hell, lose again, then cut back or stop until on winning track

**Usual stopping period**: three to four weeks

#### Psychology of Losing
- Losing begets losing
- When start losing, touches off negative elements in psychology, leads to pessimism

### What Makes Marcus Different

#### Open-Mindedness
- Very **open-minded**
- Willing to take in information difficult to accept emotionally but still recognize as true
- Example: Seen others make money much faster than him, only to give everything back when started losing because couldn't stop
- When had bad losing streak, able to say: "You just can't trade anymore"
- When market moves counter to expectations, always able to say: "I had hoped to make a lot of money in this position, but it isn't working, so I'm getting out"

## Bruce Kovner Introduction

### Background and Scale
- May be **world's largest trader** in interbank currency and futures markets
- 1987 alone: scored profits exceeding **$300 million** for himself and fund investors
- Past ten years: remarkable **87% average annual compounded return**
- $2,000 invested with Kovner in early 1978 would be worth over $1,000,000 ten years later

### Low Profile
- Despite incredible track record and huge trading size, kept surprisingly low profile
- Assiduously pursued privacy by refusing all interview requests
- Agreed to interview reflecting vote of confidence and trust
- Seven years earlier, paths crossed briefly when both worked at **Commodities Corporation**—Kovner as principal trader, interviewer as analyst

### Academic Background
- Hardly fits intuitive image of billion-dollar trader
- Incisive intellect and easygoing manner—reminds one more of professor than giant-scale currency/futures trader
- Indeed, started as academic
- After graduating from **Harvard**, taught political science courses at Harvard and **University of Pennsylvania**
- Didn't enjoy always confronting blank page in morning thinking of something brilliant to write

### Career Shift to Trading
- Early 1970s: managed political campaigns with idea of eventually running for office himself
- Abandoned politics—didn't have financial resources or desire to work up political ladder from committee jobs
- During this time, also worked as consultant for various state and federal agencies

### Discovery of Trading
- Mid-1970s: shifted attention to financial markets
- Believed economics and political science education provided right background
- Found idea of analyzing world to make trading judgments tremendously appealing
- For about a year, immersed himself in studying markets and related economic theory
- Read everything he could get hands on

### Interest Rate Theory and Early Trades
- Studied **interest rate theory** intensively
- Fell in love with **yield curve** (relationship between yield on government securities and time to maturity)
- Example: if each successively longer-term maturity provided higher yield (five-year T-notes higher yield than one-year T-bills), yield curve would reflect continually rising slope on graph

#### Discovery of Market Inefficiencies
- Kovner's study of interest rate markets coincided with initial years of trading in **interest rate futures**
- Market relatively unsophisticated, price distortions persisted over time
- As Kovner explains: "The market hadn't become important enough for CitiBank or Solomon Brothers, but it was important enough for me"

#### Spread Trading Discovery
- Primary anomaly: price spread (difference) between different futures contracts
- **Futures traded for specific months** (March, June, September, December)
- Interest rate theory predicted nearby contract (e.g., March) should trade at higher price (lower yield) than next contract (e.g., June)
- Nearest two contracts did reflect this relationship
- But Kovner found price difference between more forward contracts often started trading at near-zero levels

#### First Successful Trade
- First trade: bought forward interest rate contract and sold more forward contract
- Expectation: as purchased contract became nearby contract with passage of time, price spread between two contracts would widen
- Trade worked according to textbook theory, Kovner was hooked as trader

#### Second Trade: Intra-Market Spread
- Second trade also involved **intra-market spread** (purchase of one contract against sale of another in same market)
- Bought nearby copper contract, sold more forward contract
- Expectation: supply tightness would cause nearby copper contract to gain relative to forward position
- Idea eventually proved right, but too early
- Lost money on trade
- End of these two trades: Kovner still ahead, original $3,000 stake grown to about $4,000


<!-- pp. 71-90 -->

## Bruce Kovner (continued)

### Market Intelligence and Information Asymmetry

- **Soviet Union as informed trader**: Soviets are considered good traders in currencies and grains, operating through commercial banks and dealers
- Information advantage stems from intelligence capabilities—the Soviets can eavesdrop on commercial communications, giving them advance notice of market-moving information
- Large commodity trading firms sometimes use scramblers for sensitive calls
- Markets often move before news reaches typical traders—"the one thing that does hit the market is a huge sale or purchase"

### Technical Analysis Philosophy

- Technical analysis has validity but also contains "a great deal that is mumbo jumbo"
- **Technical analysis as thermometer**: Like a doctor taking a patient's temperature, ignoring charts would be foolish for any serious market participant
- Charts reflect the vote of the entire marketplace and pick up unusual behavior
- **New chart patterns signal unusual events**: By definition, anything creating a new pattern represents something unusual worth investigating
- Will trade purely on technical breakouts without fundamental reasons if the pattern suggests informed traders are acting
- Breakouts from tight consolidations with no clear explanation are often the best risk/reward trades

### Handling False Breakouts

- **Heisenberg principle applied to markets**: If something is closely observed, odds are it's already priced in
- News-driven breakouts (e.g., *Wall Street Journal* story) are less reliable than unexplained moves
- The more a price pattern is watched by speculators, the more prone to false signals
- The more a market is driven by non-speculative activity, the more significant technical breakouts become

### Computerized Trading Systems

- **Trend-following systems create false signals**: Billions of dollars in technical systems using moving averages produce many false breakouts
- Kovner developed similar systems to anticipate when other systems will trigger
- A breakout caused by computerized buying is less interesting than one caused by informed players (e.g., "the Russians")

### Stop Loss Discipline

- **Predetermined stops are mandatory**: "That is the only way I can sleep"
- Knows exit point before entering any trade
- Position size determined by stop distance
- Stops placed beyond technical barriers to avoid being easily taken out
- Mid-range stops avoided since the market shouldn't go there if the trade is right

> "I never think about that, because the point about a technical barrier—and I've studied the technical aspects of the market for a long time—is that the market shouldn't go there if you are right."

### Risk Management After Losses

- Losses slow him down, leading to reduced position sizes
- Changes in technical picture provide "second thoughts"—if a major intermediate high is penetrated while bearish on the dollar, he would reevaluate
- First response to being wrong: reduce positions, then reassess

### Trend-Following Systems Limitations

- Uses own trend-following systems for about 5 percent of managed money
- Systems make money overall but have volatility and risk control problems he dislikes
- Used for diversification from other trading

### Expert Systems for Trading

- **Unlikely to match human traders**: Learning features would need to be highly developed
- Computers excel at "learning" only with clear hierarchies of information (e.g., medical diagnostics)
- **Trading rules constantly change**: "The rules of the trading and investment game keep changing"
- Worked with expert system developers who concluded trading is a poor candidate—too many types of knowledge, rules for interpreting information keep shifting

### Scale and Liquidity Challenges

- Managing over $650 million (last year's profits alone: ~$300 million)
- Fewer markets with sufficient liquidity for optimum trade size
- **Copper example**: Likes copper but is now "the elephant"—can comfortably move 500-800 contracts/day, uncomfortably beyond that
- Daily copper volume: only 7,000-10,000 contracts (much is local trading/spreads)
- Contrast: T-bond market can handle 5,000 contracts; interbank currency market has enormous liquidity
- Coffee trade made "a few million dollars" last year—but at $600 million AUM, $2 million profit doesn't matter much and diverts focus from primary currency markets

### Managing Client Money vs. Personal Capital

- Substantial personal funds invested in own funds
- Portion of funds that is managed money represents a **call**: unlimited profit potential on upside, risk limited to cost (reputation) on downside
- Not flippant—reputation among investors extremely important
- A call is "a much better position than a symmetrical win/lose position"

### Practical Limits on Fund Size

- **Most commodity futures markets have capacity limits**
- Currencies, interest rates, and a few commodities like crude oil have very high limits
- Plans to carefully manage future growth in fund size

### Market Impact and Manipulation Attempts

- Never bullies a market
- **Manipulation rarely works**: Can succeed short-term but eventually leads to arrogance, loss of touch with market structure (both fundamental and technical)
- Example: British trading organization tried to corner crude oil market—succeeded initially, then lost control and crude fell $4
- Result: Lost ~$40 million, organization in trouble
- Traders who overestimate their ability and try to bully markets ultimately make the mistake of overtrading

### Emotional Management

- **Depersonalize losses**: "If you personalize these losses, you can't trade"
- Could lose millions on any given day
- Only disturbance: poor money management (taking significantly too large a loss)
- **July/November soybean spread lesson**: Lifting the short side scared him, taught him about risk control
- As day-in, day-out process, taking losses doesn't bother him

### 1981 Loss Year

- Lost about 16 percent
- Combination of errors and market nature: first major bear market in commodities
- **Bear markets have different characteristics**: Very sharp down movements followed by quick retracements
- Problem: Would sell too late, then get stopped out in what proved to be wide-swinging congestion pattern
- Poor money management: too many correlated trades

### Post-1981 Risk Management Overhaul

- Designed risk management systems
- Pays strict attention to correlations of all positions
- **Measures total portfolio risk daily**

### Currency Trading: Interbank vs. Futures

- Only uses interbank market unless doing arbitrage against the **IMM** (International Monetary Market—Chicago Mercantile Exchange subsidiary, world's foremost currency futures exchange)
- Liquidity enormously better in interbank market
- Transaction costs much lower
- **24-hour market**—critical because they literally trade 24 hours/day

### Currency Trading Scope

- 50-60% of profits from currency trading on average
- Trades any highly liquid currency: all European currencies (including Scandinavian), all major Asian currencies, Mideast currencies
- **Crosses** are the most important trading vehicle outside the IMM (e.g., buying British pounds/selling Deutsche marks)
- Can't trade crosses on IMM due to fixed contract sizes
- Interbank market more exact and direct for crosses (e.g., Deutsche mark/British pound, Deutsche mark/Japanese yen)

### Interbank vs. Futures Arbitrage

- Two markets well arbitraged but swift arbitrageurs can profit when they get out of line
- Interbank market response to surprise news/statistics less extreme than futures
- Futures market: locals back away, let stops run; only arbitrageurs pull markets back

### Bank Market Activity

- Fed study shows it's basically a hedging market
- Banks are principal speculators, plus a few players like Kovner

### Futures Market Inefficiency for Currency Hedging

- **Hedging requires specific dollar amounts and dates**—futures trade only specific dates and fixed contract sizes, so hedger not precisely covered
- Interbank market can tailor hedge for any customer (e.g., $3.6 million for April 12)
- Activity takes place within normal commercial banking relations—hedgers often want to show banking interest for locked-in profit to borrow against

### Fundamental Analysis Methodology

- **Current price is always correct**: Tries to figure out what changes will alter future prices
- **Mental scenario building**: Imagines many alternative pictures of the world, waits for one to be confirmed
- Tries scenarios "one at a time"—most will be wrong (only a few elements correct)
- Then "all of a sudden, you will find that in one picture, nine out of ten elements click"—that scenario becomes the world reality image

### Post-October 1987 Crash Analysis Example

- Friday after October 19 crash: Had unusual trouble sleeping (very unusual for him)
- Struggled all week with how events would impact the dollar
- **Scenario testing**: Tried different visions of the world
- One picture: total panic—the world ending financially
  - In this scenario, dollar becomes safest political haven → tremendous dollar rise
  - Tuesday of that week: dollar did rise dramatically as people withdrew money from other places
  - Next three days: tremendous confusion, dollar started giving ground again

### The Plaza Accord Realization

- Late Friday realization: Combination of need for stimulative action (dictated by worldwide financial panic), reluctance of Bank of Japan and German Bundesbank to adopt inflationary measures, continuing wide U.S. trade deficits → only solution was for Treasury Secretary Baker to let dollar fall
- Someone had to play stimulative role, and that would be the United States
- **Dollar would drop and other central banks wouldn't defend it**
- Absolutely convinced this was the only thing Baker could do

### Weekend Trading Decision

- Realized this late Friday—too late for immediate market action
- Very tense weekend waiting for Far East markets to open Sunday night

### 24-Hour Trading Operation

- Monitors everywhere: home, country home
- Literally on duty 24 hours/day

### Alert System for Staff

- **Call levels set for every currency**: If currency breaks out of predetermined range, staff calls immediately
- Assistant trader allowed to wake him at home twice a year—"but it really isn't necessary very often"
- When markets busy, knows what's happening all the time
- Home fully equipped with trading monitors and direct lines
- Assistant's job: be up and get the calls (probably called 3-4 times/night)

### Scenario Planning Protocol

- Create scenario for every currency at least once/week
- Define expected ranges for each currency and predetermined actions if ranges broken

### Delegated Decision Making

- Assistant knows buy/sell decisions beforehand for range breakouts
- Must call if Prime Minister resigns, major unexpected currency revaluation, or other events invalidating scenario

### Trading Schedule and Work-Life Balance

- Ends up trading at night frequently
- Generally tries to confine trading between 8 AM and 6-7 PM
- Far East very important—if currency markets very active, will trade Far East (opens 8 PM)
- Tokyo AM session: trades until 12 PM
- If tremendous market movement, will sleep a couple hours then catch next market opening

### The Global Trading Experience

> "Absolutely. When you are really involved, the screen almost reaches out and grabs you. The way the quotes are made changes: They get wider; they get wilder. I have contacts all over the world in each of these markets and I know what is going on. It is a tremendously exciting game."

- Opportunities all the time
- **Market analysis as intellectual pleasure**: "For me, market analysis is like a tremendous multidimensional chess board. The pleasure of it is purely intellectual."
- Example: figuring out New Zealand finance minister's problems—how he'll cope with Australia, U.S., labor unions
- Job: "do the puzzle with him and figure out what he is going to decide, and what the consequences of his actions will be that he or the market doesn't anticipate"

### Information Sources

- Gets "guru report" daily
- Newsletter writers with large followings: **Prechter, Zweig, Davis, Eliades**, and others

### Contrary Opinion Usage

- Tries not to be "too much of a wise guy"
- During major price moves, gurus will be right for portion of it
- Looking for consensus that market is not confirming
- **Wants to know many people will be wrong**—likes seeing lots of people about to be on wrong side

### Risk Control: Position Sizing

- **Tries very hard not to risk more than 1% of portfolio on any single trade**
- Studies correlation of trades to reduce exposure
- **Daily computer analysis of position correlations**
- Through bitter experience: mistakes in position correlation = root of most serious trading problems
- **Eight highly correlated positions = one position eight times as large**

### Cross-Currency Position Management

- If bullish both Deutsche mark and Swiss franc, decides which one preferred and places entire long position in that currency
- Even more important: **trading long in one market against short in related market** (e.g., long yen/short Deutsche mark)
- "In all my trading, if I am long something, I like to be short something else"

### Cross Rates vs. Individual Currencies

- Cross rates move slower than individual currencies? **Not necessarily**
- **Sterling/mark cross rate example**: Yearlong congestion between 2.96-3.00, broke out about a month ago
- Day it broke out: challenged top of range ~20 times
- Bank of England kept defending it
- Bank of England finally gave in—cross rate pierced 3.01, then no trades until 3.0350
- Moved virtually a full 1 percent without trading

### Unusual Interbank Market Behavior

- Very unusual—meant everybody watching the 3.00 level
- Once everyone realized Bank of England not stepping in, no one wanted to be seller

### Violent Quick Breakouts

- **Much more reliable than typical breakouts**
- Worse the fills, better the trade
- After trading couple hours between 3.04-3.02, rate went straight to 3.11

### Cross Rates as Better Trading Opportunities

- **Far fewer people pay attention to cross rates**
- General rule: **The less observed, the better the trade**

### Fundamentals vs. Technical Analysis Priority

- Like asking a doctor whether he'd prefer diagnostics or patient chart monitoring condition—**need both**
- **Fundamentals more important now** (vs. 1970s when easier to make money using technical analysis alone)
- 1970s: Far fewer false breakouts
- Now: Everyone is a chartist, huge number of technical trading systems
- That change made it much harder for technical traders

### Trend-Following Systems: Self-Destruction Risk

- **Will eventually self-destruct under weight of size and similar approaches**
- Only thing that will save technical systems: **period of high inflation** when simple trend-following methodologies work again
- With stable, moderate inflation rates, technical trading systems will kill each other off

### Stock Market vs. Other Markets

- **Stock market has far more short-term countertrends**
- After going up, always wants to come down
- Commodity markets driven by supply/demand for physical goods—if true shortage, prices tend to keep trending higher

### Stock Index Technical Approaches

- Technical approaches can work but keep changing
- Very long-term decision-making systems catch bigger stock market advances, but need very wide stops

### Filtering Out Noise

- **Must be very long term**—much longer than most traders can handle (strategy involves riding out large retracements)
- Alternative approach: Trader he knows does well in stock index markets by trying to figure out how stock market can hurt most traders (seems to work)

### October 1987 Crash Causes

- Two elements: (1) Overly high prices left stock market vulnerable to decline (triggered by rising interest rates and other fundamental causes); (2) Decline accentuated by heavy selling from pension funds involved in **portfolio insurance**

### Portfolio Insurance vs. Program Trading

- Portfolio insurance: systematically selling stock index futures as stock prices decline (covering shorts when prices rise) to reduce portfolio risk
- Program trading: buying/selling stock index futures against opposite position in basket of stocks when prices are out of line
- Only way arbitrage contributed: if not for program trading arbitrage, portfolio insurance might never have been developed

### Arbitrageurs' Culpability

- Only to blame insofar as they made portfolio insurance possible
- **Portfolio insurance was terrible idea**: insurance in name only, nothing more than massive stop-loss order
- Without portfolio insurance selling, market would still have gone down sharply but not like the 500-point decline witnessed

### Trading Success: Talent vs. Hard Work

- Great traders have special talent (by definition, only small group can be superior traders since trading is zero-sum game)
- **Hard work absolutely necessary**: "If you don't work very hard, it is extremely unlikely that you will be a good trader"

### One-Year Wonders

- Can coast on innate skills for a while
- Common to find traders with strong feeling for specific market (e.g., sugar to 40 cents, copper spreads widening dramatically) that turns out right
- Example: Trader made $27 million trading copper spreads last year, then lost virtually all of it

### Advice for Novice Traders

1. **Risk management most important thing** to understand
2. **Undertrade, undertrade, undertrade**—second piece of advice
3. **Cut position at least in half**: "Whatever you think your position ought to be, cut it at least in half"
4. Novice traders trade 3-5 times too big
5. Taking 5-10% risks on a trade when should be taking 1-2% risks

### Common Novice Mistakes Beyond Overtrading

- **Personalizing the market**: Thinking of market as personal nemesis
- Market totally impersonal—doesn't care whether you make money or not
- Saying "I wish" or "I hope" = engaging in destructive thinking that takes attention from diagnostic process

### Summary: Key Trading Principles

**Risk Management is Paramount**
- Always decides on exit point before entry
- Evaluates risk on portfolio basis, not individual trades
- Critical when holding highly correlated positions (overall portfolio risk much greater than realized)

**Stop Placement Strategy**
- Places stop where it's too far away or too difficult for floor traders to reach easily
- Maximizes chances of not being stopped out of correct trade while maintaining rigid money management
- Philosophy: Allocate predetermined maximum dollar risk to smaller number of contracts with wider stop
- Reverse of typical trader (limiting loss per contract but trading many contracts)
- Usual approach results in many good trades stopped out before market moves in anticipated direction

**Moral: Place stops where they'll reasonably indicate trade is wrong, not at point determined by maximum dollar amount willing to lose per contract. If meaningful stop implies uncomfortably large loss per contract, trade smaller number of contracts.**

**Avoid Impulsive Trades**
- Worst mistake: "going bust trade" (spur of moment decision)
- Regardless of approach, stick to game plan
- Avoid unplanned trades (e.g., friend recommendation, liquidating before predetermined stop due to adverse price movement)

**Traits of Winning Trader**
- **Strong, independent, and contrary in the extreme**
- Discipline and willingness to make (and accept) mistakes = significant traits

<!-- pp. 91-110 -->

### Interview Context & Conclusion

- **Richard Dennis** interview ran over time—interviewer thought they'd continue beyond the allotted hour, but Dennis had only 10 minutes left
- Interviewer skipped political questions (Senate hearings on soybean manipulation, Roosevelt Institute connections) as not pertinent to book's trading focus
- Six weeks later, second interview covered **budget deficit crisis** and Dennis's public fund losses at that time
- Month after final conversation, Dennis announced **retirement from trading** to focus on political interests full-time
- Author speculates: "Will Dennis never trade again? Maybe, but don't bet on it."

### Early Trading Career

#### First Steps (1968-1969)

- After high school, got summer job as **runner on the exchange floor**
- Making $40/week, losing $40/hour trading—"tuition was small for what I learned"
- **1968-1969**: father had exchange membership but didn't know much about trading; Dennis (under 21) signaled trades from sidelines while father stood in ring
- Father's reaction at age 21: "I really hate this. I have no idea what I'm doing. It's yours!"

#### Disadvantaged Start

- Trading one step removed (father filling orders) meant consistently losing
- Lost "a couple of thousand dollars during that period"
- Dennis's counterintuitive take: **"When you start, you ought to be as bad a trader as you are ever going to be"**—cheaper to fail early
- "You shouldn't be too surprised if you really screw up"

#### Early Success Psychology

- **Traders who get imprinted early** (like ducks with a warship as mother): First big profit on long or short side creates **perennial bulls or bears**—"that is very bad"
- Both sides must be "equally OK"—no psychological preference
- **1973 soybean bull market** example: Even traders who didn't profit got "imprinted" by witnessing the mania

### First Big Success (1970)

#### Mid America Exchange Advantage

- Started trading **minicontracts** on Mid America Exchange—"a few mistakes in me, and I made most, but not all of them"
- No real confidence, just "a need to try to succeed"
- Did enough things right to avoid capsizing small capitalization
- **Corn blight of 1970**: Staggered into having right positions before the move

#### Trend-Following Breakthrough

- Friday close: grain markets at **yearly highs**
- Applied rule: "Go with the trend, and the stronger the trend, the better"
- Bought minicontracts in corn, wheat, beans on the close
- Monday: markets **opened limit-up** due to corn blight news
- Grew account from $400 to **$2,000**—"a real grubstake"
- Key lesson: "I did something that should work in the long run—I went with the trend"

#### Market Pattern Discovery

- **Strong Friday close** = don't be short if market closes at high, or long if closes at low
- "At a minimum, it is important not to have a short position with a loss on Friday if the market closes at a high, or a long position if it closes at a low"

### Graduate School Decision

- Signed up for grad school **before summer 1970** (when he first traded in the pit)
- Made **$3,000 in three months**—big impression
- Went to **Tulane in New Orleans**, lasted one week
- Used laundromat quarters to phone trades into Chicago
- "Once I used up all the quarters and had nothing but dirty clothes; I had no choice but to come back to Chicago"
- Full-time commodity trader since then

### Most Dramatic Trading Experience

#### The $1,000 Loss Day (early career)

- Just quit grad school to trade
- Made bad trade, lost **$300** (out of $3,000 total capital)—10% loss
- **Reversed position** → lost again
- **Reversed back** to original position → lost third time
- End of day: lost **$1,000 (one-third of entire capital)**

> "Since then, I have learned that when you have a destabilizing loss, get out, go home, take a nap, do something, but put a little time between that and your next decision. When you are getting beat to death, get your head out of the mixer."

- Lesson: **No trading rule about losses** at the time—if he had, wouldn't have had that traumatic experience

#### Best Trade in Disguise

- In retrospect, **one of his best trades** because:
  - Learned to avoid trying to catch up or double up to recoup losses
  - Realized loss affects judgment—must put time between loss and next trade
  - Corollary: **"When things aren't going right, don't push, don't press"**
- Can't afford to throw away capital on suboptimal trades—depletes resources when the right position comes along

### 1973 Soybean Market

- Made enough to go to **Chicago Board of Trade** the next year
- Not just trend-following—was **"basically a pit trader, who traded in and out a lot"**
- Markets excellent because of **order flow**—"great time to be in the pit"

#### Scalping Dynamics

- Many traders made terrible exits just to take profit, even when market locked limit-up and almost certain to go higher next day
- "They couldn't stand the profits burning a hole in their pocket"
- Dennis would buy when they were getting out—**high probability edge**

#### Limit-Up Streaks

- Markets went **limit-up ten days in a row**
- Most thought even four or five consecutive limit-ups were impossible
- Buying at limit bid = **"odds play"**—"a lot of volatility in the outcome, but you know the odds are in your favor"

### Bad Trading Years

- When having bad periods, **"it is really not one market that does it"**
- In those situations, almost all markets going sideways with lots of false breakouts
- "If one of the markets is decent, that is usually enough to avoid a bad situation"

#### 1978: Worst Year

- Not good for trading—**compounded losses unnecessarily**
- In process of transitioning from **floor trader to off-the-floor trader**—"had no idea how different they were"

### Transition to Off-Floor Trading (1977-1978)

#### Why the Switch?

- 1970: no futures markets in currencies, interest rates, or gold
- By 1978: these markets listed long enough to be viable (currencies started 1974, took years for volume)
- Motivation: **desire to trade more markets** than physically possible in single location

#### Lessons from 1978

- **Must be longer-term as desk trader**—in pit, could sell soybeans breaking 3 cents and get out quickly
- Off the floor: **lose the edge** when putting in orders
- Judgments from screen prices "aren't as good as those made in the pit watching what is going on"
- Pit has **subconscious indicators**: "these three guys are never right at market turns," and if they all do same thing, "a light clicks on"
- "It took me a long time to realize that those tools weren't going to be available anymore"

### Trader-Trainee Program ("The Turtles")

#### Origins (1984-1985)

- Hired groups beginning of 1984 and 1985
- **Philosophical argument** with partner (friend since high school):
  - Dennis: Successful trader skills can be **reduced to rules**
  - Partner: Something "ineffable, mystical, subjective, or intuitive" makes someone good
- Dennis: "Here is a way we can definitely resolve this argument. Let's hire and train some people and see what happens"

#### The Experiment

- **Intellectual experiment**—trained them as well as possible
- Codified everything Dennis knew about markets
- Taught: probability, money management, trading
- "It turned out I was right. I don't say that to pat myself on the back, but even I am surprised how well it worked. It's frightening how well it worked."

#### Selection & Screening

- **1,000 applications** → narrowed to 40 interviews → picked 10
- NOT "almost any reasonably intelligent individual"—screened carefully
- Won't disclose all criteria (mentioning **chess players** as example would cause resume flood)
- Intelligence was one trait but **not essential**—picked from intelligent or extremely intelligent; chose extreme intelligence "just because they were available"

#### Training Process

- **Shockingly short**: First year took two weeks, then traded one month keeping logs
- Second year course: **just one week**
- Wanted to see if consistent in doing what they'd been taught

#### Results

- **23 trainees total**
- Dropped 3 who didn't do well
- Other 20: **averaged about 100% profit per year**
- Started with **$100,000 each**
- Now average about **$2 million each** in trading capital

#### "Turtles" Name Origin

- Just returned from trip to **Far East**
- Told someone: "We are going to grow traders just like they grow turtles in Singapore"
- Had visited farm with huge vat of thousands of squirming turtles—became his image

#### Teaching Philosophy

- Told class repeatedly: **"We are going to teach you what we think works, but you are expected to add your own personal flair, feeling, or judgment"**
- Huge spread in results despite same training—personal application matters
- Trading results highly correlated? **No**—"There was a huge spread"

### On Trading Secrets

> "I don't think trading strategies are as vulnerable to not working if people know about them, as most traders believe. If what you are doing is right, it will work even if people have a general idea about it."

- Could publish trading rules in newspaper and no one would follow
- **Key is consistency and discipline**—"Almost anybody can make up a list of rules that are 80 percent as good as what we taught our people. What they couldn't do is give them the confidence to stick to those rules even when things are going bad."

### Role of Luck

- **Long run: zero**—"Absolutely zero. I don't think anybody winds up making money in this business because they started out lucky"
- **Individual trades**: "almost all luck"
- Matter of statistics: 53% chance trade works → over long run, 100% chance it works
- Takes **couple years minimum** to determine if one trader better than another

### Discretionary vs. Systems Trading

#### Professional Traders (Discretionary)

- May do intelligent things, but **don't think systematically** about what they're doing
- Example: Most traders who make successful trade don't ask:
  - Why did it work?
  - What did I do here that I might be able to do in another market, at another time?
- **Not a lot of reflection** on the trading process

#### Academic Types (Pure Systems)

- Research before ever trading
- Lack **"seat-of-the-pants knowledge"** necessary to develop good trading systems
- Dennis did trading first, so research "more applicable to the real world"

#### Real World Experience Example

- Mechanical system might place stops where Dennis knows "there will tend to be a lot of stops"
- In real world: **"not too wise to have your stop where everyone else has their stop"**
- That system will have **above-average skids** (slippage)
- Without understanding this, system "looks great on paper, but is going to do consistently poorer in the real world"

### Trading Process Analysis

- Before developing mechanical system: **wrote down observations** and thought about them
- "I thought about everything I was doing"
- Advises other traders: **keep track of what they're doing right and wrong**
- Natural tendency to avoid thinking about trading once day is over when things working
- When things go bad, traders shouldn't "stick their heads in the sand and just hope it gets better"
- Most tempting time to avoid thinking = **when you should be thinking the most**

### Systems vs. Intuition Balance

- When **feelings and systems absolutely opposed**: do nothing until can resolve conflict
- Most systems **trend-oriented**, so never right at market turns
- But Dennis may sense turn coming—would **liquidate faster** than trend-following system because of intuitive factor
- Weighs **psychological/opinion-oriented** segment about equal with technical/trend-following

### Countertrend Trades

- Has made countertrend initiations, but **"as a rule of thumb, I don't think you should do it"**
- Generally do more poorly, though occasionally give great story
- Example: **Short sugar at 60 cents** (November 1974 high of 66 cents → under 12 cents seven months later)
  - Each 1-cent move = $1,120 per contract
  - Large trader positions measured in thousands of contracts
- "I've got ten stories like that. But I have to tell you in all honesty, I don't think the broad class of trades I have done like that have been profitable"

### Sugar Trade Analysis

- Market had explosive upward move to 60 cents
- "But take the flip side when sugar is in a real bear market and is down to 5 cents; every trend-following system in the world is going to be short"
- If fundamentals in transition and price only slightly over cost of production: **make an exception?**
- **Dennis lost more money** in situations like that—"all the market has to do is go down one more cent and you are out of there"
- Made money shorting sugar at 60 cents, but lost much more going long sugar at 6 cents

### Limited Downside Trades

- When buying market because downside "limited," do you ride it out or throw in towel?
- **"You throw it in"**—"Because how do you know? Maybe it is going to 2 cents; maybe it is going to 1 cent"
- Main concern: **constantly giving up premium in forward months** (contango in bear markets)
- Example: May sugar 6¢, July 6½¢, October 7¢—holder of October futures loses 1 cent between May and October even if cash stable
- "Sure, you are forced out at 3 and get back in at 5. Then it falls to 3 again"

### Expect the Unexpected

> "The idea that one side of the market is much more likely to work in the absence of anything else is an illusion. The market just wouldn't be there if that was true."

- 1973: plenty went short soybeans at $4 thinking "sugar at 4 cents couldn't go any lower, beans at $4 couldn't go any higher"
- **Beans went to $12.97** in four or five months
- **Key lesson**: "You should expect the unexpected in this business; expect the extreme. Don't think in terms of boundaries that limit what the market might do"
- "If there is any lesson I have learned in the nearly twenty years that I've been in this business, it is that the unexpected and the impossible happen every now and then"

### Don't Be Too Tied to History

- Good trend-following system keeps you in market until evidence trend changed
- Historical research on 1972 soybeans: might conclude 50-cent advance is maximum
- **Wrong conclusion**—it went up another $8
- Good system would have kept you in for most of move

#### History as Structure, Not Boundary

- Correct: "This structure means up, and this structure means up no more"
- Wrong: "never that this structure means up this much and no more"

### Optimal vs. Suboptimal Parameters

- **Toughest problem**: Go with optimal parameter set (best past performance) or start from different premise?
- Might deliberately trade **suboptimal set** if you think future unlike past in specific way
- By definition, suboptimal has poorer past performance
- But if only 10% difference, "might well be worth that 10 percent difference if you believe the suboptimal set, as measured by past data, will fit the future better"

### Managing Large Size

- Currently: **$120 million in customer funds**
- Hasn't hit the wall yet
- About **3x current amount** ($360 million) would be about the limit
- **Diversification** key: using many different approaches and diversity in decision makers
- "You can handle several hundred million dollars without any major problem"
- Trader-trainee program helps diversify decision-making process

### Slippage Management

- **Not a problem** in Dennis's trading
- Makes hard-nosed estimate when building cost of trading into system
- Reduces costs significantly by **having own brokers**

### Knowing When Wrong

- If loss on trade after **week or two**, clearly wrong
- Even when around breakeven but significant time passed, probably wrong

### Risk Management

- Should always have **worst case point**
- Only choice: get out quicker

### Self-Taught vs. Learning from Others

- **"I would say I am self-taught"**
- "What is really amazing is how little published literature there is on trading"
- Recommends: **Edwin Lefevre's _Reminiscences of a Stock Operator_** (semifictionalized biography of Jesse Livermore)
  - "Interesting and captures the feel of trading pretty well, but that book was written sixty-some years ago"

### Key Trading Strategies

> "The market being in a trend is the main thing that eventually gets us in a trade. That is a pretty simple idea. Being consistent and making sure you do that all the time is probably more important than the particular characteristics you use to define the trend."

- Method to enter trades less critical than ensuring if **major trend**, your approach gets you in it
- Might buy earlier or later depending on how market reacts to news
- If market goes up when should go up, buy earlier; if goes down when should go up, wait

### Market Similarities

- **"I could trade without knowing the name of the market"**
- Patterns in different markets very similar
- In research: **if system doesn't work for both bonds and beans, don't care about it**

### Stocks vs. Commodities

- Stock market probably **separate behavior pattern**
- Research on individual stocks: **price fluctuations closer to random** than in commodities
- "Demonstrably, commodities are trending and, arguably, stocks are random"

#### Explanation

- **Not enough fundamental information per stock** to create sufficient trends
- Aren't as many commodities as stocks
- Commodity markets: technical information basically **price, volume, open interest**
- Stock indexes have much more: **advance/decline ratios, sentiment indicators, relationships between different groups**, etc.
- Disadvantage for trend-following in stocks: **index prices too close to random** to develop clear-cut trends because inputs (individual stocks) mostly random

### On Program Trading Criticism

> "The people that are complaining ought to be ashamed of themselves."

- Financial community should understand **"inanity of what they are complaining about"**
- **Scapegoat for declining market**—"good excuse for doing a lousy job for yourself and your clients"
- Claim: program traders taking money from stock market investors
- Reality: Program trading may move market around a bit, but **not in any systematic way**
- If caused prices too high or low, **provides better opportunities for value investors**
- "Of course, it's bad for those people who pretend they are value investors, but are really traders"

### Handling Losing Streaks

- **"Cut back. If it is really bad, stop and get out"**
- Sometimes need to get away from markets for few days
- Takes day or two, but need to stop for period of time
- "Almost like a pitcher not balking. Before he throws the ball, he has to stop at least for that second. That is what I try to do—at least have a pause. It could be for just one day."

### Public Fallacies

- **Biggest**: "That markets are supposed to make sense"
- **Technical analysis fallacy**: "The belief that technical factors are not as important as the fundamentals"

### Respects Zweig

- "There are a lot of them. Zweig, for example, is good"
- But **won't consider outside analysts as input** in a trade
- Hypothetical to trainees: "Suppose everything you know about the markets indicates a 'buy.' Then you call the floor and they tell you that I'm selling. Do you: (a) buy, (b) go short, (c) do nothing?"
- If didn't eventually understand **(a) was correct** because they have to make own market decisions, "then they didn't fit into the program"

### Managing Other People's Money

- **Big advantage: potential return with no risk**
- For ten years, people asking if he's getting tired of risk, going to burn out, going to stop
- Didn't understand what they were talking about
- Admits now: **understands value of cutting down own risk**
- Could have traded smaller with smaller profit and risk
- **Customer money** allows him to supplement profitability and keep risk lower—"just gives you a better deal"

[Note: In later interview, Dennis changed mind, possibly influenced by aggravation of large funds. Decided to extricate himself gradually, saying: "I found that it was more trouble than it was worth. The costs were not financial; they were psychological."]

### Public Fund Shutdown (April 1988)

- Funds down just under **49% when stopped trading**
- Rather than trigger automatic 50% termination point: liquidated all positions and resolicited investors to allow lower cutoff
- Would cut back faster in future, but trades still the same
- Someone said: "You claim the markets were bad. Well, since you could have done the exact opposite and made a lot of money, weren't they really good?"
- Dennis: "Last thing I would have wanted to do was to be on the opposite side of those trades. In the long run, that is a way to lose an infinite amount of money"

### October 1987 Interest Rate Loss

- Short side of interest rate markets = one of worst losses
- Loss due to market **gapping way past stop point**
- Example: October 20, normally would have been out of short Eurodollar position 40-50 points higher
- Market opened **240 points higher** that day—blew **190 points in a skid** absolutely unavoidable
- "If you have any doubt about getting out as fast as possible in a situation like that, then you are really in big trouble"

### Market Changes & False Breakouts

- Only factor objectively identified: **tendency toward more false breakouts**
- Related to **tremendous increase in computerized trend-following** past 5-10 years
- "There is no doubt about it. In a perverse sort of way, it represents the ultimate triumph of technical trading over fundamental trading. I say perverse because it is a victory that devalues technical trading"

### Future of Trend-Following

- **Will come a day** when easily discovered, lightly conceived trend-following systems no longer work
- "It is going to be harder to develop good systems"
- But if you **view problem correctly**, can make many other trend followers work to your advantage
- Can't get too specific about solution—"if we are right, that is pretty valuable information"
- "To be successful you always have to be one step ahead of everyone else"

### Solving the Crowding Problem

- Started working on this well before 1987 performance problems
- Past ten years: **virtual bandwagon-effect** of trend-following
- Half the work in solving problem = finding right way to conceptualize it
- Took years to figure out right questions to ask
- Arrived at satisfactory solution **right around time closed down public funds** (ironic timing)

### Solution to False Breakouts

- Can't be specific, but involves **being far more short-term or as long-term as you can stand**
- **Intermediate term** picks up vast majority of trend followers
- **Best strategy: avoid the middle like the plague**

### Emotional Detachment

> "I try for there not to be. It is totally counterproductive to get wrapped up in the results. Trading decisions should be made as unemotionally as possible."

- Maintains perspective: **"There is more to life than trading"**
- Being emotionally deflated would mean **lacking confidence** in what he's doing
- Avoids focusing on short-term results—misleading

#### Avoiding Both Emotional Extremes

- Also avoids emotional elation when things going well
- "There is no way to play just one side of that street"
- Feel too good when things good → inevitably feel too bad when things poor
- After twenty years: "it either drives you crazy, or you learn to put it into perspective"

#### Does It Get Easier?

- **Not necessarily**—gets easier to put in perspective
- "Everyone has shock absorbers that deteriorate over time"
- **"Being a trader is like being a boxer: Every now and then, the market gives you a good wallop. After twenty years you get a bit punch-drunk"**

### Staying Emotionally Calm

- **"Like playing golf: You can throw your clubs around after making a bad shot, but while you are making the next shot you should keep your head down and your eye on the ball"**

### Long-Term Scenarios

- Has mental pictures but tries not to use when trading
- "Trading to me is like betting on independent rolls of the dice that you think are loaded a little bit in your favor"
- Know some statistical things about market
- **Long-term scenarios can be right or wrong**, but even if right, "I'm not convinced that they make much difference over the term of any individual trade"

### Dollar Collapse View

- Would like to say it doesn't affect basic trading pattern, doesn't think it should
- **But probably has in the past**
- Worst thing: miss a profit opportunity (assuming disciplined enough to cut losses short)
- Rigid long-term views the kind of thing most likely to lead to that mistake
- Example: If believe dollar going to weaken and ignore sell signal in foreign currencies, might risk missing large profit
- "What is my reward if my view was right? Avoiding a small loss. Therefore, the risk/reward is all wrong for my type of trading"

### Major Trends Prediction (mid-1988)

- **"I bet we will be at record levels of inflation by the end of 1990"**

#### Driving Force

- Driven by trying to avoid deep recession
- Recession caused by **federal budget deficit** as investors require higher real interest rates to buy debt
- Government will try to avoid recession by **stimulating economy**—"a tactic which essentially doesn't work"

#### Fear of Recession → Monetary Easing → Inflation

- "Unfortunately, a very Republican idea, but I think it is right"
- Financial markets in conservative hands—people lending money to government and business won't buy monetary easing as solution to recession

### Deficit as Time Bomb

- "We tend to think that since it is not a problem now, that means it won't be"
- "We expect continuity in our lives, but the economy, and certainly the markets, are more discontinuous than continuous"
- **"It is like having termites in the foundation of your house. You may not notice them until one day they gnaw away a big chunk and the house collapses. I don't think anybody should take a large amount of comfort in the fact that things appear to be holding together"**

### Political View: Keynesianism

- If were President: deficit would be first thing to change
- **"Especially important for Democrats, since they were the first ones to pick up the banner of _Keynesianism_"** [advocacy of government intervention and deficit spending to stimulate economy]

<!-- pp. 111-130 -->

## Richard Dennis (conclusion)

### Performance Track Record

- **Investor returns**: $1,000 invested at start of Dennis's fund → $3,833 at close (~25% annual compounded return)
- **Dennis's final year loss**: Lost ~10% of money made in markets during final trading year
- Dennis lost substantial portion of net worth, but remains a legend
- **Career transition**: No impact on moving into politics — made decision independently
- Completely stopped trading after retirement announcement

### Dennis's Trading Philosophy Summary

**95% of profits from 5% of trades** — missing major opportunities is the worst mistake
- Dennis downplays trying to pick turning points despite his success at catching tops/bottoms
- **Key insight**: Losing periods are when you need to focus most on trading, not pull back
- Guard against rigid opinions that prevent you from catching major trends

> "Trade small because that's when you are as bad as you are ever going to be. Learn from your mistakes. Don't be misled by the day-to-day fluctuations in your equity."
> — Richard Dennis, advice to novice traders

---

## Paul Tudor Jones: The Art of Aggressive Trading

### Background & Performance

**October 1987**: Market crashed like 1929, but **Tudor Futures Fund returned 62%** that month
- **Five consecutive triple-digit return years** with very low equity retracements (1986: 99.2%)
- Started as broker (second year: $1M+ in commissions)
- Went to NY Cotton Exchange floor as independent trader (fall 1980)
- **Floor trading record**: Only one losing month in 3.5 years
- Launched **Tudor Futures Fund**: September 1984 with $1.5M → grew to $330M by October 1988
- $1,000 invested at inception → $17,482 by October 1988
- Stopped accepting new funds in October 1987

### Character & Style

**Public image vs. reality**: Swaggering, egotistical trader publicly; relaxed and unassuming privately
- Shouts orders with "ferocity of a drill sergeant"
- Maintains steel-hard emotional control — can carry on calm conversation while positions get decimated
- **Chesapeake Bay mansion**, 3,000-acre wildlife preserve, philanthropy (second avocation)

### Philanthropic Work

**I Have a Dream Program**: Finances college education for 85 elementary students from Brooklyn's Bedford-Stuyvesant
- Meets with adopted students weekly — personally involved, not just donating money
- **Robin Hood Foundation**: Endowment grown to $5M
- Raises money from rich, distributes to private groups/individuals helping the poor
- Targets frontline workers operating with virtually no budget (not bureaucracies)

### Mentors & Early Training

**Eli Tullis** (legendary cotton trader, New Orleans):
- **Steel-hard emotional control**: Carried on polite conversation with visitors while positions got decimated
- Traded position sizes of 3,000 contracts when entire market open interest was 30,000
- Pure speculator using his own floor broker — everyone knew his position
- Attitude: "The hell with it, I'm going to take them head on"

**Key lessons from Tullis**:
- Trading is competitive — you must handle getting your butt kicked
- **Moving volume**: Get out when market lets you, not when you want to
- Don't wait for new highs/lows to move large positions — little volume trades at turning points
- **Contrarian lesson**: When markets look their best at new highs, often best time to sell

### The 1979 Cotton Trade (Formative Disaster)

**Setup**: Broker with speculative accounts, long 400 contracts July cotton trading 82-86 cent range
- Bought every time market came to low end of range
- Market broke to new lows, took out stops, rebounded 30-40 points
- Thought stops being triggered = ready to rally

**The mistake**: Standing outside ring, told floor broker to bid 82.90 for 100 July (very big order then)
- Broker bid 90 for 100, Refco broker screamed "Sold!"
- Refco owned most certificated stock — intended to deliver against July contract
- Premium to October was ~4 cents — they were trading at 4-cent premium
- **Congestion pattern insight**: Width of 82-86 range would equal the next move down (measured move concept)

**The panic**:
- Saw immediately market going straight to 78 cents
- "It was my blood that was going to carry it there"
- Had entered long 400, added 100 day trade, final 100 on macho bid = 600 contracts total
- Lost 60-70% of client equity in single trade

**Lessons learned**:
- Never play macho man with the market
- Never overtrade relative to account equity
- **Turning point**: Almost quit, then decided to become disciplined and businesslike
- Now thinks constantly about losing money, not making money
- Always knows exit point before entering trade
- **Mental stop**: "If it hits that number, I am out no matter what"

### Current Risk Management Philosophy

**Daily equity monitoring**: Goal to finish each day with more than started
- Never thinks about overnight position carryover — mental reference point is always last night's close
- Being short from previous night at higher levels has no bearing on current market opinion

**Risk control is most important thing in trading**:
- Currently down 6.5% for month → has 3.5% stop on equity for rest of month
- Never wants double-digit loss in any month
- If trading poorly, keeps reducing position size → trading smallest when performing worst

> "Risk control is the most important thing in trading."
> — Paul Tudor Jones

**Monthly equity stop discipline**: Down ~6.5% this month → 3.5% remaining stop ensures no double-digit monthly loss

### Trading Rules

1. **Don't average losers** — decrease trading volume when trading poorly, increase when trading well
2. **Never trade situations without control** (e.g., don't risk significant money ahead of key reports — that's gambling)
3. **Get out if uncomfortable** — can always get back in; fresh start is valuable
4. **Entry point doesn't matter** — only question is current bullish/bearish stance (mental reference = last night's close)
5. **Play great defense, not offense** — assume every position is wrong, define maximum drawdown, have exit game plan
6. **Don't be a hero, don't have an ego** — question yourself constantly; feeling very good = death

> "Don't be a hero. Don't have an ego. Always question yourself and your ability. Don't ever feel that you are very good. The second you do, you are dead."
> — Paul Tudor Jones

**Jesse Livermore quote**: "In the long run, you can't ever win trading markets" (devastating but frightening — guides Jones to play great defense)

### Flexibility & Turning Points

**Extreme flexibility** demonstrated during interview period:
- First meeting: Heavily short stock market, building major short position
- Two weeks later: Shifted 180 degrees to bullish after market failed to follow through on downside
- Not only abandoned original position quickly but willing to join opposite side when evidence proved him wrong

**Market opportunism approach**:
- Develops idea, pursues from very-low-risk standpoint until proven wrong or changes viewpoint
- Does series of probes until finally hitting the turn
- "Better story": catching exact turn vs. being right on fifth try (but both work)

**Swing trading philosophy**:
- Best money made at market turns
- Has often missed "the meat in the middle" but caught many bottoms/tops
- Conventional wisdom: get killed picking tops/bottoms, make money catching trends — Jones inverts this
- Markets only trend ~15% of the time; rest of time they move sideways

### Success After Winning Streaks

**More scared now than ever** despite years of success:
- Recognizes how ephemeral success can be in trading
- Biggest hits always come after great winning periods (overconfidence danger)
- Success breeds complacency — must stay frightened

**Managing large sums is tremendously more difficult**:
- Could make substantially higher percentage returns trading smaller amounts
- Profit incentive fees vs. size impact on performance — thinks about this daily

### October 1987 Crash

**Preparation**: Expected major collapse since mid-1986, drew up contingency plans for financial meltdown
- Week of crash = "one of most exciting periods of my life"
- Monday October 19: knew market would crash that day

**Why so certain?**:
- Previous Friday = record volume day on downside (exact same thing happened in 1929, two days before crash)
- **Analog model to 1929**: Jones's research director **Peter Borish** superimposed 1980s over 1920s market
- Two markets showed remarkable correlation — model perfectly nailed the collapse
- Treasury Secretary **Baker's** statement that U.S. wouldn't support dollar due to West Germany disagreements = kiss of death

**The trade**:
- Covered shorts and went somewhat long on close of crash day itself (October 19)
- Also had extremely profitable bond position (not just short stocks)
- Bond market acting terrible all day October 19 — very concerned about financial safety of clients' assets (funds with commission houses on street could be in jeopardy)
- Couldn't pull trigger on long bond position during trading
- During last half hour, bonds suddenly turned up → Fed was adding massive liquidity
- "As soon as I saw bond market act right for a moment, I went wild"

### Economic Views (Post-1987)

**Second interview showed extreme caution** about projections (feared becoming scapegoat):
- Concerned second major selling wave could lead to "financial McCarthyism"
- **Historical precedent**: 1930s Senate hearings desperately sought villains for 1929 crash → dragged up NYSE officials who held long positions during collapse
- Had been rattled by prominent government official's call about his trading
- Replied to trading strategy questions with prerecorded-sounding responses (possibly making official statement for future congressional hearing)

**Wall Street Journal article**: Publicized Jones was short 2,000 S&P contracts
- Market didn't decline as expected → Jones uses **time stop** in addition to price stop
- If thinks market should break and it doesn't, gets out even without losing money

**Credit availability delaying crash**:
- Economy much stronger than 1929 analog model suggested
- Volvo offering 120-month car loans (10 years!) vs. 24 months twenty years ago (now 54 months average)
- Ease of credit delaying process relative to 1920s cash economy
- Believes final outcome will be same, but credit delays the timeline

**Reagan economic critique**:
- Made country feel good but "biggest disaster that ever struck" economically
- Promised to cut deficit, then went on "biggest spending binge in history"
- Borrowed against future to create prosperity — "soon we will have to pay"
- Historical pattern: Credit eventually kills all great societies (Romans, 16th-century Spain, 18th-century France, 19th-century Britain)
- "We are going to relearn what financial discipline is all about"

**Macroeconomic pessimism**:
- No blueprint out of current dilemma
- Perhaps responding to larger super cycles beyond our control (civilizational decline pattern)
- Period of pain ahead

### Trading Systems

**Found one system that works well** after testing every system available:
- **Trend-following system** (obvious reasons for secrecy)
- Basic premise: markets move sharply when they move
- Sudden range expansion in a market = signal market getting ready to move in direction of that expansion
- Human nature tries to fade price moves; range expansion = loud, clear signal of impending directional move
- Started trading system portion of funds six months before interview — doing very well

**System vs. trader comparison**:
- Good system may trade more markets effectively (unlimited computing power advantage)
- Good trader usually outperforms good system (complexity of defining/interacting/changing market patterns)
- **Good system helps diversify** — catches 10x as much of price move during 15% trending periods

### Training Traders

**Motivation**: Guy helped him at 21 — felt obligation to do same for others
- **Hired ~35 traders** via countless interviews (deluged by applicants)
- Mixed success overall — starting to believe it takes talent

**Too optimistic about others' ability to succeed** (self-identified weakness)

### 85% of Net Worth in Own Funds

"Safest place in world for it" — believes his defensive/conservative approach will get money back

### Life Philosophy

**Emotional intensity**: Trading gives "incredibly intense feeling of what life is all about"
- Nothing worse than bad trading day (feel so low, hard to hold head up)
- Would take combination of winning and losing days anytime over just winning
- Emotionally live on the extremes

> "Don't focus on making money; focus on protecting what you have."
> — Paul Tudor Jones, advice to average trader

**Career commitment**: "I wouldn't have it any other way" — sees himself trading 10-15 years down the road

