## Paul Tudor Jones — Summary & Key Themes

### Risk Control as Core Philosophy

**Traumatic 1979 cotton trade** permanently forged importance of risk management
- Overtraded massively (60-70% of client equity in one position)
- Learned: never play macho, always know exit before entry, think about losses not gains

**Current discipline**:
- Mental stop on every position
- Daily equity goal (finish higher than started)
- Monthly maximum loss limit (caps at ~10%)
- Reduces position size during losing streaks
- Mental reference point = last night's close (no loyalty to positions)

### Trading Style: Swing Trading & Opportunism

Contrarian approach — best money at market turns, not trend-following middle
- Repeated low-risk probes from long side in declining market until finally catching bottom
- Very short-term pain horizon → frequently tries trades, gets stopped out, re-enters
- "Premier market opportunist" — develops idea, pursues until proven wrong or changes mind

### Elliott Wave Theory & 1929 Analog Model

Attributes much success to Elliott Wave approach (creating favorable risk/reward opportunities)
- **Peter Borish's analog model**: superimposed 1980s over 1920s → remarkable correlation
- Model perfectly predicted October 1987 crash timing
- Record volume Friday before crash (exact 1929 pattern) + Baker dollar statement = confirmation

### Emotional Control & Humility

**Eli Tullis's example**: Steel-hard control while getting decimated
- Jones maintained composure during $1M+ loss in closing minutes (didn't realize market moved against him until checking prices later)
- After big wins, particularly cautious about overconfidence
- More scared now than ever despite success — knows how ephemeral winning can be

### Economic Worldview

**Credit cycle pessimism**: Believes advanced civilizations fall prey to credit excess (historical pattern)
- Reagan borrowed future prosperity via deficit spending
- Ease of credit (120-month car loans) delaying inevitable reckoning
- No clear solution — may be part of larger super cycle beyond control
- Period of pain and relearning financial discipline ahead

### Philanthropy as Second Calling

Not just donating — personally involved (meets students weekly)
- I Have a Dream Program (85 Brooklyn students)
- Robin Hood Foundation ($5M endowment) targeting frontline poverty workers
- Believes in leverage — helping one kid impacts family and other kids (multiplicative effect)
- "Markets have been so good to me that I feel I should give back something in return"

<!-- pp. 131-150 -->

## Gary Bielfeldt: Yes, They Do Trade T-Bonds in Peoria

### The One-Lot Corn Trader Who Became a T-Bond Giant

- **BLH** (basically one individual: **Gary Bielfeldt**) ranks among the world's largest T-bond futures traders
- Started 25 years ago with just **$1,000**, initially trading a single corn contract
- Built account through extreme focus: doesn't believe in diversification—pick one area and become expert
- **Soybean complex** was his focal point for most of his career, then shifted to T-bonds
- Lives and trades from **Peoria, Illinois**—refused to move to Chicago trading floor to maintain cherished lifestyle
- Philosophy: plow trading wealth back into community projects benefiting his hometown

### The All-or-Nothing Soybean Trade (1965)

- By 1965, built $1,000 to $10,000 through painstaking effort
- Put entire account into **twenty soybean contracts**—extremely high leverage for $10,000
- Consulted former agricultural economics professor **Thomas Hieronymus** who also believed soybeans would rise
- A **10-cent price decline** would have completely wiped out account; smaller decline would trigger forced liquidation
- Prices initially fell, came perilously close to margin call, then reversed
- **More than doubled equity** on that single trade—launched him toward full-time trading career

### The Great Pivot: From Soybeans to T-Bonds

- By early 1980s, trading size grew so large that **government position limits** in soybeans/grains became impediment
- **1983 soybean loss** + bad trade forced shift to T-bond futures (which had no position limit at the time)
- Shift coincided with **major bottom forming** in T-bond market
- Became very bullish, built huge long T-bond position at the right time
- When T-bond market exploded **mid-1984 to early 1985**, Bielfeldt was perfectly positioned
- His ability to **stay with a major position** for a long-term move allowed massive leverage of well-timed trade
- **Best trade ever**—catapulted him into same league as major institutional market participants

### Trading Approach: Fundamental + Technical Backup

- Leans primarily on **fundamental analysis**—but knows getting 80% of fundamentals is best-case scenario
- Developed own **trend-following system** as backup in case fundamental analysis wrong
- Uses system primarily to signal **when to get out** of a position
- **Example (early 1988)**: Long bonds expecting weaker economy; system provided rationale for exiting losing position when economy proved stronger than anticipated and October 1987 crash fear factor didn't materialize

### Opinion on Trend-Following Systems

- **Best thing for new traders**: teaches principle of letting profits run and cutting losses short
- Learning discipline via trend-following system (even temporarily) increases odds of success
- **Systems sold to public** generally trade too frequently—transaction costs kill profitability
- To be viable, trend-following system needs **medium to longer term** focus; sensitive systems generate excessive commissions
- Advises combining system with own judgment: **trade half on system, half on judgment** in case system isn't working
- Now focuses mostly on own judgment rather than systems
- Systems don't work as well because **too many people using them**—when crowd does same thing, market adjusts

### Fundamental Factors for T-Bond Market

- **Economy** is single most important factor
- Four other key elements: **inflation expectations**, **the dollar**, **trade balance**, **budget deficit**

### The 1983-1984 Bond Bottom: Most Dramatic Trade

- Started trying to pick bottom when bonds trading in **63-66 area**
- Risk tolerance: Generally **½ to 1½ points** per trade (one point in T-bond futures = 32 ticks = **$1,000 per contract**)
- Multiple failed attempts before finally going long in right place
- **Turning point (May 1984)**: Government auctioned five-year notes at **13.93% yield**
  - No qualified borrowers for three-year loans at 13% since 1974
  - Yet government five-year notes selling at nearly full percentage point above that level
  - At height of recession in Peoria: unemployment approaching 20%, farm crisis worsening
  - Felt interest rates had gone high enough
- From May 1984 through April 1986, traded T-bonds heavily from the long side
- **No question best trade and longest trend ever**

### Elements of Good Trading

- **Most important**: method for staying with winners and getting rid of losers
- Develop plan before putting on trade—strategies for various contingencies
- Helps to have **long-term objective** derived from thorough homework
- Combine long-term objective with **protective stop** that moves as position goes your way
- Alternatively, use trend-following system to signal exit
- Plan objective + exit strategy **greatly increases potential** for staying in winning positions

### Why Most Traders Lose

- **Overtrade**—have to be right a lot just to cover commissions

### Traits of Successful Trader

1. **Discipline**—everyone says this
2. **Patience**—if you have good trade on, stay with it
3. **Courage**—comes from adequate capitalization; need courage to enter market
4. **Willingness to lose**—also related to adequate capitalization
5. **Strong desire to win**

### On Willingness to Lose

- Attitude: if trade loses, handle it without problem and move to next trade
- **Can't let losing trade get to you emotionally**

### On Courage

- If 260-pound fullback running through line and 175-pound linebacker has to stop him, linebacker needs courage
- Need courage when **everyone bullish on dollar and yen sharply lower**—takes courage to fade major consensus and buy the yen

### How Bielfeldt Judges Success

- Most people judge success by performance in their field
- Personally: judges success by **what he does with accumulated money**
- Wife and he established **foundation** to share success with community by supporting various programs
- Family directly involved in evaluating projects and deciding which to fund
- Set up in **1985**, but had thought about idea since early 1970s
- Always planned that if successful, would establish foundation to help community
- Believes this **long-term goal was important motivation** leading to success as trader

### Advice for Beginning Trader

- **Very important not to get too far behind**—very difficult to fight back
- Most traders take **risks too large** at beginning
- Not selective enough about when to take risks

### The Poker Analogy (Off-the-Record, Then On)

> "I learned how to play poker at a very young age. My father taught me the concept of playing the percentage hands. You don't just play every hand and stay through every card; because if you do, you will have a much higher probability of losing. You should play the good hands, and drop out of the poor hands, forfeiting the ante."

- When more cards on table and you have very strong hand—**when percentages skewed in your favor**—raise and play to hilt
- **Applied to trading**: increases odds of winning significantly
- Keeps **concept of patience** by waiting for right trade (like waiting for percentage hand in poker)
- If trade doesn't look right, get out and take small loss—equivalent to **forfeiting ante** by dropping out of poor poker hand
- When percentages strongly in favor, be aggressive and leverage trade (like raising on good hands in poker)

> At this point, Bielfeldt asked me to turn off the tape recorder. He talked about the relevance and application of poker strategy to trading. His reason for keeping the comments off-the-record was that he didn't want to contribute to the image of trading as a form of gambling. I found his analogy particularly apropos and finally persuaded him to put it on the record.

### Interviewer's Commentary

- Bielfeldt's story: **inspiring example** of patience + aggressive trading style
- Starting with minuscule capital, working independently, without staff or elaborate technology—became one of world's most successful traders
- Long-term goals and actions **positively impacted entire community**
- Most insightful part: **poker analogy**
- Comparison to **James Rogers**: both emphasize having patience to wait for right trade to come along

## Ed Seykota: Everybody Gets What They Want

### Unknown but Elite: Record-Breaking Returns

- **Completely unknown** to public and most financial community
- Early 1970s: hired by major brokerage, conceived and developed **first commercial computerized trading system** for managing clients' money in futures
- System quite profitable, but **management interference and second-guessing** significantly impeded performance
- This experience catalyzed Seykota going out on his own
- Applied systematized approach to handful of accounts + own money
- **Astounding rate of return**: One customer account starting with **$5,000 in 1972** was over **250,000% on cash-on-cash basis** by mid-1988
  - Normalized for withdrawals, theoretically up **several million percent**
- **No other trader matched this track record** over same length of time
- Interviewer had never heard of Seykota when starting book project
- **Michael Marcus** cited Seykota as person **most influential** in transforming him into successful trader

> "You know, you really should interview Ed Seykota. He is not only a great trader; he is a mind." —Michael Marcus

### The Reno Interview: Two Hours Between Flights

- Marcus provided phone introduction; interviewer outlined book concept
- Already out West; most convenient to interview Seykota by rerouting return to New York via Reno
- Seykota agreeable but skeptical about completing interview in **two-hour window** (time available for flight connections)
- Interviewer assured feasible as long as conversation stayed focused
- Cut arrival extremely close, nearly missed flight due to ticket agent argument
- Raced through airport, reached gate with only seconds to spare
- Drive to Seykota's house too far for cab—rented car
- Early morning, highway winding into mountains, found classical music station playing **Mozart's Clarinet Concerto**—combination glorious
- Seykota works from **office in his house** bordering **Lake Tahoe**
- Brief walk onto beach behind house before interview—cold, clear morning, idyllic view
- Contrast to interviewer's Wall Street office (prominent view of ugly building)—plead guilty to jealousy

### Seykota's Workspace and Trading Style

- Desk **not flanked by array of quote screens**—or even single screen
- Trading largely confined to **few minutes** running computer program generating signals for next day
- Struck by intensity of both **intelligence and sensitivity**—odd combination
- Unique vantage point: could discuss analytical techniques like consummate scientist (degree in electrical engineering from MIT), then reveal great sensitivity/insight into human behavior when conversation turned to trading psychology
- In recent years, very involved in **psychology**—helping people solve problems more important element than market analysis/trading
- Suspects Seykota finds contrast artificial: **trading and psychology one and the same thing**

### Interview Not as Focused as Intended

- Conversation went off in many directions, barely scratched surface by end of two hours
- Continued on, assuming would catch later flight
- Flight interviewer missed was **last direct Reno to New York**
- Seykota later said he knew in first phone conversation interviewer would end up spending the day
- **Extremely perceptive about people**

> "How many minutes fast do you set your watch?" —Ed Seykota

- Found question particularly striking: in brief time together, picked up on basic character trait
- Also particularly timely, given near-missed flight earlier that morning
- Seykota's success goes well beyond trading
- Impressed as someone who **found meaning in life** and **living exactly the life he wanted**

### First Involvement in Trading: The Silver Disaster

- Late 1960s: decided **silver had to rise** when U.S. Treasury stopped selling it
- Opened commodity margin account to take full advantage of insight
- Broker convinced him to **short copper**
- Soon got stopped out, lost money, **lost trading virginity**
- Went back to waiting for start of big inevitable bull market in silver
- Finally the day arrived—bought
- **To amazement and financial detriment, price started falling!**
- At first seemed impossible silver could fall on such bullish deal
- Yet price was falling—that was fact
- Soon stop got hit

> "This was a very stunning education about the way markets discount news. I became more and more fascinated with how markets work."

### Discovery of Richard Donchian's Mechanical System

- Saw letter published by **Richard Donchian** implying purely mechanical trend-following system could beat markets
- Seemed impossible at first
- Wrote computer programs (on **punch cards** in those days) to test theories
- **Amazingly, theories tested true**
- To this day, not sure understands why or whether really needs to
- Studying markets and backing up opinions with money **so fascinating** compared to other career opportunities—began trading full time for living

### First Trading Job: Analyst for Eggs and Broilers

- Landed first Wall Street job early 1970s as analyst with major brokerage
- Assigned to cover **egg and broiler markets**
  - **Broilers**: young chickens up to 2½ pounds dressed weight
  - Futures markets for both have since disappeared as waning trading activity prompted delisting by parent exchanges
- Found it interesting that entry level guy like him **immediately placed in charge of dispensing trading advice**
- Once wrote article recommending traders **stay away from market for a while**
- Management censored that comment—likely because didn't promise to motivate much trading

### Desire to Apply Computers to Analysis

- Wanted to start applying computers to business of analysis
- In those days, computers still typically **punch card devices** used for accounting
- Guy running computer department saw Seykota as **threat to job security**—repeatedly chased him off turf
- After about month, announced quitting
- Head of department called to find out why—**first time ever interested** in talking to him

### Second Job: Using Computer to Test Trading Systems on Weekends

- Went to work for another brokerage going through reorganization
- Lot less management—took advantage of lack of supervision by **using accounting computer to test trading systems during weekends**
- Had IBM 360 taking up large air-conditioned room
- Over course of about half year, tested **about hundred variations of four simple systems** for about ten years of data on ten commodities
- Today, same job takes about **one day on PC**
- Got results—confirmed **possibility of making money from trend-following systems**

### Official Job: Loading Paper on Reuters Machine

- Normal **Clark Kent type job** during week: load new rolls of paper onto Reuters machine when margin turned pink
- Responsible for tearing off news in strips and hanging up on wall behind machine
- Trick: tear between line-feeds to get smooth edge
- Hardly anyone read news—would have to lean way over machine to see pages
- Started reading news and **personally delivering to brokers**
- **Bonus**: got to observe lot of brokers' trading styles

### Why Accept Menial Job?

> "Because I knew I wanted to be in the business, and I didn't care what I did, or what I got paid."

### Why Not Stay at Original Position as Analyst?

- **Stultifying environment**
- Disapproved of management pressures to recommend trades when no trading opportunities
- Also, never being allowed access to company computers for testing trading systems (real desire) was **dead issue**

### Development of First Commercial Computerized Trading System

- Eventually management got interested in using research results for managing money
- Developed **first large-scale commercial computerized trading system**
- Program marketed by **several hundred agents** of firm
- Equity under management **several million dollars**—large amount in early 1970s

### Management Familiarity with Richard Donchian

- Familiar with **Richard Donchian**, pioneer in developing trend-following trading systems (although at the time doing everything by hand)
- Because of exposure, already favorably disposed to concept of using trading systems to manage money
- Also, computers so new that **"computer system" was great buzzword**

### How Trading Program Performed

- Program did fine
- **Problem**: management couldn't keep from second-guessing signals
- **Example**: Program generated buy signal for sugar when trading around 5 cents
- Management thought market already overbought, decided not to take signal
- When market kept going higher, came up with rule: **buy on first 20-point pullback** [100 points = 1 cent]
- When no pullback developed, modified rule to **buying on first 30-point reaction**
- As market kept moving higher without meaningful retracements, changed rule to 50 points, eventually 100 points
- Finally, with sugar around **9 cents**, decided it was bull market and better buy before prices went much higher

### The Compounded Error

- Put managed accounts long at that point
- Sugar market peaked shortly thereafter
- Compounded error by **ignoring sell signal** as well—signal which also would have been very profitable

### Bottom Line of Management Interference

- Because of interference, **most profitable trade of year ended up losing money**
- Instead of theoretical return of 60% for year, quite a few accounts actually lost money
- This type of **meddling** one of main reasons eventually quit

### Other Reasons for Quitting

- Management wanted to change system to **trade more actively**, generating more commission income
- Explained very easy to make such change, but doing so would **seriously impede performance**
- They didn't seem to care

### After Quitting Research Department

- Just quit research department, stayed on as broker managing accounts
- After about two years, gave up brokerage to become **money manager**
- Shift allowed getting away from earning living from commissions—**counterproductive incentive** to making money for clients
- Switched to **pure profit incentive fee arrangement**

### Continue Trading the System After Leaving?

- Yes, although **substantially revised system** over the years

### Performance Track Record

- Does not publicize track record other than **"model account"**
- Actual customer account starting with **$5,000 in 1972** has made **over $15 million**
- Theoretically, total return would have been **many multiples larger** had there been no withdrawals

### Why Not Deluged with Requests to Manage Money?

- Receives requests but **very rarely accepts new accounts**
- Only after considerable interviewing and screening to determine **motivations and attitudes** of client
- Found that people he associates with have **subtle yet very important effects** on performance
- If able to support him and methods over long term, they **tend to help**
- If get too concerned with short-term ups and downs of account, they can be **hindrance**

### How Many Accounts Originally Started With?

- About **half dozen** back in early 1970s

### How Many Still With Him?

- **Four**
- One client made about $15 million, decided to withdraw money and manage himself
- Another made over $10 million, decided to buy house on beach and retire

### Source of Learning Before Designing First System

- Inspired and influenced by book ***Reminiscences of a Stock Operator***
- Also by **Richard Donchian's** five- and twenty-day moving average crossover system and weekly rule system
- Considers Donchian **one of guiding lights of technical trading**

### First Trading System

- Variation of Donchian's moving average system
- Used **exponential averaging method**—easier to calculate, computational errors tended to disappear over time
- So new at the time being passed around by word of mouth as **"expedential system"**

### Eventually Changed Systems—How Know When Needed to Change?

- **Systems don't need to be changed**
- Trick: for trader to **develop system with which he is compatible**

### Incompatible with Original System?

- Original system very simple with **hard-and-fast rules** didn't allow for deviations
- Found it difficult to stay with system while disregarding own feelings
- Kept **jumping on and off**—often at just wrong time
- Thought knew better than system
- At time, didn't really trust trend-following systems would work
- Plenty of literature "proving" they don't
- Seemed waste of intellect and MIT education to just sit there and not try to figure out markets
- **Eventually**: became more confident of trading with trend, more able to ignore news, became more comfortable with approach
- Also, as continued to incorporate more **"expert trader rules,"** system became more compatible with trading style

### Trading Style

- Basically **trend following**, with some **special pattern recognition** and **money management algorithms**

### Without Divulging Trade Secrets, How Spectacularly Outperform Standard Trend-Following?

- **Key to long-term survival and prosperity**: lot to do with money management techniques incorporated into technical system
- **Old traders vs. bold traders**: very few **old, bold traders**

### Why Done So Much Better with Money Management Rules?

- Seems to have **gift**
- Related to overall philosophy: **loving markets** and **maintaining optimistic attitude**
- As keeps trading and learning, system (mechanical computer version of what he does) keeps evolving
- **Considers self and how does things as kind of system**—by definition, always follows
- Sometimes trades entirely off mechanical part
- Sometimes overrides signals based on strong feelings
- Sometimes just quits altogether
- Immediate trading result probably **breakeven to somewhat negative**
- However, if didn't allow freedom to discharge creative side, might build up to **some kind of blowout**
- **Striking workable ecology** seems to promote trading longevity—**one key to success**

### Relative Advantages/Disadvantages: Systems vs. Discretionary Trading

- **Systems trading ultimately discretionary**
- Manager still has to decide: how much risk to accept, which markets to play, how aggressively to increase/decrease trading base as function of equity change
- These decisions **quite important**—often **more important than trade timing**

### Percentage of Trading Systems-Based? Changed Over Time?

- Over time, become **more mechanical**:
  1. More trusting of trend trading
  2. Mechanical programs factored in more "tricks of the trade"
- Still go through periods of thinking can outperform own system
- Such excursions often **self-correcting through process of losing money**

### Present/Future Prospects for Trend-Following Systems? Growing Prevalence Doom to Eventual Failure?

- No. **All trading done on some sort of system**, whether or not conscious
- Many good systems based on following trends
- **Life itself based on trends**: Birds start south for winter and keep going; Companies track trends and alter products; Tiny protozoa move in trends along chemical and luminescence gradients
- **Profitability moves in cycles**: Periods when trend-following highly successful → increased popularity → number of system users increases → markets shift from trending to directionless price action → systems become unprofitable → undercapitalized/inexperienced traders shaken out
- **Longevity is key to success**

### Thoughts on Using Fundamental Analysis as Input?

- Fundamentals you read about typically useless—market already discounted price (**"funny-mentals"**)
- However, if catch on early, before others believe, might have valuable **"surprise-a-mentals"**

### Answer Facetious—Only Use Technical Analysis?

- Primarily **trend trader** with touches of hunches based on about twenty years experience
- **In order of importance**: (1) long-term trend, (2) current chart pattern, (3) picking good spot to buy or sell
- Those three primary components of trading
- **Way down in very distant fourth place**: fundamental ideas
- Quite likely, on balance, have **cost money**

### Picking Right Spot to Buy: Determining Reaction Point? How Avoid Missing Major Moves?

- No. If buying, point would be **above market**
- Try to identify point expecting **market momentum strong** in direction of trade to reduce probable risk
- **Don't try to pick bottom or top**

### If Bullish, Always Wait for Short-Term Strength Before Entering? Or Sometimes Buy on Reaction?

- If bullish, **neither buy on reaction nor wait for strength**—already in
- Turn bullish **instant buy stop hit**, stay bullish **until sell stop hit**
- **Being bullish and not being long is illogical**

### Ever Use Contrary Opinion as Aid to Trading?

- Sometimes
- **Example**: At recent goldbug conference, virtually all speakers bearish
- Said to self: **"Gold is probably near bottom"**
- [Market did indeed rally after that conference]

### Buy Because of That Input?

- No, trend still down
- But might get to **lighten up short position**

### Most Dramatic or Emotional Trading Experience?

- Dramatic and emotional experiences tend to be negative
- **Pride, hope, fear, greed** are great banana peel
- Biggest slip-ups occurred shortly after got **emotionally involved with positions**

### Actual "War Stories"?

- Prefers not to dwell on past situations
- Tends to **cut bad trades as soon as possible, forget them, move on** to new opportunities
- After burying dead trade, doesn't like to dig up details again—at least not in print
- Maybe some evening, after dinner, sitting around fire, off record, deep in Tahoe winter...

### Specific Trading Mistakes Learned From?

- Had **"thing" for silver** for years
- One of first losses in silver, as were many worst losses
- Seemed to get into blood and hypnotize
- Inveigled to **pull protective stops** to avoid getting bear-raided
- Naturally, would hold momentarily then collapse some more
- Got killed so many times by silver spikes started thinking was **some kind of werewolf**
- Worked on self with **hypnosis and positive imagery**
- Also avoided **walks in full moon**
- So far seems to be working

### How Pick Trades?

- Mostly by **trading system**
- Occasionally get impulsive flash and override system
- Fortunately, don't usually take big enough position to do lasting damage to portfolio

### Elements of Good Trading?

- Elements of good trading: (1) **cutting losses**, (2) **cutting losses**, (3) **cutting losses**
- If can follow these three rules, may have chance

### Handle Losing Streak?

- Handle by **trimming down activity**
- Just wait it out
- Trying to trade during losing streak **emotionally devastating**
- Trying to play "catch up" is **lethal**

### Since Primarily Systems Trader, Following System Imply No Change During Losing Periods?

- Incorporated logic into computer programs: **modulating trading activity** depending on market behavior
- Still, important decisions need to be made **outside mechanical system boundaries**
  - How maintain diversification for growing account when some positions at position limit or markets too thin
- **Psychologically**: tend to alter activity depending on performance
- Tend to be **more aggressive** after winning, **less so** after losses
- In contrast, costly tendency: **get emotional over loss**, then try to get even with **overly large position**

### Self-Taught or Did Another Trader Teach Worthwhile Lessons?

- **Self-taught trader** continually studying both self and other traders

### Decide Exit Before Entry?

- Set **protective stops** at same time enter trade
- Normally move stops in to lock in profit as trend continues
- Sometimes take profits when market gets wild
- Usually doesn't get out any better than waiting for stops to close in, but **cuts down volatility** of portfolio, which helps calm nerves
- **Losing position aggravating**, whereas **losing nerve devastating**

### Maximum Percentage of Equity Risk on Individual Trade?

- Intend to risk **below 5%** on trade, allowing for poor executions
- Occasionally taken losses above that when major news caused thin market to jump through stops

### Single Worst "Thin Market" Loss?

- All markets too thin when want to get out of bad position in hurry
- Most markets occasionally moved rapidly against due to surprise news
- As soon as news digested, market thickens up again at new level
- During **big sugar bull market** when prices moved from 10 cents to 40 cents, carrying thousands of contracts, gave up **several cents** getting out of position
- [Each cent in sugar = **$1,120 per contract**]

### Very Few Traders Enjoyed Spectacular Success—What Makes Different?

- Feel success comes from **love of markets**
- Not casual trader—**it is my life**
- Have **passion for trading**
- Not merely hobby or even career choice
- **No question this is what supposed to do with life**

### Trading Rules You Live By?

**a.** Cut losses
**b.** Ride winners
**c.** Keep bets small
**d.** Follow the rules without question
**e.** Know when to break the rules

### Last Two Rules Contradictory—Which Believe: Follow Rules or Know When to Break?

- Believe both
- **Mostly follow rules**
- As keep studying markets, sometimes find new rule which breaks and replaces previous rule
- Sometimes get to **personal breakpoint**—just get out of markets altogether, take vacation until feel ready to follow rules again
- Perhaps some day will have more explicit rule for breaking rules
- Don't think traders can follow rules very long unless **reflect own trading style**
- Eventually **breaking point reached**, trader has to quit or change or find new set of rules can follow
- Seems part of **process of evolution and growth** of trader

### How Important to Trading Success: Varying Size of Bet?

- Might be good idea depending on reason for doing so
- Consider: if had successful modification policy (say **"M"** for changing system **"S"**), might be better off just trading **"M"**

<!-- pp. 151-170 -->

## Ed Seykota Interview (Continued)

### On Gut Feel and Intuition

- **Gut feel** is important but can be deceptive — may reflect subconscious analysis or just wishful thinking
- Use meditation and reflection to distinguish true **intuition** from "into wishing"
- If gut feeling persists after reflection, may be valuable subconscious information
- Otherwise, likely a dangerous sublimation of desire for excitement rather than market reality

### Worst Trading Year: 1980

- **1980** was one of Seykota's worst years — bull markets ended but he kept buying dips
- Markets kept breaking; never experienced major bear market before
- Continued trading despite system being largely out due to volatility
- Tried picking tops/bottoms in overbought/oversold markets — markets kept going
- Eventually recognized futility of approach and quit trading temporarily

### Advice for Average Traders

- Find a superior trader to manage money, then pursue what you really love
- Most people would be better off not trading themselves

### On Chart Reading and Technical Analysis

- **Trend following** is a subset of charting
- Charting like surfing — need to understand physics of tides, resonance, fluid dynamics
- Must sense when a wave is happening and have drive to act at the right time

### October 1987 Crash

- Made money on crash day, for the month, and for the year
- Lost money day after crash (was short interest rate markets)
- Most trend traders likely out or short stocks/indexes during crash

### Markets and Professional Participation

- Markets remain the same despite greater professional participation
- "Markets keep changing — just like they did then"

### Trading Size and Difficulty

- Larger size makes trading both harder and easier
- **Harder**: difficult to move positions without moving market
- **Easier**: more access to competent support people — experienced brokers, team members, old-timers who can smell beginnings/endings of major moves

### Support Systems

- Team of experienced brokers with professional attitudes
- Experienced traders valuable for sharing joys and sorrows
- Old-timers can detect early signs of major market moves
- Support from friends, associates, family

### Outside Advisory Services

- Tracks many advisers through business press and brokers
- Services usually break even until they start to gloat — then headed for trouble

### Market Letters

- Tend to lag market since they respond to demand for news about recent activity
- Often written by inexperienced traders or non-traders (beginning job in industry)
- **"Good traders trade. Good letter writers write letters."**

### Using Others' Opinions

- Usually ignores advice from traders who believe they're on a "sure thing"
- Old-timers who talk about "maybe there is a chance of so and so" often right and early

### Confidence in Trading

- Vacillates between "I can keep winning" and "I have just been lucky"
- Gets most confident right before major losing streak

### Price Patterns Across Markets

- Common patterns transcend individual market behavior
- Example: bond prices move like cockroaches crawling up/down wall
- When cockroach followers crowd in, no one left to take other side

### Stock Market Behavior

- Stock market behaves differently from all other markets
- Stock market also behaves differently from itself — patterns seldom repeat exactly
- Trying to understand markets is futile, like trying to understand music
- **"A lot of people would rather understand the market than make money."**

### Long-Term Macro Views

- **Inflation**: societies sweep away old order; all currencies eventually debased
- Example: one penny at time of Christ compounded at 3% — nobody has that amount now
- **Gold**: tends to be dug up, refined, buried again; geographical entropy decreases over time; projects trend toward central world gold stash
- All gold collected in vaults

### Talent vs. Work in Trading

- Great traders have special talent like musicians and athletes
- Great traders are ones absorbed by the talent — "the talent has them"
- Balance between talent and work unclear — doesn't know where one starts and other stops

### Role of Luck

- **Luck** plays enormous role
- Some people lucky to be born smart; others smarter and born lucky
- Acknowledges complexity but doesn't dismiss talent
- Talent can be discovered and developed if already present
- Some people natural musicians, painters, salesmen, analysts — trading talent may be difficult to acquire if not innate

### Trading and Personal Life

- Personal life integrated with trading life

### Joy of Winning vs. Pain of Losing

- Joy of winning and pain of losing right up there with pain of winning and joy of losing
- Also consider joy and pain of not participating
- Relative strengths of feelings increase with distance from commitment to being trader

### Jesse Livermore and Managing Winnings

- **Jesse Livermore**: famous early 20th century speculator who made and lost several fortunes
- Livermore's experience function of psychology, not asset location
- Used to lock winnings away then find key to get at them
- To emulate Livermore's experience: need to lock up winnings, overtrade, have wipeouts, fire up emotions with burning desire to "win it right back"
- This drama could be exciting but terribly expensive
- Alternative: keep bets small, systematically reduce risk during equity drawdowns for gentle financial and emotional touchdown

### Quote Machines

- Has no quote machine on desk
- Quote machine like slot machine — feed it all day long
- Gets price data after close each day

### Why Traders Fail

- **"Many are called and few are chosen"** — like baby turtles failing to reach maturity
- Society works by attraction of many; as they're culled out, good ones left, others released to find their calling
- Same true for other fields of pursuit

### Can Losing Traders Transform?

- Losing trader can do little to transform into winning trader
- Not going to want to transform — that's what winning traders do

### Psychology vs. Market Analysis

- **Psychology** motivates quality of analysis and puts it to use
- **"Psychology is the driver and analysis is the road map."**

### Identifying Winning Trader Personality

- Winning traders usually winning at whatever field they've been in for years
- Two traits:
  1. Loves to trade
  2. Loves to win

### Don't All Traders Want to Win?

- **"Win or lose, everybody gets what they want out of the market."**
- Some people seem to like to lose — they win by losing money

#### Example: The Cyclical Loser

- One trader gets in near start of every substantial bull move
- Works $10K up to about $250K in couple months
- Changes personality and loses it all back again
- Process repeats like clockwork
- Once traded with him but got out when his personality changed
- Doubled money while he wiped out as usual, even paid him management fee
- He couldn't help himself, wouldn't want to differently
- Gets excitement, martyrdom, sympathy, attention
- Possibly more comfortable relating to people on their financial plane
- **"On some level, I think he is really getting what he wants."**

#### Example: The Cancer Patient

- Doctor friend's story: cancer patient used condition to demand attention and dominate others
- Family arranged shot that would cure her
- She constantly found excuses to avoid shot, eventually avoided entirely
- Perhaps political position more important than life
- **Trading performance probably reflects priorities more than people admit**

### Traders Playing for More Than Profits

- Most flamboyant and interesting traders playing for more than profits alone — probably also excitement
- Best way to increase profits: **goal setting and visualizations** to align conscious and subconscious with making profits
- Uses combination of hypnosis, breathing, pacing, visualization, gestalt, massage to work with traders
- Traders usually either (1) get much more successful, or (2) realize they didn't really want to be traders

### People Who Lack Skill But Want to Win

- Happy circumstance: when nature gives true burning desires, also gives means to satisfy them
- Those who want to win and lack skill can get someone with skill to help them

### Dreams and Market Direction

- Sometimes has dreams related to impending market direction
- Dreams tend to be very infrequent but often prove right
- Knows several people who claim market insights during dreams
- **Function of dreams**: reconcile information and feelings conscious mind finds intractable

#### Silver Dream Example

- Once told friends expected silver to keep going up
- When it went down, ignored signs and tried to tell self it was temporary correction
- Stood to lose face and money, couldn't afford to be wrong
- Had dreams of being in big, shiny, silver aircraft that stalled out and started going down toward inevitable crash
- Eventually dumped silver position, even went short, dreams stopped

### Judging Success

- Doesn't judge success, celebrates it
- **"Success has to do with finding and following one's calling regardless of financial gain."**

### Interviewer's Commentary on Seykota

- Don't be fooled by humor — great deal of serious wisdom in pithy replies
- Most striking comment: **"Everybody gets what they want out of the market."**
- Initially seemed cute, then realized deadly serious
- Implies all losers want to lose and all winners who fall short of goals fulfilling some inner need for constrained success
- Difficult proposition to swallow
- Respect for Seykota's knowledge forces consideration of provocative concept

---

## Chapter: Larry Hite — Respecting Risk

### Background and Early Career

- **Larry Hite** took circuitous path to Wall Street
- College course sparked interest in financial markets
- Inauspicious academic performance
- Went through string of odd jobs, never holding any very long
- Drifted into dual career as **actor and screenwriter**
- No major successes but managed to support himself and enjoyed work
- One movie script optioned so often began viewing it as steady income source

### First Exposure to Markets

- Heard **H.L. Hunt** on radio describing buying cheap oil options
- Gave opportunity for occasional windfall profits with minimal risk
- Same night met **Brian Epstein** (Beatles manager) at party
- Two ideas fused: rock promoter with potential for big money with minimal investment
- Landed few record contracts but none reached stardom
- Limited success but earned satisfactory living in self-employed position

### Transition to Finance

- Real interest remained financial markets
- **"You often hear about people working on Wall Street to become screenwriters. I may be the only person who ever worked as an actor and a scriptwriter to pay for my Wall Street career."**
- 1968: finally decided to pursue primary interest
- Fascinated with futures markets but didn't know how to break in
- Began as stockbroker
- Several years later became full-time commodities broker

### Formation of Mint Investment Management

- More than decade passed before taking initial steps toward **Mint Investment Management Company**
- Realized trading ideas needed rigorous scientific testing
- Offered partnership but no immediate pay
- Enlisted **Peter Matthews** (Ph.D. in statistics)
- One year later hired **Michael Delman** (designer of computer systems for defense electronics firm)
- Matthews and Delman brought ideas but more significantly provided mathematical proof Hite's concepts were statistically sound
- Emphasizes Mint's success wouldn't have been possible without Matthews and Delman

### Mint's Philosophy and Performance

- Objective: never make largest percentage return
- Philosophy: aim for best growth rate consistent with extremely rigorous risk management
- **Return relative to risk** is what really shines
- April 1981 through mid-1988: average annual compounded return over 30%
- Consistency most impressive: annual returns ranged from worst +13% to best +60%
- Largest loss in any six-month period: only 15%
- Under 1% in any twelve-month period (not just calendar years)

### Growth Under Management

- Stellar performance resulted in spectacular equity growth
- April 1981: began trading with $2 million
- Mid-1988: manage over $800 million
- No evidence surge of money under management had deleterious effect on performance
- Believes Mint can ultimately manage **$2 billion** — unprecedentedly large sum for futures fund

### Interview Setting

- Conducted over lunch at **Windows of the World** atop New York's World Trade Center
- Day blanketed with clouds
- Took hint when last ones left in restaurant, finished in Hite's office

---

## Larry Hite Interview

### Getting Interested in Markets

- College business course with professor with trenchant sense of humor
- Professor worked as bank examiner
- After audit, jokingly told bank president "Got you!" — man had heart attack on spot
- Next audit found bank president embezzled $75,000
- Professor reviewing financial instruments in class: stocks, bonds, etc.
- Then said: **"Now we come to the craziest market of all — commodities. These people trade on only 5 percent margin — and most of them borrow that."**
- Whole class laughed except Hite
- Idea of trading on 5% margin made perfect sense

### First Involvement in Financial Markets

- Not until many years later
- Rock promoter at time
- One weekend: three separate shootings in clubs where groups worked
- Decided opportune time to change careers and pursue true interest — financial markets
- Really interested in futures but didn't know how to get job
- Decided to start as stockbroker

#### Old-Line Wall Street Firm Interview

- First interview with very old-line Wall Street firm
- Offices made you feel should speak in hushed tones
- Interviewer pompous, refined voice, talks with teeth together, lives in Connecticut
- Tells Hite: **"We only buy blue chip for our clients."**

#### Learning About "Blue Chip"

- Unfamiliar with term "blue chip" but sounded odd in context of staid investment firm
- After interview looked up derivation
- Origin: color of most expensive chip in Monte Carlo
- Said to himself: **"Aha, now I know what this game is all about — gambling."**
- Threw away copy of **Graham and Dodd** (*Principles of Security Analysis* — considered "bible" of stock market analysis)
- Bought book called **Beat the Dealer**
- Came away with idea: successful investment matter of odds
- If you could compute odds, could find and test methods that could beat market

### Belief in Developing Winning Methods

- Didn't understand it all then but came to realize **markets are inefficient**
- Friend who is economist tried explaining markets are efficient (as if talking to child)
- Noticed everyone who ever told him markets are efficient is poor
- Argued: if I could develop winning system on computer, so could others, would all cancel each other out

#### What's Wrong With Efficient Market Argument?

- **People develop systems and make mistakes**
- Some alter system or jump system to system as each has losing period
- Others unable to resist second-guessing trading signals
- At money management conferences, always hears: "My system worked great, but I just didn't take the gold trade, and that would have been my biggest winner."

#### People Don't Change

- Very important message: **People don't change**
- Why whole game works
- **1637**: tulips in Holland traded for 5,500 florins then crashed to 50 (99% loss)
- Might say trading relatively new, people primitive, capitalism in infancy — today more sophisticated
- **1929**: find stock like **Air Reduction** — traded high of $233, after crash fell to $31 (87% decline)
- Might say Roaring '20s crazy times but now things different
- **1961**: **Texas Instruments** trading at $207, eventually dropped to $49 (77% decline)
- Think we've gotten more sophisticated in 1980s? Look at **silver prices**: 1980 peak $50, subsequently fell to $5 (90% decline)

#### The Edge From Rigorous Testing

- **Because people are the same**, if use sufficiently rigorous methods to avoid hindsight, can test system and see how would have done in past
- Get fairly good idea how system will perform in future
- **That is our edge**

### Can Markets Change Making Future Different From Past?

- Markets may change but people won't
- Still in testing stage before actually managing money
- Partner **Michael Delman** came up with concept of using **holding periods** as measure of system performance
- Evaluating systems solely on calendar year very arbitrary
- What you really want to know: odds for profitable performance in holding period of any length
- In simulations, **Peter** determined:
  - 90% of all six-month holding periods profitable
  - 97% of twelve-month periods profitable
  - 100% of eighteen-month periods profitable
- After over seven years actual trading, numbers turned out: 90%, 99%, 100%

#### Confidence in Evaluation Process

- Very confident of future validity
- Works for them: fellow who used to be colonel in British army
- Service specialty: **dismantling bombs** all over world
- Asked: "How did you do it?"
- **"There are different styles of bombs; a bomb in Malaysia is different from a bomb in Middle East. You go there and see what kind of bomb it is and take it apart."**
- Asked: "What happens when you come across bomb you don't know?"
- Looks in eye and says: **"You record your first impression and hope it is not your last."**

#### Fed Policy Change Example

- Came into office one day and found steel-nerved individual virtually on brink of tears
- Asked what was wrong
- Fed made major policy change dramatically reversing major market trends
- Overnight fund (started $10, risen to nearly $15) fallen back under $12 just after opening major Swiss bank account
- Told him: **"Get them on the phone."**
- He asked "What?" somewhat confused
- Repeated [speaking slowly and emphatically]: **"G-e-t t-h-e-m o-n t-h-e p-h-o-n-e."**

#### Broker Lesson

- When broker, boss taught: if you don't call client when losing money, someone else will
- To be honest, when broker did same thing
- When called prospects complaining about broker would say: **"Oh, how could he put you in that trade?"**

#### Handling the Crisis

- Got account on phone, explained simulations show this type of event occurs once every few years
- Confident in nine months fund will be back to new high
- **"In fact, I have just borrowed some money to add to my own investment in the fund."**
- Asked in surprised tone: **"You really did that?"**
- Assured him that I did
- Account doubled up on investment, fund immediately shot straight up
- Today that account one of biggest clients

#### Why So Confident?

- **Knew what those systems were about**
- What makes business so fabulous: while may not know what will happen tomorrow, can have very good idea what will happen over long run

#### Insurance Business Analogy

- Insurance business provides perfect analogy
- Take one sixty-year-old guy: absolutely no idea odds he'll be alive one year later
- Take 100,000 sixty-year-olds: can get excellent estimate how many alive one year later
- **We do same thing; let law of large numbers work for us**
- **In sense, we are trading actuaries**

### Trading by System vs. Excitement

- Friend went broke trading futures, can't understand how Hite trades by computerized system religiously
- Were playing tennis one day, asked: **"Larry, how can you trade the way you do; isn't it boring?"**
- Told him: **"I don't trade for excitement; I trade to win."**
- May be very dull but also very lucrative
- When get together with other traders exchanging war stories about different trades, have nothing to say
- **To me, all our trades are the same**

### What Makes Mint Different — Superior Return/Risk Ratios

- Many money managers use trend-following systems
- Quite a few don't second-guess own systems
- **What makes Mint different? How achieved return/risk ratios far above industry average?**

#### Key Lesson: "We Know That We Don't Know"

- **Because we know that we don't know**
- No matter what information have, no matter what doing, can be wrong
- Friend who amassed fortune over $100 million taught two basic lessons:
  1. **If you never bet your lifestyle, from trading standpoint, nothing bad will ever happen to you**
  2. **If you know what worst possible outcome is, it gives you tremendous freedom**
- Truth: while can't quantify reward, **you can quantify risk**

#### Coffee Trader Example

- One of world's largest coffee traders invited to house in London
- Walked into library: had just about every book ever written on power
- Invited to one of finest restaurants ever been to
- At dinner asked: **"Larry, how can you know more about coffee than me? I am largest trader in world. I know where boats are; I know the ministers."**
- Answered: **"You are right, I don't know anything about coffee. In fact, I don't even drink it."**
- **"How do you trade it then?"**
- Told him: **"I just look at the risk."**
- Great meal lasted several hours
- Five times he asked what I did, five times told him managed risk
- Three months later heard blown $100 million in coffee market
- Obviously didn't get message
- Want to know something? **He does know more about coffee than I do. But point is, he didn't look at the risk.**

### Mint's First Rule: Risk Management

- **Very first rule we live by at Mint: Never risk more than 1 percent of total equity on any trade**
- By only risking 1%, indifferent to any individual trade
- Keeping risk small and constant absolutely critical
- Example: one manager had large account that withdrew half money trading
- Instead of cutting position size in half, kept trading same number of contracts
- Eventually half of original money became 10% of money
- **Risk is no-fooling-around game; it does not allow for mistakes**
- If you do not manage risk, eventually they will carry you out

### Four Key Principles of Risk Management at Mint

#### 1. Always Follow Trends, Never Deviate

- Always follow trends and never deviate from methods
- Written agreement none of us can ever countermand system
- Trades all the same
- **Reason we have never had bad trade at Mint**
- Four kinds of trades/bets: good bets, bad bets, winning bets, losing bets
- Most people think losing trade was bad bet
- **Absolutely wrong**
- Can lose money even on good bet
- If odds 50/50 and payoff $2 versus $1 risk, that's good bet even if you lose
- Important point: **if you do enough of those trades or bets, eventually you have to come out ahead**

#### 2. Risk Limited to 1% Per Trade

- Maximum risk on each trade limited to 1% of total equity

#### 3. Diversify Extensively

- Diversify in two ways:
  1. **Probably trade more markets worldwide than any other money manager**
  2. **Don't just use single best system** — use lots of different systems ranging from short term to long term
- Some of these systems may not be good by themselves but don't care — that's not what they're there for
- Provide balance

#### 4. Track Volatility

- When volatility of market becomes so great that adversely skews expected return/risk ratio, will stop trading that market

### Three-Light System for Trading Signals

- Approach has three lights determining acceptance of trading signals
- **Green light**: take all signals
- **Yellow light**: liquidate existing position on signal but won't put on new position
- **Red light**: liquidate existing positions automatically, do not take any new positions

#### Coffee 1986 Example

- 1986: coffee went from $1.30 to $2.80 and back to $1.00
- Got out of long positions on way up at $1.70
- Didn't trade market for rest of price climb and subsequent collapse
- While may have lost some additional profits, being out of markets like that one of ways able to achieve rigid risk control

### Key Difference: Defining When Not to Play

- One of key differences between Mint and other trend-following managers: **developed way of defining when not to play**
- In any situation or game, can define positional advantage for any player — even weakest one
- In trading, can define three categories: trade, floor, speculator
- **Trade** has best product knowledge and best ways of getting out of positions (e.g., offset risk in futures with cash market)
- **Floor** has advantage of speed — can never be faster than floor
- **Speculator** doesn't have product knowledge or speed, but has advantage of **not having to play**
- **Speculator can choose to only bet when odds in his favor**
- **That is an important positional advantage**

### Volatility Filter Details

- **Anywhere from ten to 100 days of past data** used to determine volatility filter
- Deliberately ambiguous — look at different time windows in that range

### 1% Stop-Loss Rule and Getting Back In

- Fully understand logic of 1% stop-loss
- **Once stopped out without system providing opposite signal, what gets you back into trade if market reverses to original direction? Isn't it possible could get stopped out on moderate reaction and miss subsequent major move?**
- **If market makes new high, we get back in**

### Wide Trading Ranges and Whipsaws

- **Suppose market goes into wide trading range, might not get continuously whipped between being stopped out and reentering position at new highs?**
- **That happens, but not enough to be problem**

### Personal Events Ingraining Respect for Risk

#### Pork Belly Experience

- When first involved in commodities, noticed if bought pork bellies in September and sold before July, almost always made profit
- Formed fund with group of friends, put on trade
- Worked, doubled money, felt like genius
- Had friend who followed corn market, didn't know anything about corn, only knew about pork bellies
- Talked into buying new crop corn and selling old crop
- Supposed to be relatively safe trade — offsetting long position in one contract month with short position in another month
- Really loaded up
- Shortly thereafter government released surprising crop estimate
- In response, month was long went limit-down and month short went limit-up

#### The Prayer on the Stairway

- In such despair, remember walking out to stairway and literally getting down on knees
- Said out loud: **"Dear God, I don't care how much I lose, but please don't let the account go into a debit."**
- At time working for sophisticated international firm
- Just as making providential plea, Swiss banker came walking down staircase
- To this day still wonder what he must have thought

### Other Traumatic Risk Experiences

- Not for self but continually witnessed examples of other people being ruined by failure to respect risk
- **If you don't take hard look at risk, it will take you**

#### Motorcycle Lesson

- When kid got first motorcycle, had older friend who would always get into fights
- Told me: **"Larry, when you are on a motorcycle, never argue with a car. You will lose."**
- Same lesson applies to trading: **If you argue with the market, you will lose**

#### Hunt Brothers Example

- **Hunt brothers** perfect example
- Somebody once asked: **"How could the Hunts lose? They were worth billions."**
- If you have billion dollars and buy $20 billion worth of silver — making these numbers up for sake of example — in exactly same risk position as guy with $1,000 who owns $20,000 worth of silver

#### Arbitrageur Friend's Story

- Good friend started from very humble beginnings; father was sanitation man
- Very bright guy, got into option arbitrage
- Extremely good at it, made fortune
- Remember visiting him at palatial estate bought in England
- May have been great arbitrageur but turned out to be bad trader
- Developed trading system that made money
- One day said: **"I am not taking the sell signal in gold; it doesn't look right to me. Besides, almost 50 percent of signals are wrong anyway."**
- Not only didn't take sell signal, actually wound up going long
- Sure enough market went down
- Told him **"Get out!"** but insisted **"The market will come back."**
- Didn't get out, lost mansion and everything else
- Now lives in rented flat on street with hundred other ticky-tacky houses
- To this day still remember name of estate: **"Beverly."**
- Still one of best friends, loss of huge house had enormous emotional impact
- **He had it and lost it all! And all because of one trade**
- Irony: if followed his system, would have made fortune on that trade

#### Cousin's Option Trading Story

- Cousin turned $5,000 into $100,000 in option market
- One day asked how did you do it?
- Answered: **"It is very easy. I buy an option and if it goes up, I stay in, but if it goes down, I don't get out until I am at least even."**
- Told him: **"Look, I trade for a living, and I can tell you that strategy is just not going to work in the long run."**
- Said: **"Larry, don't worry, it doesn't have to work in the long run, just till I make a million. I know what I am doing. I just never take a loss."**
- Said: **"OK..."**

##### The Merrill Lynch Options Disaster

- Next trade buys $90,000 worth of Merrill Lynch options
- This time goes down, and down, and down
- Talk to him about one month later, tells me in debt for $10,000
- Said: **"Wait a minute. You had $100,000 and you bought $90,000 in options. That should still leave you with $10,000, even after they expired worthless. How could you have deficit of $10,000?"**
- Said: **"I originally bought the options at $4½. When the price went down to $1, I figured out that if I bought another 20,000, all it had to do was go back to $¾ for me to break even. So I went to the bank and borrowed $10,000."**
- **Respect for risk not just matter of trading; applies to any type of business decision**
- Once worked for firm where company president hired option trader who was brilliant but not stable
- One day option trader disappeared leaving firm stuck with losing position
- President not trader, sought advice
- **"Larry, what do you think I should do?"**
- Told him: **"Just get out of the position."**
- Instead decided to hold on to trade
- Loss got little worse but then market came back, liquidated position at small profit

#### Finding Another Job

- After incident told friend who worked at same firm: **"Bob, we are going to have to find another job."**
- **"Why?"** he asked
- Answered: **"We work for a man who has just found himself in the middle of a mine field, and what he did was close his eyes and walk through it. He now thinks that whenever you are in the middle of a mine field, the proper technique is to close your eyes and go forward."**
- Less than one year later same man had to liquidate huge **delta neutral spread position** in options
- Instead of just getting out, decided to get out of position one leg at a time
- By time he finished liquidating that position, **had gone through all of the firm's capital**

### Why People Lose Money Trading

- Sometimes because trades based on **personal bias** instead of statistical approach
- Example: regular panelist on "Wall Street Week" about sixty-five or seventy years old
- On show one day said lesson his father taught him was: **"Bonds are the cornerstone of your portfolio. Think about that! Since this man first got into the business, has seen interest rates go down only once out of every eight years."** [Bonds go up when interest rates decline]
- Obviously name "bonds" means lot more to him than reality

### Trading All Markets the Same Way

- **We don't trade markets, we trade money**
- **Mickey Quenington** (marketing director) once introduced to former chief executive of E.F. Man (firm to which Hite gave 50% ownership in management company in exchange for financial backing)
- Guy was tough, old Irishman
- Asked: **"How do you differentiate between gold and cocoa in your trading?"**
- Answered: **"They are both a 1 percent bet; they are the same to me."**
- Was outraged, practically shouted back: **"You mean to tell me that you don't see any difference between gold and cocoa?"**
- Think if wasn't for fact he liked Mickey so much, would have thrown out of office

#### London Times Interview

- Married very proper English woman always concerned family considers him bit crass
- Once interviewed by reporter from *London Times*
- Asked what thought about future direction of London cocoa market
- Told him: **"Frankly, I don't see markets; I see risks, rewards, and money."**
- Was last person quoted in article
- Finished by saying: **"Mr. Hite doesn't care about the cocoa market, all he cares about is money."**
- Wife read article and said: **"Great. Now I'll never be able to go home; this will just prove to my family that they were right about you all along."**

### Don't Believe in Optimization

- **Assume if you trade all markets same, probably don't believe in optimization**
- [Optimization: testing many variations of system for past, then selecting best-performing version for actual trading. Problem: link between past and future performance often very rough one]
- Absolutely
- Saying here: **"It is incredible how rich you can get by not being perfect."**
- Not looking for optimum method; looking for hardiest method
- Anyone can sit down and devise perfect system for past

### Overrated Technical Indicators

- **Overbought/oversold indicators**
- None of them seem to prove out in testing

### Particularly Valuable Indicators

- Although don't really trade off them, two come to mind:
  1. **If market doesn't respond to important news in way it should**, telling you something very important
     - Example: when news of Iraq-Iran war first came out over newswire, gold only able to move up $1
     - Said to self: **"A Middle East war has just broken out and the best the gold market can do is go up $1; it has to be a great sale."**
     - Market broke sharply after that
  2. Something **Ed Seykota** taught: **When market makes historic high, it is telling you something**
     - No matter how many people tell you why market shouldn't be that high, or why nothing has changed, mere fact that price is at new high tells you something has changed

### Other Lessons From Ed Seykota

- Ed Seykota actually explained philosophy one day:
- **"You can risk 1 percent of your capital, you can risk 5 percent, or you can risk 10 percent, but you better realize that the more you risk, the more volatile the results are going to be."**
- And he was absolutely right

### Other Teachers Besides Partners

- Absolutely
- **Jack Boyd** hired as broker/analyst
- Having read that **Handy and Harman** said in annual report that silver stocks totaled either three billion or seven billion ounces, wrote report on silver market saying: **"According to Handy and Harman, there is either twice as much silver as some people think or less than half."**
- That report went over very big with Jack and helped land job
- Jack had been putting out trading recommendations for firm for many years
- Found that if followed all his recommendations, would have made money in every year
- Finally asked Jack how he did it
- Have to picture Jack was six foot-four
- Said: **"Larry, if you want to know where a market is going, all you have to do is this."**
- Threw charts on floor and jumped up on desk
- Said: **"Look at it, it will tell you!"**

### Getting Big Picture Perspective

- **Right, because I don't know of too many people who get rich by taking small profits**
- Working with Boyd extremely important
- From time met him, knew his approach was right way to do it
- In other words, knew that **if you traded across the board, controlled your risk, and went with the trend, it just had to work**
- Could see it absolutely clearly

### Final Words

- Have two basic rules about winning in trading as well as in life:
  1. **If you don't bet, you can't win**
  2. **If you lose all your chips, you can't bet**

---

## Summary Commentary on Larry Hite

Two basic elements to Hite's trading philosophy:

1. **Markets are inefficient** — contrary to many academics' opinion
   - If can develop method placing odds in your favor (and it doesn't have to be by very much), *you can* win

2. **Effective method necessary but not sufficient condition to win**
   - To survive and thrive at trading, must also **respect market risk**
   - If don't, sooner or later it will get you

### Hite's Four Principles of Risk Control:

**1. System never trades counter to market trend**
- No exceptions, always follows system

**2. Maximum risk on each trade limited to 1% of total equity**

**3. Diversification carried to extreme**
- System really combination of many different systems
- Selected not only for individual performance but also for degree of lack of correlation with other selected systems
- Mint trades in an extraordinarily wide range of markets worldwide

**4. Track volatility**
- When volatility becomes so great that adversely skews expected return/risk ratio, will stop trading that market

Hite's rigorous risk control and extreme diversification allow Mint to achieve spectacular return/risk ratios — far superior to industry average.
