## Part II: Mostly Stocks

## Michael Steinhardt: The Concept of Variant Perception

### Background and Track Record

**Michael Steinhardt** began his market interest at age thirteen when his father gifted him 200 shares, watching ticker tape in brokerage offices while friends played stickball. Graduated **Wharton School** at nineteen in 1960, worked as research assistant and financial journalist before founding **Steinhardt, Fine and Berkowitz** (later **Steinhardt Partners**) in 1967.

- Firm achieved **30% compounded annual growth** over twenty-one years (under 25% after 20% profit incentive fee)
- **S&P 500** managed only 8.9% compounded annual growth during same period
- $1,000 invested at inception in 1967 grew to **over $93,000** by Spring 1988 (after fees)
- Same $1,000 in S&P basket would have grown to only $6,400
- Only **two losing years** in twenty-one years, both losses under 2% before profit incentive adjustments

### Trading Philosophy Core Principles

**Variant perception** — Steinhardt develops perceptions at variance with general market view and plays those until they are no longer variant.

> "I try to develop perceptions that I believe are at variance with the general market view. I will play those variant perceptions until I feel they are no longer so."

**Distinction between trading and investing**:
- Traders go short as readily as long; investors (like mutual fund managers) stay 70% invested minimum, always long
- Traders focus on market direction; investors focus on picking best stocks
- No value judgment between the two — just different thematic focus

**Core trading elements**:
- Willing to be contrarian — shorts stocks at favorites backed by institutional enthusiasm
- Tends to short early, often starting with losses
- Willing to get "in the way of danger" to make money in markets
- No stop-loss orders, no rules about buying on weakness/strength
- No breakouts or breakdowns
- **Does not use charts** — finds them completely unhelpful

### Variant Perception Examples

**Genentech short** (held for year and a half at interview time):
- Lost money for months maintaining position
- Variant perception: **TPA** (their drug) will be minor drug in 1-2 years, supplanted by more effective, cheaper alternatives
- Entire company based on this one drug
- If correct, company earning 20-30 cents/share selling under $10
- Stock at $27 in June 1988, down from high of $65 (by late November fell to $15)
- Market perception: Genentech first-class biotech company producing many revolutionary products
- Steinhardt stays short as long as his view remains variant

**Tobacco stocks short** (one month before interview):
- Reasoning: if plaintiffs won case, stocks down a lot; if lost, wouldn't rise much (tobacco companies never lost case before)
- Variant perception example — asymmetric payoff
- After Liggett Group verdict, Steinhardt indifferent to whether market reacts — only cared if fundamental reason remained valid
- Would cover immediately once news out (variant perception collapsed)

### Position Management and Psychology

**Holding losing positions**:
- As long as fundamentals (as perceived) unchanged, will hang tough regardless of how much position goes against him
- If "triple horrible," might trade around position to reduce pressure temporarily
- Periodically buys when short to separate fundamental view from short-term fervor
- Example: **Time Inc.** short — stock up 10% after entry, Steinhardt questions traders regularly about why position not acting as expected

**No rigid rules**:
- Knows exactly where getting out before entering, but not necessarily a risk control rule
- No stops or objectives — doesn't think in those terms
- Charts "leave me blank" — ignores price history, only watches stocks closely for sense of price levels and ranges
- Path from $10 to $40 makes no difference to him

**When analysis wrong**:
- Reviews portfolio six times daily
- Talks to people only when things "lousy" or stocks not acting right
- Acts as "negative monitor" — questions positions when they don't behave as expected
- If can't explain market action, covers anyway (superficial or serious explanation usually available)

### Major Trading Campaigns

**1973-1974 bear market**:
- Net short during enormous market decline
- Made substantial gains

**1981-1982 treasury bond trade**:
- Went long debt markets in 1981, held **two and a half years**
- Started buying spring 1981, treasuries bottomed **September 30, 1981**
- Rates moved against him first half year (painful given position size)
- **Summer 1981** worst experience of business life — thoughtful investors very unhappy with what he was doing
- Never came close to liquidating or decreasing position despite self-doubt
- Reasoning: higher inflation rates would lead to higher interest rates, slowing economy
- With 14% available in long-term treasuries, stocks had to sell much lower to compete
- Clear unidirectional message — timing the turn was only issue
- **Contrarian mentality**: early 1980s interest rates presented potentially great opportunity
- Fed would ease once business ran into trouble; already seen topping in inflation rate
- **Leveraged position**: at one point had 3-4 times firm's capital in five-year maturities
- Treasuries allow 98% financing depending on maturity — no real constraint like stock margin

### October 1987 Crash

**Spring 1987**: wrote letter to investors reducing market exposure, cautious about overvaluation
- Identified unique combination: substantial equity reduction coinciding with more liberal debt attitude
- Banks comfortable lending, junk bond market good, corporate managers repurchasing shares
- Created unusual upward bias to equity prices
- Question: what would change this? Answer: recession
- Government lacked flexibility to fight recession (deviated from countercyclical fiscal policy during expansion)

**Fall 1987**: economy strengthening (not weakening) — Fed tightened
- Real world after October 19 crash: almost nothing happened
- **Baker criticism of Germany** merely disagreement on currency valuation
- Problem internal to market — market mechanism unable to handle institutional changes
- Elements of stability (individual investor, specialist system) greatly reduced
- 1980s creations (**portfolio insurance**, **program trading**, **global asset allocation**) exerted unidirectional impact

**October 19 positioning**:
- Came in 80-90% net long, **increased exposure during the day**
- Contrarian trade: enormous moves usually right to take opposite view
- Emotionalism and extremism in the move — maintaining distance from emotion profitable
- Buying on any 300-, 400-, 500-point down day is standard contrarian response

**Post-crash**:
- Reduced position throughout next two months
- Magnitude of decline and confidence change affected him
- Better to sit back and rethink with cash than try to hang in
- Underestimated impact of forces diminishing market stability
- Down **over 20% for October**

### Hedge Fund Concept

**Original A.W. Jones hedge fund concept**:
- Money managers cannot forecast stock market trends (functions of variables beyond consistent anticipation)
- Can make accurate judgments on which companies doing well vs. poorly
- Balance long positions in strong stocks with short positions in weak stocks — eliminates market risk
- Original concept emphasized **stock-picking ability**

**Modern hedge fund reality**:
- Term now misnomer — refers to limited partnership with performance-based general partner compensation
- Manager has much more **flexibility** than traditional money manager
- Can short stocks, use options, futures, etc.
- Variations cover very wide continuum
- In most hedge funds: "Where is the hedge?"

**History of hedge funds**:
- 1960s flexibility attracted young, aggressive entrepreneurs
- Allowed starting own business early when not otherwise possible
- Great stocks with wonderful stories, terrific growth
- Practitioners not theoretical hedgers — wanted flexibility to be long lots of stock
- Had shorting flexibility but didn't use it seriously
- Name had connotation of shorting, anti-American ring — embarrassing
- Started using term "private partnership" instead

**Why pure hedge fund concept no longer practiced**:
- Very restricting approach
- Being dollar long and dollar short in related entities (e.g., Ford vs. General Motors) uses dollars ineffectively
- Both affected by same macroeconomic factors
- Might realize only 10% difference over a year even if right
- **Steinhardt Partners**: actively uses shorts, averages about **40% net long** over twenty-one years
- Range: 15-20% net short to over 100% net long
- Flexibility to shift market exposure is "exceptionally meaningful—sometimes perhaps too meaningful"

### Market Direction vs. Stock Selection

Steinhardt's approach integrates both but leans toward market direction:
- Being right on market direction provides slight edge (51% vs. 50%)
- Not big advantage like being right 80% of time
- **No set pattern** of successful activity over twenty-one years
- Some years did well on strength of well-selected stocks
- Other years did exceptionally well being right side of market
- Example: 1973-1974 net short during enormous decline
- Other periods: bulk of money made in bonds
- Message: no formula for success in this racket
- Anyone thinking they can formulate success formula is deluding themselves
- Changes too quickly — formula's own success carries weight of inevitable failure

### Evolution of Stock Trading (1960s to 1980s)

**Early days (pre-1975)**:
- Minimal intellectual power on trading desks
- Institutional traders typically kids from Brooklyn with little education, discretion, or money
- "Taking candy from a baby"
- **Penn Central example**: bought 700,000 shares at 6⅛ (stock in Chapter 11, last trade at 7)
- Seller didn't check the board, sold dollar under last trade
- Turned around and sold 700,000 shares at 6⅞
- Made half million dollars in twelve seconds

**Post-consolidated tape (1975)**:
- Much more competition
- Trading desk people much brighter
- Retail buyers/sellers diminished greatly
- Market became **institutionalized**

**Short-term orientation shift**:
- World became much more short-term oriented
- Former investors now traders
- Institutions define themselves as enterprises seeking highest rate of return (vs. long-term investors)
- Confidence in predicting secular trends greatly diminished
- 1967: typical to see McDonald's per-share earnings estimated to year 2000
- Belief companies growing in stable, predictable way — belief in America and steady growth
- Today: stocks don't lend themselves to same secular analysis
- Implication: secular growth trend analysis not working in 1970s-1980s relates to trading question
- 1950s-1960s heroes: long-term investors
- Today's heroes: wise guys talking about capitalism but practicing short-term trading
- **Goldsmith example**: in Goodyear for seven months, made eight billion dollars (greenmail), left management

### Laws Enabling Short-Term Trading

**Justice Department reinterpretation** of takeover laws and definition of monopolistic behavior enabled actions previously forbidden.

### Advice for Laymen

> "Recognize that this is a very competitive business, and that when you decide to buy or sell a stock, you are competing with people who have

<!-- pp. 191-210 -->

## Michael Steinhardt (continued)

### Advice on Trading vs. Professional Management

- Professionals devote their lives to trading and are often on the opposite side of retail trades
- Novice traders need a compelling reason to expect superior returns beyond risk-free bonds
- If T-bonds yield 9-10% and T-bills 7-8%, stock returns must justify the incremental risk
- **Don't underestimate the difficulty of the game** — stocks don't automatically deliver higher returns just because they're riskier

### Elements of Good Trading

- Balance between **conviction** (following your ideas) and **flexibility** (recognizing mistakes)
- You will be wrong a considerable number of times — this is learned through experience
- **Respect for the person on the other side of the trade** — ask "Why does he want to sell? What does he know that I don't?"
- **Intellectual honesty** with yourself and others — all great traders are seekers of truth

### Steinhardt's Contrarian Approach

- Being contrarian requires **timing**, not just sentiment surveys
- Sentiment is bullish at tops and bearish at bottoms, but extreme readings also occur during extended trends
- Can't use formulaic approach — successful contrarian must filter out true opportunities
- **Flexibility** is key: equally comfortable going short or long, trading stocks, bonds, or futures
- Taking on large positions when perceiving major opportunities separates great traders from good ones

> "The more things you bring to the table—shorting, hedging, participation in bond markets, futures market trading, and so on—the better off you are."

### Conviction Under Pressure

- **Steinhardt's treasury note position (1981-1982)** — maintained large position through six-month interest rate climax
- Remained immune to market moves against him and psychological pressure from complaining investors
- His conviction enabled the transition from stock trader to treasuries trader
- **No absolute formulae or fixed patterns** — markets always changing, traders who seek fixed approaches will fail

## William O'Neil: The Art of Stock Selection

### Background

- **Unreserved optimist** about American economic system and possibilities
- Born in Oklahoma during Great Depression, raised in Texas
- Built dual fortunes as investor and businessman
- Started as stockbroker at **Hayden, Stone and Company** (1958)
- Developed investment strategy based on studying what worked

### Early Success (1962-1963)

- Pyramided profits from three exceptional back-to-back trades: short **Korvette**, long **Chrysler**, long **Syntex**
- Turned initial $5,000 into $200,000

### Business Ventures

- **1964**: Bought NYSE seat, formed **William O'Neil and Co.** institutional research brokerage
- Firm services 500+ institutional accounts and 28,000 individual subscribers to **Daily Graphs** charting service
- Database contains 120 statistics on 7,500 securities
- **1983**: Launched **Investor's Daily** in direct competition with Wall Street Journal
- Started with 30,000 press run vs. 2 million for WSJ
- By mid-1988: circulation expanded to 110,000, breakeven point of 200,000 subscribers seems achievable
- Target: 800,000 readers

### Published Work

- **1988**: Published *How to Make Money in Stocks* (McGraw-Hill)
- Best-selling investment book of the year
- Combines clarity, brevity, and very specific trading advice

### Investment Performance

- Averaged over 40% annual profit on stock investments over past ten years
- Big winners: Canadian oils (1970s), **Pic'n'Save**, **Price Co.** (late 1970s/early 1980s)
- Famous market calls: two full-page Wall Street Journal ads heralding bull markets (1978, February 1982)

## The CANSLIM Formula

### Origins

- **1959**: Studied **Dreyfus fund** (managed by **Jack Dreyfus**), which was doubling competitors' results
- Plotted every stock purchase on charts to identify patterns
- Discovery: Not some, but **every single stock had been bought when it went to a new high price**

### Core Insight

- **Buy stocks breaking out of broad bases and making new highs** — not stocks near their lows
- Avoid wasting months in stocks going nowhere
- Study past winners to find common characteristics **before** they became major successes

### CANSLIM Components

**C = Current Earnings Per Share**
- Best stocks showed 70% average increase in current quarter earnings over prior year **before** major advance
- **Quarterly EPS should increase at least 18-50% year-to-year**
- Individual and institutional investors commonly buy stocks with unchanged or lower earnings — "absolutely no reason for a stock to go up if current earnings are poor"

**A = Annual Earnings Per Share**
- Prior five-year average annual compounded earnings growth: **24%**
- Ideally, each year's EPS should increase over prior year
- Strong current earnings + high average earnings growth creates superb stocks
- **EPS rank** (published in *Investor's Daily*): combines recent two quarters with five-year average, compares to all stocks
- EPS rank of 95 = outperformed 95% of all companies

**N = New (Something New)**
- 95% of greatest winners had **new product/service, industry change, or new management**
- "New" also means **new high price**
- 98% of investors unwilling to buy at new highs — yet "what seems too high usually goes higher and what seems too low usually goes lower"

**S = Shares Outstanding (Supply)**
- 95% of best performers had **less than 25 million shares** during best performance period
- Average capitalization: 11.8 million shares (median only 4.6 million)
- Institutional investors handicap themselves by restricting purchases to large-cap companies, automatically eliminating best growth companies

**L = Leader or Laggard**
- 500 best-performing stocks (1953-1985) had average **relative strength of 87** before major price increase
- **Relative strength** measures stock's price performance vs. all other stocks over past 12 months
- Pick leading stocks (high relative strength above 80), avoid laggard stocks
- Example: relative strength of 80 = stock outperformed 80% of all others in past year

**I = Institutional Sponsorship**
- Leading stocks usually have institutional backing
- However, **excessive sponsorship is undesirable** — would create large selling if problems arise
- Most widely owned institutional stocks are often poor performers
- "By the time a company's performance is so obvious that almost all institutions own a stock, it is probably too late to buy"

**M = Market Direction**
- **Three out of four stocks follow market averages**
- Must learn to interpret price and volume daily for market top signals

### Market Timing

At any given time, **less than 2% of stocks fit CANSLIM formula** — deliberately restrictive to pick only the very best

> "If you were recruiting players for a baseball team, would you pick an entire lineup of .200 hitters, or would you try to get as many .300 hitters as possible?"

### Buying Timing

- Don't anticipate breakout from base — stock may never break out
- Can buy too soon or too late
- **Buy when least probability of loss** — at new high, stock usually won't drop more than 7% maximum
- Within base, stock can fluctuate 10-15%, easy to get shaken out
- **Buy at the breakout**, not during base formation

### High Relative Strength Risk

- High relative strength (80+) is good if stock just beginning to emerge from sound base
- **Don't buy stock already extended 10%+ beyond most recent price base** — vulnerable to sharp correction
- Key is not how high relative strength is, but **how far stock is extended beyond price base**

### Identifying Market Tops

**Two patterns:**
1. Average moves to new high on **low volume** — poor demand, rally vulnerable
2. Volume surges for several days with little/no upside price progress — distribution occurring on the way up

**Additional signals:**
- Leading stocks start breaking down
- **Federal Reserve discount rate** — after 2-3 rate increases, market runs into trouble
- **Advance/decline line** lags market averages, fails to penetrate prior peaks when averages make new highs — fewer stocks participating

### Short Selling

- Doesn't normally advise unless professional traders
- Only made significant profits on short side in two of last nine bear markets
- **Never sell short just because price looks too high**
- Short at the right time: after general market shows top signs
- Best pattern: stock breaks out on third/fourth base then fails, breaking down toward low end of previous base on increased volume
- After first serious price break below base, pullback attempts provide good short timing

### Unlimited Risk in Shorting

- **Never takes unlimited risk**
- Exit after first 6-7% loss
- Before selling short, decide cover price if loss occurs

### Risk Control Philosophy

> "My philosophy is that all stocks are bad. There are no good stocks unless they go up in price."

- If stock goes down instead, **cut losses fast**
- Secret to winning: can win even if right only half the time
- **Maximum 7% loss rule** on any stock purchase
- If stock drops 7% below purchase price, automatically sell at market — no hesitation

> "Letting losses run is the most serious mistake made by most investors."

- Without cutting-loss rule, can lose 70-80% in bear markets like 1973-1974
- Analogy: **Turkey trap story** by **Fred C. Kelly** (*Why You Win or Lose*)
  - Man rigs turkey trap — once door shuts, can't reopen without scaring away outside turkeys
  - Had 12 turkeys, then 11, then thought "maybe one more will return"
  - Ended empty-handed because couldn't give up idea that original turkeys would return
  - **Moral: "To reduce your stock market risk, stop counting turkeys"**

### Position Management

- Hold stock as long as it performs properly
- **Jesse Livermore**: "It is never thinking that makes big money, it's the sitting"
- Never sell exact top — ridiculous to regret if price continues higher after selling
- Goal: substantial profits, not upset about missing additional gains

### Conventional Wisdom Critique

**P/E Ratios**
- Very low correlation between P/E and best-performing stocks
- Best stocks had P/E ratios ranging from 10 to 50 at early emerging stage
- 1953-1985 average P/E: 20 for best performers vs. 15 for Dow Jones
- At expansion phase peak: average P/E approximately 45
- Mistake: buying solely because P/E looks cheap — usually good reason why P/E is low
- Personal example: bought **Northrop** at 4x earnings, watched it decline to 2x earnings
- Mistake: selling stocks with high P/E ratios
- 1962 example: investor complained **Xerox** overpriced at 50x earnings — Xerox went to $1,300 (adjusted)

**Dividends**
- **No correlation** between dividends and stock performance
- Higher dividends may weaken company — may need high interest rates to replace funds paid in dividends
- Naive to hold declining stocks because they pay dividends
- Example: 4% dividend with 25% stock decline = 21% net loss

**Overbought/Oversold Indicators**
- Rarely pays attention
- Once hired professional specializing in technical indicators
- During 1969 market break, professional said "too late to sell because indicators said market was very oversold"
- Once indicators were oversold, market break accelerated

**Diversification**
> "Diversification is a hedge for ignorance."

- Better to own few stocks and know them well
- Being selective increases chances of picking superior performers
- Can watch stocks more carefully, important for controlling risk

**Recommended portfolio size:**
- $5,000: 1-2 stocks
- $10,000: 3-4 stocks
- $25,000: 4-5 stocks
- $50,000: 5-6 stocks
- $100,000+: 6-7 stocks

### Public Misconceptions

**Charts**
- Most investors think charts are hocus-pocus
- Only 5-10% of investors understand charts
- Just as doctors use X-rays and EKGs, charts provide valuable information unobtainable easily otherwise
- Allow following huge number of stocks in organized manner

**Volume**
- When stock beginning to move into new high ground, volume should increase at least 50% over average daily volume in recent months
- High volume at key point = extraordinarily valuable tip-off
- Volume in reverse: during consolidation after advance, volume should dry up substantially — very little selling coming into market (constructive)

### Handling Losing Streaks

- After 5-6 straight losses, pull back to see if whole market going bad
- May be time to move into cash

### Mutual Funds

Surprisingly endorses mutual funds as "absolutely outstanding way to invest"

> "I believe that every person should own their own home, own real estate, and have an individual stock account or own mutual funds."

- Key to mutual fund success: **sit and don't think**
- Buy fund intending to hold 15+ years
- Need courage to sit through 3-5 bear markets
- Typical diversified growth fund: up 75-100% in bull market, down only 20-30% in bear market

**Different treatment from individual stocks:**
- Individual stocks: must have stop-loss (7% rule) — stock can go to $1
- Mutual funds: sit through bear markets
- Diversified funds (100+ stocks across economy) will recover after bear markets
- Unfortunately, most people get scared in bear markets and sell, ruining long-term plan
- When good diversified growth fund is down sharply, should buy more

### Public Behavior Pattern

- People hold losers in individual stocks but liquidate mutual funds when down sharply
- Should do opposite: strict stop-losses on stocks, hold mutual funds through downturns
- "Because of the emotional element, most of what people do in the market is wrong"

## Eighteen Common Mistakes (from O'Neil's book)

1. **No selection criteria** — buy fourth-rate stocks not acting well, not real market leaders
2. **Buying on the way down** — declining stock seems cheap, but often headed for trouble (example: **International Harvester** at $19 in March 1981, headed for possible bankruptcy)
3. **Averaging down** — buying more as price falls compounds mistakes, puts good money after bad
4. **Buying cheap low-priced stocks** — feel better buying round lots of 100-1,000 shares; should buy 30-50 shares of higher-priced, sounder companies; think in dollars invested, not shares; $2, $5, $10 stocks are there because companies inferior or had recent problems; can't buy best quality at cheapest price
5. **Want to make killing too fast** — looking for easy way without study/preparation or acquiring methods and skills
6. **Buying on tips/rumors/stories** — risking money on what someone else says rather than own knowledge; most rumors false
7. **Selecting second-rate stocks for dividends or low P/E** — dividends less important than EPS; higher dividends may weaken company; can lose dividend amount in 1-2 days' stock fluctuation; low P/E probably reflects inferior past record
8. **Buying familiar company names** — best investments often unfamiliar names requiring research
9. **Not finding good information/advice** — can't recognize or follow sound advice; friends, stockbrokers, advisory services usually not successful (only small minority successful, like doctors, lawyers, baseball players)
10. **Afraid to buy stock going into new high ground** — 98% afraid; personal feelings less accurate than markets
11. **Holding losses when small and reasonable** — could exit cheaply but wait until loss much bigger
12. **Cashing small profits, holding losers** — opposite of correct procedure; will sell winners before losers
13. **Worrying too much about taxes/commissions** — key objective: make net profit first; excessive tax worry leads to unsound investments or holding too long for long-term capital gain; commission costs minor compared to making right decisions; stock's lower commission/instant marketability advantage over real estate
14. **Speculating in options** — trying to get rich quick; concentrate on shorter-term, lower-priced options (greater volatility/risk); limited time period works against short-term holders; "naked options" = great risk for small reward, unsound procedure
15. **Using limit orders instead of market orders** — quibbling for eighths/quarters, missing market and larger overall movement; limit orders result in completely missing market, not getting out of stocks requiring substantial loss avoidance
16. **Can't make buy/sell decisions** — vacillate; unsure because don't know what doing; lack plan, principles, or rules
17. **Not looking at stocks objectively** — always hoping, having favorites; rely on hopes/personal opinions rather than marketplace opinion (which is more frequently right)
18. **Influenced by non-crucial factors** — stock splits, increased dividends, news announcements, brokerage recommendations

### Wall Street Research Quality

- Article in *Financial World*: top-rated analysts generally underperformed S&P average
- **80% of brokerage research written on wrong companies** — each industry analyst must meet quota even though only few industry groups are leaders each cycle
- Insufficient screening for which reports should actually be written
- Seldom provides sell recommendations

### Market Efficiency

> "The stock market is neither efficient nor random. It is not efficient because there are too many poorly conceived opinions; it is not random because strong investor emotions can create trends."

### Trading Success Requirements

Three basic components:
1. **Effective trade selection process**
2. **Risk control**
3. **Discipline** to adhere to first two items

O'Neil provides perfect illustration: specific strategy (CANSLIM), rigorous risk control rule (7% stop), discipline not to deviate. Common mistakes list particularly useful for traders and investors.

<!-- pp. 211-230 -->

## David Ryan (continued)

### Recommended Reading List

- **Super Performance Stocks** by **Richard Love** (Prentice Hall, 1977) — case study of greatest winners
- **Profile of a Growth Stock** by **Kermit Zieg** and **Susannah H. Zieg** (Investor's Intelligence, 1972)
- **Winning on Wall Street** by **Marty Zweig** (Warner Books, 1986)
- **Secrets for Profiting in Bull and Bear Markets** by **Stan Weinstein** (Dow Jones-Irwin, 1988) — includes sections on short selling
- **Elliott Wave Principle** by **Frost** and **Prechter** (New Classic Library, 1978) — has some validity
- **Super Timing** by **Beckman** (Milestone Publishers, London)

> "All those books are good, but you learn the most from the market itself."

### Trader's Diary — Learning from Experience

- **Ryan writes down reasons for every stock purchase** on annotated charts with binder system
- Helps cement winning stock characteristics and learn from mistakes
- Diary taught three key lessons:
  - Don't buy overextended stocks
  - Use **O'Neil's criteria** for stock selection
  - Be as disciplined as possible — discipline correlates with success
  - Listening to tips and rumors = losing money

> "The more disciplined you can get, the better you are going to do in the market. The more you listen to tips and rumors, the more money you're likely to lose."

### Stock Selection Process

**Initial screening (7,000 stocks → ~4,000 reviewed weekly)**:
- Avoid stocks under $10 (usually down for a reason, knocks out many OTC stocks)
- Wait for stocks to prove themselves by moving to $15-$20 range
- Reviews ~4,000 charts weekly, writing down stocks with strong technical action

**Fundamental filters applied next**:
- **Five-year earnings growth record** — consistent long-term growth
- **Last two quarters earnings vs. prior year** — checks for deceleration
- Warning sign: 30% five-year growth but only 10-15% recent quarters = growth period may be over
- **EPS rank** (earnings per share): At least 80, preferably 90+. Many purchases at EPS rank 99
- **Relative strength**: At least 80, preferably 90+ (ranks stock's price change vs. all others)

> "Markets usually anticipate. One thing that surprises me about the EPS is that I would think that the price of the stock would run up well before the earnings growth starts to be extremely positive."

**Contrarian insight**: Earnings often "on the table for a while" before stock moves — not too late when earnings already strong.

**What can delay a stock despite good earnings**:
- Weak broad market holding it back
- Perceptions — people don't believe earnings will continue
- Once market weight lifts, stocks "go right through the roof"

**Additional screening criteria**:
- **Industry relative strength**: Top 50 out of 200 (uses **Investor's Daily** rankings)
- **Shares outstanding**: Less than 30 million, preferably 5-10 million (supply/demand — takes more money to move mature stocks)
- **Institutional ownership**: 1-20% mutual fund sponsorship ideal (powers stock but not too much)
- **"Something new"** attracting people: Hot product (Reebok shoes), innovative tech (Compaq portable computer), industry leadership (Microsoft software)
- **Avoid mature companies** like General Electric (nothing hot/new, though occasional exceptions like GM's high-styling shift)

**From 70 stocks down to 7 finalists**:
- Select stocks with all characteristics **plus great-looking base pattern**
- Check past performance: Has stock doubled before? (Shows unusual strength)
- **Prefers stocks that already doubled** — "if situation is that good, a doubling may just be the beginning"

> "I am looking for the strongest stocks in the market, in terms of both earnings and the technical picture."

### Win Rate and Risk Management

- **50/50 win rate** — cuts losers very quickly
- **Maximum loss: 7%** — usually exits losing stocks faster
- Makes money on "few stocks a year that double and triple in price"
- Big winners easily compensate for small losers

**Holding periods**:
- Big winners: 6-12 months
- Moderate stocks: ~3 months
- Losers: Less than 2 weeks

**Exit strategy**:
- No price objective set in advance
- Waits for stock to run up, build another base, then break down
- That's when he liquidates

### Execution — Market Orders vs. Limit Orders

> "If you really think the stock is going to make a big move—and that should be the only reason you are buying the stock to begin with—then there is no reason to haggle over an eighth of a point."

- **Use market orders** when expecting big move (same applies to downside selling)
- Dull markets can use limit orders
- **Lesson from 1982**: Tried to buy Textone at $15 for $14¾. Next day jumped 1½ points, couldn't bring himself to pay $16½. Stock eventually went to $45.

**Buying at new highs**:
- Fundamental conditions may have been in place earlier, but Ryan buys when "most chance of making money"
- Stock coming off base low back to base high has "overhead resistance" — people at loss want to get out at breakeven
- **New highs = open running field** — no one ahead at loss, everyone profitable and happy

**Avoiding false breakouts**:
- **Volume must double** when stock breaks to new high (signals strong interest)
- If volume only up 10%, would be wary
- Buys as soon as stock goes to new highs (doesn't wait for consolidation)

**Managing pullbacks after breakout**:
- If stock pulls back into range after breakout, **cut at least 50% of position**
- Example: Stock trading $16-$20, breaks to $21, you buy, then drops back to $19
- If just reenters base (not penetrating it), may break out again — can stay with stock
- But if drops back to $19¾ (base was $20), **sell at least half** because stock didn't keep moving
- Frequently when stock drops back into base, it goes all the way to lower end

> "If it goes from $21 down to $19¾, it will often go all the way back down to $16. Therefore, you want to cut your losses quickly."

**Technical indicator**: Price going back into base = bearish. "Stocks should be at a profit the first day you buy them."

### Volume Analysis

- **Investor's Daily volume table**: Lists stocks with greatest percentage increase vs. 50-day average
- Uses to spot stocks ready to take off
- After weekly screen, sometimes waits for stock to hit that column as timing signal

**Volume patterns**:
- **Consolidation phase**: Want volume to dry up (downtrend)
- **Breakout**: Want volume to pick up (signals ready to blast off)
- **Continued high volume during consolidation** = potential top (people getting out)

**Volume at market bottoms**:
- Increased volume + absence of further downside progress = support
- Example: Dow declines 2,200 → 2,100, trades down to 2,085 next day, then closes higher on increased volume = buyers coming in

### Ryan's Methodology — CANSLIM with Modifications

**Base is William O'Neil's CANSLIM** (see O'Neil chapter for definition)

**Ryan's additions**:
- **P/E ratio matters** (O'Neil says not important)
- Greatest winning recommendations started with prices under 30x earnings
- Lower P/E ratio stocks = higher success ratio
- Target: **P/E between 1x and 2x the S&P 500 P/E**
  - If S&P 500 at 15x earnings, buy stocks with P/E 15-30
  - Going beyond 2x S&P P/E requires more exact timing and produces more mistakes

**Avoid high P/E stocks in most cases**:
- Most profitable: Strong earnings trend trading at P/E in line with broad market
- Exception: New industries where whole group trades at high P/E (e.g., biomedicals)
- Don't be absolutely rigid with rules

### Market Behavior Consistency Across Decades

> "The same types of stocks work time after time. It hasn't changed at all. We can take one of the greatest winning stocks from 1960 and line it up with one of the best stocks in 1980 and they are going to have exactly the same characteristics."

### Short Selling Thoughts

- Needs more study and experience
- To pick short: **Flip the characteristics** — poor 5-year growth, decelerating quarterly earnings, losing relative strength, breaking uptrends, hitting new lows
- Would help in long bear market, but **O'Neil says shorting 3x harder than buying**
- O'Neil made substantial money in only 2 of past 9 bear markets
- O'Neil's advice for bear market: "Just sit it out"

**Recognizing bear market before too late**:
- Watches individual stock performance
- If leaders start losing during bull phase, caution flag
- **5-6 stocks in a row get stopped out** = warning

**Bear market indicators**:
- **Advance/decline line** divergence from Dow (cumulative net difference between NYSE stocks advancing vs. declining each day)
- Advance/decline tends to top out months before Dow peaks

**1987 crash signals**:
- Advance/decline topped Q1 1987, well before August stock market peak
- Individual stocks still doing well initially (not looking for top yet)
- After Dow came off high at 2,746, feeble low-volume rally, then 90-point loss
- At that juncture, decided to exit market
- Low volume rally + few stocks participating + advance/decline not moving as high as previous rally
- Late August discount rate increase (first in 3 years) "really stabbed the market"

### Long-Term Success Foundation

> "I have established a very defined set of principles that will provide the foundation for successful trading for years to come. Also, I plan to never stop learning."

**Getting better as trader**: "If you try to learn from every single trade that you make, you are only going to get better and better as time goes on."

### Why More Successful Than Typical Investor

- **Loves what he does** — fascinating work, goes home and spends more time on markets
- Charts delivered Saturdays, goes through them 3-4 hours on Sunday
- **Disciplined system for picking stocks** — not reading articles or following broker recommendations

> "I think if you love what you are doing, you are going to be a lot more successful."

**Advice for novice trader**: "Learn from your mistakes. That is the only way to become a successful trader."

### Trading as Treasure Hunt

> "The greatest thing about the market is that it is always fun to be looking for that next big winner—trying to find the stock with all the characteristics that are going to make it have a big move. The feeling isn't any different now than when I was only trading 500 shares."

> "It is like a giant treasure hunt. Somewhere in here [the weekly chart book] there is going to be a big winner, and I am trying to find it."

---

## Summary Essay: David Ryan's Philosophy

Conventional wisdom: Buy low, sell high. **David Ryan disagrees**: Buy high, sell higher. Won't even consider stocks under $10.

**Ryan's success = precise methodology + great discipline**. Readily acknowledges most of his approach learned directly from **William O'Neil**. With hard work and in-depth study, he's applied O'Neil's trading philosophy with great effectiveness.

**When traders deviate from their own rules, they invariably lose**. Ryan's exception: Mid-1983 to mid-1984 witnessed extremely poor performance. He let previous success go to his head by repeatedly breaking cardinal rule: **Never buy an overextended stock** (trading far above most recent price base). The 1983-1984 experience made lasting impression — hasn't repeated that mistake.

**Trader's diary = essential element**. Every time Ryan buys stock, he annotates chart with reasons. When liquidating or adding to position, new chart included with updated comments. Helps reinforce characteristics of winning stocks. More important: helps avoid repeating similar trading mistakes.

**Ryan's basic approach** (like O'Neil's): **Buy value and strength**. Focuses on very best stocks as opposed to diversifying portfolio. Important observation: **Best trades are usually winners right from the start**. Little reservation about getting out of losing trade quickly. **Maximum risk: 7% price decline**. Rigid stop-loss rule = essential ingredient for many successful traders.

---

## Marty Schwartz — Champion Trader

**Marty Schwartz**: Very opinionated and intense about trading. Intensity occasionally spills into anger when raw nerve hit (e.g., program trading). Finds anger useful trait in trading. **Marketplace = arena; other traders = adversaries**.

Struck by **Schwartz's dedication to daily work routine**. Was doing market analysis when Schwartz arrived for interview, continued running calculations during interview. When left that evening, analysis still unfinished. Appeared very tired, but no doubt would finish work that evening. **Followed daily work routine religiously for past nine years**.

### Trading Record

- **Spent decade losing money** before finding his stride as remarkably successful professional trader
- Earlier years: Well-paid securities analyst, always broke because of market losses
- Eventually **changed trading methodology**, transforming from repeated loser to amazingly consistent winner
- **Enormous percentage gains every year** since turning full-time trader in 1979
- **Never lost more than 3% of equity on month-end to month-end basis**

**Trades independently from home office**. Proud of having no employees. Solitary traders of this type usually unknown to public.

**Schwartz attained fame** through repeated entries in **U.S. Trading Championships** (run by **Norm Zadeh**, Stanford University professor):
- **Nine of ten four-month championships entered**: Made more money than all other contestants combined
- **Average return: 210% (nonannualized!)**
- One remaining four-month contest: Near breakeven result
- **Single one-year contest entry**: 781% return

Entry into these contests = way of telling world he's the best trader around. In terms of risk/reward ratios, may well be.

### Early Life — New Haven Childhood

> "I grew up in New Haven in a family of modest means. I was very hard working. When I was seven or eight I would go out with a snow shovel and come back with $10 after a snowstorm."

**Still works 12 hours/day**. "I feel uncomfortable not doing the work; that's why I am doing it now as you are sitting here." Calculates mathematical ratios and oscillators, posts own charts. "My attitude is that I always want to be better prepared than someone I'm competing against. The way I prepare myself is by doing my work each night."

### Education Journey

**Education = ticket** (strongly emphasized in family). Studied hard, honor student in high school.

**Amherst College** — "one of great experiences of my life":

> "Look to your left and right and realize that half of you are going to be in the top half of the class and half of you are going to be in the bottom half."

Most who matriculated there (including Schwartz) were in top 5% of high school class. "Perceiving that I wasn't going to be at the top of everything was a difficult first realization."

**First time had to struggle**. Got tutor for calculus because "just wasn't getting the concept."

> "But when I finally got it, when the light bulb clicked on, it was like looking at a magnificent painting. I really experienced the joy of learning and working hard there."

**Amherst had profound influence**.

### Columbia Business School & Marine Corps

Accepted to **Columbia Business School** 1967. Government had just ended graduate school military deferments. Unhappy at Columbia and combat in Vietnam didn't appeal, so joined **U.S. Marine Corps reserve unit** recruiting officers.

**Marines training philosophy**:
- "You have to be somewhat crazy to be in the Marines; it is a very unusual organization."
- Push you to edge, then rebuild you in their own mold
- Developed great respect for bureaucracy — consistent in training procedure throughout history
- **As second lieutenant: Forty-six lives under your control** — must be well skilled
- Tremendous pressure. "If you couldn't cut the mustard, you didn't get the bars."
- **Attrition rate approached 50%**

**Personal challenges**:
- Only reservist in Officers Candidate School in Quantico at the time
- 199 regulars went to Vietnam, but came home (the deal when recruited)
- Only Jewish person there — not favorably disposed toward Jews
- Platoon sergeant drew Star of David on forehead with magic marker
- "I wanted to knock the crap out of him, but I figured he didn't really know the historic significance of what it meant."
- "The hardest thing I had to do was scrub the magic marker off my forehead. That's a bitch."
- **Persevered and made it through successfully** — "really fine achievement"

> "The rigorous Marine training gave me the confidence to believe that I could perform at levels beyond my previous expectations."

**Combined with Amherst**: "Just as Amherst had strengthened my mind, the Marines strengthened my body. The two experiences convinced me that I could do almost anything if I worked hard enough and provided the groundwork for my successful trading."

### Wall Street Career — Kuhn Loeb & XYZ Firm

After Marines, returned to Columbia, completed M.B.A. **First full-time job: Securities analyst at Kuhn Loeb** (specialized health/retail field, stayed 2 years). On Wall Street, best way to get pay increase = change jobs. Company never wants to pay as much as company trying to recruit you.

**Left for XYZ in 1972** (name/particulars withheld "for reasons that will soon become obvious"):
- Firm had 30 analysts divided into three subgroups of ten
- Research director didn't want to work, had senior analysts of each group review other analysts' work
- Policy: Research reports circulated and critiqued by other analysts within subgroups before sending out

**The leaked bearish report incident**:
- Schwartz wrote bearish report on hospital management stocks (industry would go to utility rate of return)
- As part of normal routine, draft circulated among other analysts
- One analyst got drunk on flight home from California, told client about report, even sent copy in progress
- Client started spreading rumors that negative report about to be issued
- **Stocks began plummeting prior to report's release**

**New York Stock Exchange hearing**:
- Had to testify for six hours
- Company's counsel: "We will represent you, but should our interests diverge at any point, we will inform you."

**At the time, didn't know what had happened**:
- "I didn't, but I assumed that everything would be all right if I told the truth, which I did."
- "I was totally exonerated; the exchange realized I had been set up."
- Drug analyst eventually confessed (exchange official pieced it together)

> "It was a rotten, bitter experience for me, and I was very sour. I shut the door of my office and stopped working. I lost the spark, the drive, the desire to succeed."

### Turning Point — 1973 Bear Market

**Still doing reports** but heart not in it. Besides negative experience, **early 1973** — felt market was topping out. Had become very interested in technical analysis. **Advance/decline line had formed major top many months earlier**. "I felt that the market and the stocks I was covering were going to go down."

> "Still, people wanted to know how many widgets a company was selling and at what price. I lost the spirit to write bullish reports, because if stock prices are going down, who cares how many widgets are being sold."

Covering growth stocks selling at 40-50x earnings. "It was all so ridiculous!"

**Discouraged from writing bearish reports?**

"Nobody wrote bearish reports on Wall Street at that time. I was allowed to complete the bearish report on the hospital management industry, but I don't believe they ever intended to publish it. Of course, after it was leaked, they were forced to rush it to the printer to save their scalps."

**What eventually happened?**

Lost job in bear market, out of work four months. "That was a very interesting period, because I believe you learn the most through adversity."

**Had about $20,000** (lot of money in those days). Was going to trade. **Found "real lunatic" who developed computer programs for trading commodities**. At the time, had to rent time on monster machine to run programs (today could do on any PC). Using different moving averages. **Put some money in with him, lost most of it**—along with dreams of glory.

**Having dissipated capital, decided had to go back to work**. Was in for shock. "Although I had been totally honest and forthright, I was tainted. 'Oh, aren't you the guy who wrote that report?' It didn't matter that I had been totally ethical and exonerated. People don't want to get involved with any controversy, even if it wasn't of your own making."

### Edwards & Hanly — Meeting Bob Zoellner

Friend helped get job at **Edwards & Hanly** (retail-oriented firm with group of analysts who became real stars). **Met Bob Zoellner** (managing partner of firm):
- "Great, great trader"
- "Almost single-handedly kept the firm afloat in 1974 by shorting stocks and making money in the firm's capital account, while they were losing money on the operating side"
- Started own hedge fund in 1976, became extraordinary success

> "I always had a good nose as a securities analyst, and it has stood me in good stead."

**Warning sign**: "When I noticed that the head of research, who never went out to lunch, began going out to lunch regularly, I started interviewing for another job." When firm went bankrupt fall 1975, had another job lined up at **Loeb Rhoades**.

### Personal Turning Point — 1976

**Met wife-to-be in 1976** — "profound effect on me":

> "She made me realize that my life was not a dress rehearsal; it was the real thing and I had been screwing it up."

Although steadily earned good salaries, **still almost broke** because consistently lost money in market.

**Got married March 1978**. By then working at **E. F. Hutton**. Being married made business trips harder. "When you are twenty-five, seeing friends from college in different cities around the country is very exciting, but when you get in your thirties, it gets real stale. My wife literally had to push me out the door when I had to go on these trips."

**Resented "tap dances"** — felt like piece of meat. Meet with portfolio managers to give views on stocks, so they give commission business to firm. On typical trip: Five appointments in Houston, fly to San Antonio for dinner, then fly to Dallas later that night to be ready for breakfast next morning. "I got sick of it."

**Wanted family** but felt wasn't able to handle it financially. "I had resisted getting married because I was afraid of being tapped out."

> "But, at that point, I wondered whether it had been a self-fulfilling prophecy. People seem to know how to handle failure because they can produce it themselves. It almost becomes a negative cause and effect cycle, whereby they produce it, they know how to handle it, and they wallow in it."

**By mid-1978**: Securities analyst for eight years, become intolerable. "I knew I had to do something different. I always knew I wanted to work for myself, have no clients, and answer to no one. That, to me, was the ultimate goal."

**Had been brooding for years**: "Why wasn't I doing well when I was groomed to be successful?"

> "I decided it was now time to be successful."

### Going Independent — 1979

**When brokerage firm wants to hire you, they'll give you anything**. Once there, far less responsive.

**When being romanced by Hutton**, asked for quote machine in office. Was the only securities analyst with quote machine. During last year at Hutton, started closing door to office so could watch market.

**Talked to Bob Zoellner several times a day** — taught how to analyze market action:

> "For example, when the market gets good news and goes down, it means the market is very weak; when it gets bad news and goes up, it means the market is healthy."

**During that year**, started taking trial subscriptions to different newsletters. "I consider myself a synthesizer; I didn't necessarily create a new methodology, but I took a number of different methodologies and molded them into my own approach."

**Found Terry Laundry** (lived in Nantucket, had unorthodox approach called **Magic T Forecast**):
- MIT engineering graduate with math background (appealed to Schwartz)
- **Basic theory**: Market spent same amount of time going up as going down. Only amplitude was different.

> "In my experience, markets come down a lot quicker than they go up. Doesn't that contradict the theory?"

**Market movement before going down = distributive process** (calls them **M-tops**):
- Point used to measure time element = not price high, but **oscillator high** (precedes price high)
- "That, in fact, is a major cornerstone of his work."
- Theory had different properties that learned, "has been extremely helpful to me"

**For the record, what is the name of Laundry's book?**

"There is no book. He just extolled his theory through his various newsletters. He also had some pamphlets." Kind of funny — after mentioned him in Barron's article, got lot of inquiries for pamphlets. Response: "I don't have any copies available." Should have printed them and made some money.

**Developed and synthesized number of indicators** to determine when market at lower-risk entry point:
- Focused on determining mathematical probabilities
- Occasionally situations where market goes 3 standard deviations instead of 2
- Based on likelihood that 98% of moves will stop at 2 standard deviations, "I'll take that bet any day of the week"
- If wrong, will use risk control and stop out X dollars away
- **"That is the most critical element"**

**Subscribed to all these letters, developed methodology, and traded like crazy**. By mid-1979, had run $5,000 up to $140,000 in just two years.

### From Loser to Winner — The Psychological Shift

> "When I was able to separate my ego needs from making money. When I was able to accept being wrong. Before, admitting I was wrong was more upsetting than losing the money. I used to try to will things to happen. I figured it out, therefore it can't be wrong. When I became a winner, I said, 'I figured it out, but if I'm wrong, I'm getting the hell out, because I want to save my money and go on to the next trade.'"

**Living the philosophy**: "My winners are always in front of me, it is not so painful to take a loss. If I make a mistake, so what!"

### Complete Transition to Technical Analysis

> "Absolutely. I always laugh at people who say, 'I've never met a rich technician.' I love that! It is such an arrogant, nonsensical response. I used fundamentals for nine years and got rich as a technician."


<!-- pp. 231-250 -->

## Marty Schwartz (continued)

### October 19, 1987: The Crash

**Crisis Recognition Over the Weekend**
- Friday climactic sell-off looked like a buying opportunity — except **Treasury Secretary James Baker** verbally bludgeoning Germans about interest rates over the weekend
- **Marty Zweig** on "Wall Street Week" Friday evening predicted another 500-point risk
- Zweig's bearishness based on terribly negative monetary indicators and sinking bonds

**Monday Exit Strategy**
- S&P high Monday: 269; liquidated long at 267½
- Lost $315,000 on 40 contracts
- Proud of executing the exit — "very hard to pull the trigger on a loser"
- Avoided suicidal mistake of adding to losing position (could have lost $5 million)

> "One of the most suicidal things you can do in trading is to keep adding to a losing position." — Marty Schwartz

**Marine Corps Training Application**
- "Never freeze when under attack" — go forward or backward, don't sit still
- Applied this principle to market action: kept enough powder to make a comeback
- 1987 was his most profitable year post-crash

**Crisis Day Actions**
- By 1:30 PM with Dow down 275 points: went to safe deposit box for gold, withdrew cash from multiple banks
- Started buying Treasury bills, preparing for worst-case scenario
- Seriously worried about banks collapsing (operations side stories confirmed banks near breaking point)

**Personal Depression Fear**
- Father graduated college 1929 — ten-year period missing from lives of that generation
- Fear of depression influenced decision not to geometrically increase earnings
- Looking at infant son: "I don't want him to ask me, 'Dad, why didn't you do everything you could have done?'"

### Post-Crash Trading

**Wednesday Return**
- Started trading Wednesday with tiny positions (1-2 S&P contracts)
- S&P trading in *full point increments* [$500 per contract vs. $25 minimum tick]
- Ended Wednesday short 12 S&P contracts

**Thursday Collapse**
- **Bob Prechter** (*Elliott Wave Theorist*) issued negative hotline message Wednesday night
- Thursday: massive fund manager trying to liquidate monster long position
- Market lost $800 million during that period
- Called S&P pit before opening: "Decembers at 230, offered at 220, trading at 200"
- Made $250,000 on 12 contracts — "Cover!" — one of most memorable trades

### Program Trading Critique

**Schwartz's Strong Opposition**
- "I hate it" — program trading killed natural ebb and flow
- Firms wield extraordinary power; locals became accomplices
- Market closes near high/low of day 20% of time (last 2 years) — "mathematically impossible by chance"

**Evidence of Manipulation**
- Argues market closes suspiciously near extremes
- **Chinese wall problem**: agency program traders and principal traders on same floor (conflict of interest)
- Questions SEC allowing this structure

**Interviewer's Counterargument**
- Program trading defenders say criticism is "nonsense"
- Schwartz: "They are idiots. I can prove to any one of them that they are idiots."
- Specific example: New Jersey sold $2 billion stock, moved into bonds
- Firm knew day before, sold futures 4:00-4:15 PM to set up trade — "That stinks"

**Schwartz's Fundamental Objection**
- Trading stocks against stock index futures "serves no useful purpose"
- Started as security analyst — "analyzing things and buying something for value"
- Program trading = dumb game for 80 basis points over Treasury bills
- Order flow creates power on Wall Street

> "I am trying to earn infinity when I trade." — Marty Schwartz

### Trading Philosophy & Rules

**Most Dramatic Loss: November 1982**
- Took $600,000 loss in one day (much smaller net worth then)
- Election Day: Republicans did better than expected, market ran up 43 points (one of largest advances in history)
- Was short, S&P locked at 500-point limit against him, less than an hour left
- Wife next day: "Get smaller, get smaller" every ten minutes
- Learned: trying to get losses back at once = doomed to fail (true in trading, investing, gambling)
- Las Vegas lesson: keep only X dollars in pocket, never have credit

**Recovery After Devastating Loss**
- Always play very small after big loss — "black ink, black ink"
- Not about how much money made — about getting rhythm and confidence back
- Shrinks size to 1/5 or 1/10 of normal position
- Lost only $57,000 in November 1982 after $600,000 hit on November 4

**Key Trading Rules (from his list)**

1. **Check charts and moving averages before position** — price above/below MA better than any tool; going against MA is self-destructive

2. **Look for divergences** — stock holding above recent low when market penetrates recent low = healthier than market

3. **Before position, ask: "Do I really want to have this position?"**

4. **After successful period, take day off as reward** — difficult to sustain profitable trading more than two weeks; battle fatigue sets in; play smaller after strong run (biggest losses follow largest profits)

5. **Bottom fishing = expensive gambling** — OK to break rule if sufficient justification (bought S&Ps at 248.45 when low was 248.50 — risky but had plan and knew risk)

6. **Before position, know amount willing to lose** — know "uncle point" and honor pain threshold; must get out when reached

7. **When T-bonds and T-bills diverge (one MA above price, one below), have no position until one confirms direction** — interest rates can't move far until one confirms the other

8. **Work, work, and more work**

**Money Management Emphasis**
- "Money management, money management, money management" — most important thing
- "Anybody who is successful will tell you the same thing"
- Constantly trying to improve letting gains run (not able to do well; always working on it)

**Difficulty Letting Profits Run**
- "I just love to take profits. I hear music when the cash register rings."
- Irony: willing to risk 400 points downside, only take 200 points of 1,000-point move upside
- Hasn't perfected discipline on profit side (has varying degrees of success)

**Fear Management & Diversification**
- Fears cataclysmic event like **W.C. Fields** — several bank accounts, safe deposit boxes with gold and cash
- Extremely well diversified
- "If I screw up in one place, I'll always have a life preserver someplace else"

**Additional Rules**

9. **If very nervous about overnight position and able to get out at better price than thought possible, stay with position** — if worst fears aren't realized, probably should increase position (Example: short S&P, nervous because bond market strong, relieved to cover flat — mistake; S&P collapsed later)

**Performance Metrics**
- Records evaluated for money management deal
- Biggest drawdown over entire career: **3%** (based on month-end data)
- Worst two months: around birth of children (worried about Lamaze class)
- Philosophy: try to be profitable every single month, every single day
- Over 90% of months profitable
- Proud: virtually every year didn't have losing month before April
- Doesn't make as much money as could because more concerned about controlling downside

**Starting Fresh**
- "January 1, I'm poor" — starts every year with clean slate
- Doesn't necessarily trade smaller in January — attention is greater
- Always takes losses quickly — "probably the key to my success"

> "You can always put the trade back on, but if you go flat, you see things differently." — Marty Schwartz

**Managed Money Motivation**
- Felt getting stale; presents whole new challenge
- After October 1987, realized downside risk can't be adequately measured
- Way to get more personal leverage: outside pool of money
- Taking on only 1-2 large pools; doesn't want multiple investors or public underwriting
- More people = more headaches (large fund manager had 70 employees; "when he wants to quit, it will be more difficult")

**Work Environment**
- Took several years to accept working alone
- Used to go downtown because friends were there
- Now works from home, talks to half dozen people daily on phone
- Has taught methodologies to number of them; they have methodologies of their own

**Training Others**
- Hired four people — none lasted; all became intimidated
- Tried to clone himself — didn't work
- "You can't teach them your stomach" — learning intellectual side is only part

### Why Most Traders Lose Money

> "Because they would rather lose money than admit they're wrong." — Marty Schwartz

- Ultimate rationalization in losing position: "I'll get out when I'm even"
- Getting out protects the ego
- Became winning trader when able to say: "To hell with my ego, making money is more important"

### Advice for Aspiring Traders

**Encouragement**
- "Think that you might become more successful than you ever dreamt, because that's what happened to me"
- Has freedom wanted: financially and structurally
- Can go on vacation anytime
- Lives in Westhampton Beach half the year, New York the other half
- "Wonderful lifestyle. My kids think all fathers work at home."

**Best Advice for Ordinary Guy Trying to Become Better Trader**

1. **Learn to take losses** — most important thing in making money is not letting losses get out of hand

2. **Don't increase position size until you've doubled or tripled capital** — most people increase bets as soon as they start making money = quick way to get wiped out

---

## Chapter Summary: Marty Schwartz's Transformation

**Ten-Year Losing Streak to World-Class Trader**
- Unsuccessful for ten years, nearly broke despite good salaries
- Eventually turned around, became one of world's best traders

**Two Essential Elements**

1. **Found methodology that worked for him**
   - Used fundamental analysis during losing years
   - Became successful only after immersing in **technical analysis**
   - Point: not that technical > fundamental, but that technical was right *for him*
   - Other successful traders (e.g., **James Rogers**) use fundamental analysis exclusively
   - **Key lesson: each trader must find his or her own best approach**

2. **Attitude change**
   - Became successful when desire to win took precedence over desire to be right

**Risk Control**
- Essential element of Schwartz's style
- Incredibly low drawdowns attest to this
- Always knows "uncle point" on any trade
- Sharply reduces position size after large losses *and* after extended winning streaks
- Rationale for reducing after losses: apparent
- Rationale for reducing after wins: biggest losses follow biggest gains
- Winning streaks lead to complacency; complacency leads to sloppy trading

**Unique Rule**
- Maintain position you're worried about when market doesn't justify fears
- Implicit concept: if market won't easily get you off the hook on fearful position (fundamental adverse or technical breakout opposite direction), strong underlying forces favor original position direction
<!-- pp. 251-270 -->

## Jim Rogers (continued)

### Early Trading Disaster: The 1970 Hysteria Lesson

- **January 1970**: Rogers bought options, took all his money and bought puts
- **May 1970**: Market bottomed, he sold his puts and tripled his money—thought he was "the next **Bernard Baruch**"
- Fatal mistake: Waited for the market to rally, then went short to "make money faster"
- Two months later: **Completely wiped out** because he didn't know what he was doing
- **Memorex short at 48**: Had the staying power—psychologically, emotionally, financially—but covered at 72. Memorex eventually hit 96, then went to 2
- "I was dead right, absolutely flat-out, perfectly right to short that stock at 48. I just ended up getting completely wiped out. The market didn't care that I was dead right."

> "The market is going to go higher than I think it can and lower than I think it will. I had a tendency to think that if I knew something, everybody knew it. Most people don't have the foresight to look six months, one year, or two years out. The Memorex experience taught me that anything can happen in the stock market, because there are a lot of people in the market who don't understand what is going on."

### Long-Term Macro View (April 1988)

**Stock Market & Financial Collapse**
- Expects the market to eventually break the **October 1987 low**
- Looking primarily for a **financial collapse**, not necessarily a deep recession
- Politicians may turn financial collapse into economic collapse through protectionism, tariffs, raising taxes

**1937 Parallel**
- Uses 1937 as example: didn't expect economy to collapse, but as dollar weakens, parts of American economy will do well (steel, agriculture, textiles, mining)
- Even if stock market falls below October low, economy can still do well—unless politicians "foul it up"

**The Deficit Crisis Chain**
- **Budget deficit** causes **trade deficit** (not going to fix trade deficit until budget deficit is fixed)
- Trade deficit worsens → **dollar comes under extreme pressure**
- Why Rogers is **not long the dollar**

### The Bond Market Scenario

- At some point, foreigners will stop putting money into U.S. because of weakening dollar
- American public will have to finance the debt—but U.S. only has **3-4% savings rate**
- To get Americans to finance debt, interest rates must be **very high**
- If Fed avoids high rates by printing money → dollar disappears, Fed loses control → **hyperinflation and 25-30% interest rates**
- Either way: high rates. Might start with lower rates if politicians bite the bullet (recession), but eventually they give up and print money
- **Bond market collapses sooner or later**—could repeat English experience (British bonds fell **~70%**)
- Timeline: Could be three years, could be ten

**What Rogers monitors**: Money supply, government deficits, trade deficits, inflation, financial markets, government policy for U.S. and key foreign countries
- "It is one big, **three-dimensional puzzle**. However, if you had a three-dimensional puzzle, you could eventually put it together. But this puzzle is not one in which you can spread out the pieces on a great big table and put them all together. The picture is always changing. Every day some pieces get taken away and others get thrown in."

### Government Spending Examples

- **Sugar subsidies**: U.S. spends **$5 billion/year** to support domestic sugar at 22 cents/pound wholesale when world price is 8 cents
  - Better to give every sugar grower $100k/year for life, a condo, and a Porsche to get out of the business—would save billions
- **American troops in Europe**: Costs **$150 billion/year**
  - Sent 43 years ago as army of occupation; most Americans weren't born when decision was made
  - GAO says not enough bullets to fight even a 30-day war in Europe
  - If troops came home, Europeans would buy guns from U.S. (don't have good defense industry themselves)

### Gold Outlook

**The 1970s Bull Market**
- 1934: Gold set at **$35/ounce**, production declined 1935-1980
- No incentive to look for gold during that period
- 1970s: Great bull market driven by supply/demand (demand rising, supply falling)
- Even at zero inflation, would have had bull market in gold

**The 1980s Supply Surge**
- Price rise from $35 to $875 brought massive new supply
- Gold production up **every year since 1980**
- Major technological advances in recovery processes
- Production scheduled to rise every year until at least 1995
- "Much more gold available than there used to be, and that trend will continue at least into the mid-1990s"

**Current view**: Owns some gold as insurance, but doesn't think it will be the great inflation hedge of the 1990s like it was in the 1970s
- Supply/demand picture now negative
- If dollar collapses, gold may keep purchasing power but won't be the best market

> "Generals always fight the last war. Portfolio managers always invest in the last bull market. The idea that gold has always been the great store of value is absurd. There have been many times in history when gold has lost purchasing power—sometimes for decades."

**South Africa wild card**: Fully expects South Africa to blow up—government has "painted itself too far into a corner." If revolution occurs and blacks take over, South African whites would dump all their gold → price would go down

### Oil Prediction

- When recession hits: "The price of oil is going to go way down"
- Can guarantee it will go under $12 (oil was ~$16 at time of interview)
- Whether $11, $7, or $3: "I don't know"

### Protection for the Average Investor

Given the bearish scenario (stocks down, dollar down, bonds down):
- Buy **European and Far Eastern currencies**
- Buy **Treasury bills**
- Buy **farm land**

### Rogers' Trading Journey

**Early days (1964-1970)**
- 1964: Summer job on Wall Street (didn't even know difference between stocks and bonds)
- 1964-1966: Oxford—read *Financial Times* while other Americans were interested in politics
- Light trading with scholarship money at Oxford
- August 1, 1968: Came into market right at the top as junior analyst (machine tools, then advertising agencies)
- January 1970: Figured out bear market, bought puts, **tripled money** by May
- July 1970: Started shorting stocks
- **September 1970**: Wiped out—went from genius to fool

**Ground zero to success (1970-1973)**
- Saved everything, put it back into market—"entrepreneurial spirit personified"
- Got rid of first wife ("didn't care about TV or sofa")
- Traded bonds, stocks, currencies, commodities from the beginning
- Late 1960s: Bought gold—already had currency awareness from Oxford (kept money in dollars knowing sterling would devalue)

> "My early losses taught me a lot. Since then—I don't like to say this kind of thing—I have made very few mistakes. I learned quickly not to do anything unless you know what you are doing. I learned that it is better to do nothing and wait until you get a concept so right, and a price so right, that even if you are wrong, it is not going to hurt you."

**No losing year after September 1970**

### The Quantum Fund (1973-1980)

- Started by **George Soros** (senior partner) and Rogers (junior partner)—one senior, one junior, one secretary
- 1970: Rogers went to work for Soros at **Arnhold and S. Bleichroeder**
- 1973: Left to start own firm due to new brokerage regulations (couldn't get percentage of trading profits and manage money)
- **Investment strategy**: Stocks, bonds, currencies, commodities—long and short—all over the world
- **Division of labor**: Soros was the trader, Rogers was the analyst
- Rogers came up with ideas (e.g., shorting the dollar), Soros decided timing
- If they disagreed: Usually did nothing. Occasionally did trade if one felt strongly. "Consensus investing is a disaster, but we almost always seemed to come together."

**Leverage approach**: "Leveraged to the hilt"
- When buying something new and running out of money: Sold whatever appeared **least attractive** in portfolio at that point
- "Amoebic process"—portfolio grew organically, with pressure shifting positions

**Never evaluated risk on individual basis**—if lost money in one market and had to reduce portfolio, would cut back in another market (the least attractive position)

**September 1979**: Decided it would be his last year
- October 1979: Big stock market collapse, which they sailed through—so much fun he stayed one more year
- **1980**: Cashed in chips and retired

### Teaching at Columbia (1983-present)

- Started teaching 1983 as **part-time** "so I could play squash" (dead serious)
- Deal with Dean: Teach one course per semester **for free** in return for **lifetime access to Columbia gym**
- Teaches: Security analysis, investment analysis, **"Bulls and Bears"** course

**"Bulls and Bears" course**: Each student must find a major historical market move (any market, up or down)
- Tell Rogers what one could have known at the time to see the move coming
- Example: **1861 cotton bull market** (½ cent to $1.05)—rubber went up twelvefold when everyone said "How can rubber go up?"
- Forces students to learn historical perspective across broad spectrum of markets

### Trading Philosophy & Methods

**On historical research**:
- Spent years pouring historical data into his head—developed "great deal of perspective"
- Students astonished by range of historical markets he's familiar with
- Example: Knows about **1861 cotton bull market** from studying commodity/bond/stock books for years
- Finds anomalous years in long-term charts, asks "What caused that? Why did that happen?"

**Study method**:
- Start by finding anomalous years in long-term historical chart
- Figure out why it happened
- From that, "you learn an enormous amount"

> "I have lived through or studied hundreds, possibly even thousands, of bull and bear markets. In every bull market, whether it is IBM or oats, the bulls always seem to come up with reasons why it must go on, and on, and on."

**On market hysteria cycles**:
- Market very low → some buy because undervalued → more buy because fundamentally sound or charts look good → people buy because "it's been the thing to do" → **magical stage: hysterical buying** because they know market will go up forever, prices exceed rational economic value
- Same process in reverse on downside → eventually reaches hysteria and gets very underpriced
- "But for a long-term investment, you usually have to wait a few years and let the market base."

**On the 1987 stock market**:
- 1968: Major Wall Street houses published thesis on stock shortage (why bull market had to keep going)
- 1987: Heard it all over again—"shortage of stocks because everybody is buying in all this stock"
- At bottom of bear market: "There is going to be a shortage of money—I assure you—with a gigantic surplus of stocks."

### Japan Bubble Warning

**Prediction**: Japanese stock market will have major collapse—possibly within next year or two
- Many U.S. stocks will go down 80-90%; lot more Japanese stocks will go down 80-90%
- **Australia sold 1½ acre plot in Tokyo for $450 million** (bought for $250,000 twenty-five years ago)—**tulipmania** parallel

**How to profit**:
- Short Japanese stocks, indexes, calls
- Buy Japanese puts
- Many Japanese stocks trade in U.S., can short them
- Japanese index trades in Singapore and Osaka
- At least five major Japanese corporations have options on **Chicago Board Options Exchange**
- **Caution**: "You have to be very careful about going short Japan, because they might change the rules on you at any time"

**Kuwaiti stock market 1980-1981**: Could buy stocks with postdated checks—passport clerk owned $10 billion worth on postdated checks
- Didn't short it because knew when market caved, "they would create rules so that I would never get my money out"
- Eventually collapsed—if had gone short, would have been blamed

**Current Japan position**: Has a few Japanese shorts, will have more, but will be careful
- Knows when crisis comes, Japanese will protect themselves
- "Whatever they do to protect themselves, it ain't going to be good for Jim Rogers"

**Risk**: May not be able to get money out
- Could freeze currency, create tiered currencies
- "God knows what they will do"

### Why Rogers Left Quantum Fund

- "I didn't want to do the same thing for the rest of my life. I always wanted to have more than one career."
- 1968: Came to New York as poor boy from Alabama
- 1979: Had made more money than he knew existed in the world
- Fund getting very big (started with 3 people, by 1979 had 15)—people wanted to know about vacations, raises
- Rogers wasn't interested in getting bigger—interested in investing

### Rogers' "Retirement" (1980-present)

- 1980: "Cashed in my chips and retired"
- Term he prefers: **"Unemployed"**
- Teaching at Columbia is "unemployed"—did it part-time starting 1983 to play squash
- Still trades all the markets (currencies, commodities, bonds, stocks—long and short—all over the world)
- "I am retired now, and I still do all these markets"

**On following multiple markets**:
- "I don't see how you can invest in American steel without understanding what is going on in Malaysian palm oil"
- All part of big three-dimensional puzzle that is always changing
- Doesn't do it as actively as he used to—has developed "great deal of perspective" over the years

### Notable Trades & Experiences

**October 19 (his birthday) 1987**: Massive bond profit
- Put gigantic part of net worth into bonds throughout 1981-1982
- **August 1982**: Bonds skyrocketed—"probably the best" birthday present

**August 1971**: Very dramatic loss
- Long Japan, short America
- Nixon announced taking America off gold standard (didn't even know it happened—was on motorcycle)
- That week: Japanese market down **20%**, U.S. market up
- Losing heavily on both sides—"You can't liquidate at a time like that. Who can you sell to in Japan? Who could you buy from in the U.S.?"
- Had to figure out if right or wrong: "If there was going to be a major fundamental change forever, the first loss is the best loss. But if fundamentally you are basically correct, then you do nothing but sit there and let the market hysteria wash around you."

**Analysis**: This was not end of the world—America had simply taken short-term step, wouldn't solve country's long-term problems
- Stayed with positions
- "It turned out fine. The Nixon announcement was just another step in the dissolution of the **Bretton Woods Agreement** and the decline of America. America was rallying in its own bear market."

### Key Trading Principles

**Axiom**: "You always invest **against the central banks**. When the central banks try to prop up a currency, go the other way."

**Biggest public fallacy**: "That the market is always right. The market is nearly always wrong."

**Second fallacy**: "Never, ever, follow conventional wisdom in the market. You have to learn to go **counter to the markets**. You have to learn how to think for yourself; to be able to see that the emperor has no clothes."

> "Most people want to follow a trend. 'The trend is your friend.' Maybe that is valid for a few minutes in Chicago, but for the most part, following what everyone else is doing is rarely a way to get rich. You may make money that way for a while, but keeping it is very hard."

**Distinction on trend following**:
- Rogers' style involves staying with **economically justified trends** for years
- By "trend following" he means buying just because it goes up, selling just because it goes down
- "You have to see the supply/demand balance change early, buy early, and only buy markets that are going to go on for years."

**Trading rules**:
1. Look for **hysteria** to see if you shouldn't go the opposite way—but don't go opposite until you've fully examined the situation
2. Remember the world is always changing—**be aware of change, buy change**
3. Be willing to buy or sell anything—be **flexible and alert** to investing in anything

> "So many people say, 'I could never buy that kind of stock,' 'I could never buy utilities,' 'I could never play commodities.' You should be flexible and alert to investing in anything."

**Advice for average investor**:
- "Don't do anything until you know what you are doing"
- If make 50% two years in a row then lose 50% in third year: worse off than just putting money in money market fund
- "Wait for something to come along that you know is right. Then take your profit, put it back in the money market fund, and just wait again. You will come out way ahead of everybody else."

**On his own track record**: "There has not been a major mistake in a long time"
- But doesn't trade often—may make 3-5 decisions a year and stay with them
- Example: Owned bonds since 1981, basically still owns them. Went short dollar end of 1984.

**What makes Rogers different**: "I don't play. I just don't play."

**On selectivity**: "I have no boundaries. I am totally flexible. I am open to everything, and I pursue everything. I have no more compunction about speculating in Singapore dollars or shorting Malaysian palm oil than I do about buying General Motors."

**On waiting for convergence**: "Then I won't do anything. It happens all the time. I don't do anything until all the pieces fit."

**What happens when scenarios don't mesh**: If one scenario for currencies, one for stocks, one for bonds, and they don't all mesh—does nothing until all pieces fit.

### On Technical Analysis

- "I haven't met a rich technician. Excluding, of course, technicians who sell their technical services and make a lot of money."
- Uses charts every week for **knowledge**—to see what is going on, learn about what's happening in the world
- "I look at charts to see what has happened."
- "What has happened. If you don't know what has happened, you'll never know what is going to happen."
- Charts give him facts—"The charts say to me that there is a runaway bull market. They give me facts, but that's it."
- **Does NOT use charts predictively**—doesn't look for reversals or patterns
- Doesn't even know what a reversal is: "Don't tell me. It might mess up my mind. I don't know about those things, and I don't want to know."

### On Trading Systems

**Do markets behave differently because of trend-oriented systems?**
- No—"They may not always have been on a computer, but there always have been systems"
- Can go back 100 years and find some kind of system in every decade
- "Some kind of new formula developed to play the markets"

**Markets today same as 1970s, 1960s, 1950s—same as nineteenth century**:
- "The same things make markets go up and down. They have not changed the rules of supply and demand."

### Rogers' Current Goals

"I'm looking for adventure. I'd like to be able to wean myself more and more from the markets."

**Two problems**:
1. Investing is such a wonderful pastime, hard to give up—"I haven't changed from when I was twenty-two years old. I always wanted to read and know everything that was going on and figure out the future."
2. What to do with funds if he stops? "If I turn it over to my friendly broker at XYZ, I would be broke in five years, and then I would have to go back to work."

### Final Wisdom

> "Good investing is really just common sense. But it is astonishing how few people have common sense—how many people can look at the exact same scenario, the exact same facts and not see what is going to happen. Ninety percent of them will focus on the same thing, but the good investor—or trader, to use your term—will see something else. **The ability to get away from conventional wisdom is not very common.**"

**Summary of Rogers' core concepts**:
1. **Buy value**—if you buy value, won't lose much even if wrong

<!-- pp. 271-290 -->

## Jim Rogers' Seven Trading Principles (conclusion)

### 2. Wait for a catalyst
- Bottoming markets can remain dormant for extended periods
- Avoid tying up capital in dead markets—wait for a catalyst to change direction

### 3. Sell hysteria
- Sound principle but extremely difficult to apply
- **Rogers' methodology**: Wait for hysteria, verify market is wrong fundamentally, confirm you're right, then hold tight
- Requires rare analytical skills and intuitive insights to navigate complex market data
- Demands ability to predict long-term economic trends with high accuracy
- Even with accurate forecasts, sitting tight during counter-trend hysteria is psychologically brutal
- **Gold example**: Selling at $675, staying short through surge to $875 in four days, holding through long-term collapse
- Requires steel nerves, financial resources to outstay the market, and exceptional accuracy
- **Warning**: Unskilled attempts to apply this method can lead to financial ruin

### 4. Be very selective
- Wait for the right trade—never trade for trading's sake
- Patience to hold cash until high-probability setups appear

### 5. Be flexible
- Biases against markets or trade types limit opportunity
- Traders who refuse to short are at a distinct disadvantage
- Willingness to examine broad range of markets provides edge
- Open-mindedness superior to single-market specialization

### 6. Never follow conventional wisdom
- Helps avoid buying after major moves when consensus has already formed
- Contrarian thinking as protective mechanism

### 7. Know when to hold and when to liquidate losing positions
- If analysis was flawed (overlooked fundamental factor): "The first loss is the best loss"
- If market moves against you but original analysis remains valid: sit out the hysteria
- **Cautionary note**: Second condition should only be applied by traders who fully understand risks

---

## Mark Weinstein: High-Percentage Trader

### Background
- Former **real estate broker** who became full-time trader
- Naive start—virtually threw money away in early trading
- After initial failure, withdrew to study markets seriously
- Has traded successfully across **stocks, stock options, stock index futures, currencies, commodities**
- One disastrous trading experience, otherwise consistently successful
- Reluctant to divulge specific details but clearly profitable across all arenas

### Interview Context
- Met through mutual friend **Leigh Stevens**
- Weinstein initially reluctant due to desire for anonymity
- Multiple phone calls over months negotiating participation
- Five-hour interview conducted over deli sandwiches and soda in corner lobby
- Weinstein's mind works tangentially—tendency to go off in many directions
- Interviewer stressed need to stay focused on specific questions
- Despite efforts, interview lasted five hours and yielded 200-page transcript

### First Trade—Catastrophic Failure (1972)
- **Started with**: $8,400 in commodity account
- **Three days later**: Down to $7,800
- Went long corn based on firm's grain analyst recommendation
- Market had already been rising—was overbought when he entered
- Didn't realize he was getting in too late
- Insufficient margin to keep position going
- Lost his nerve—didn't want to add more money
- **Get-rich-quick scheme**—one of those naive money management violations

### Early Knowledge and Risk Awareness
- Knew absolutely nothing about markets
- Charts looked like "TV test patterns" to him
- Knew chances of winning were slim without knowledge
- Desperate for career change from real estate—didn't stop to learn first

### Recovery Period (6-7 months)
- Worked seven days a week renting apartments
- Sold co-ops
- Saved up about $24,000
- Took out $4,000 to live on, used remaining $20,000 to open new account

### Self-Education During Interim
- Studied **gold market**
- Learned how to chart
- Became familiar with **overbought and oversold markets**
- Strategy: Buy severely oversold market, leave enough money for two margin calls
- Figured couldn't lose unless "something drastic happened in the economy"
- Method worked in that particular market
- **"Ignorance was bliss"**

### Second Round—Building a Fortune
- Did well for several years
- Built small fortune
- Admits much was due to luck
- In those days, **commodities followed chart patterns better than now**
- Few people knew technical analysis then—markets more orderly
- Got break learning technical analysis when it was working well

### Risk Control—Nervous System Trading
- No formal risk control method then or now
- Depended on **nervous system and gut reaction**
- Covered positions when didn't feel right about them
- Sometimes after two days, sometimes after two hours

### Full Obsession
- Trading all day and all night
- Losing friends constantly
- Studio apartment with charts plastered on every wall
- Probably looked like a madman
- Slept with trading—dreamt about it
- Sometimes stayed up all night thinking about next day's moves
- Trading 24 hours a day
- **Not motivated by money at that point**—hooked on the game, the challenge of figuring out the market

### The Great American Dream
- Goal to make a million dollars
- Never had materialistic dream until started vacationing and traveling in Europe (mid-1970s)
- Had been trading 3-4 years at that point
- Had passed the million dollar mark
- Confident he could replace money spent with trading profits

### The Castle Incident—Turning Point
- Saw castle in south of France he wanted
- On market for only $350,000
- Castle had moat around it
- Would take about $50,000/year to maintain
- **Critical mistake**: Came back to U.S. wanting to make the money for castle almost immediately
- Today castle worth about $5 million
- Already had the money to buy it—didn't need to make it

> "I know people in this business who have $17 million in their trading account and won't buy a new car."

### The Soybean Disaster
- Put on large long position in **soybeans**
- Market closed up first day—about 25% profit on his money
- Planned to exit at end of week
- **Biggest mistake**: Had specific target of $350,000 profit—what he wanted from the trade
- Target determined not by market analysis but by material desire for the castle
- Didn't consider risk—took on too large a position
- Not using rational judgment—guided by material desires
- Market went up again next day, then **collapsed suddenly late in session, locking limit-down**

### Locked Limit-Down Horror
- Couldn't get out—stuck in locked limit-down position
- Next day showed up at brokerage office
- Market opened offered limit-down
- Waited all day to see if it would come off locked limit-down—it didn't
- Would have sold out at any price if market had traded

### Emotional State—Total Paralysis
- State of shock—no decision-making capability left
- Couldn't fall asleep
- Almost praying the market would somehow trade the next day
- Third day called office half hour before opening—told it didn't look like any hope
- Didn't even bother going in—couldn't face people in the office
- Certain they were getting "big thrill" out of his situation

### The Schadenfreude of Other Traders
- Few other professional traders in office never able to make the kind of money he had
- When his situation developed, seemed to justify all their years of not taking positions
- They were "really heartless"
- Only person really upset was his broker (probably afraid of losing the account)
- Other traders **overconsoled him then laughed behind his back**
- Wanted to see him come in and fall apart
- Weinstein stopped coming to the office for that reason

### Checking Quotes—Avoiding His Own Broker
- Checked with other brokerage houses trying to get price quotes
- Too embarrassed to call own broker
- Didn't want to take the derision

### The Paranoid Grains Analyst
- Starting to get paranoid and hostile
- Went to competing firm and spoke to their grains analyst
- Looking for someone to hold his hand
- Analyst told him he'd be OK—**fundamentals still strong**, tremendous demand for soybeans if market went down another day
- Of course, on fourth day, **market locked limit-down again**

### The Magnitude of Loss
- Losing about **$125,000 per day**
- At a time when average annual salary was $15,000
- Not born rich—couldn't stop thinking of loss in those terms
- Before that trade: had nearly **$1.5 million** in trading account
- Losing nearly **10% of equity each day**

### Five Days of Limit-Down Losses
- Market went limit-down **five days in a row**
- Lost over **$600,000 total**
- Fifth day: sitting in park holding hands with girl he'd picked up, literally crying on her lap
- Practically in psychotic state
- Thought about getting out of business altogether
- Started thinking what everybody was telling him was true—maybe just luck all those years
- Worried about continuing trading, winding up losing it all, forced back to job he didn't like

> "Which was more devastating, the large monetary loss, or your feelings about going from success to failure?"

- **It was the money and the limit situation, and the fact that he couldn't act**
- Exact thoughts: "Here I am, a person who thought it was un-American to go short, and what I found out was really un-American was **not being able to get out of a position**"

### Price Limits—Unfair and Harmful
- Felt cheated by not being able to exit
- To this day believes **something wrong with limit price moves**
- Believes market should be totally free of restraints
- Price limits supposedly created to protect public actually work against them
- Now average investor knows if he wants out, can at least get out at some price
- **Imagine calling broker and finding out can't even get out of market**

> "Are you implying that price limits that were supposedly created to protect the public actually work against them by preventing people from getting out of their losing positions?"

- **Yes**—market should be totally free of restraints

### Talk of Limits on Stock Markets
- Absolutely jumping from frying pan into fire
- Proposals for limits being made for benefit of sophisticated institutional investors
- **"Absolute lunacy"**—law proposed for benefit of sophisticated institutions

### Prior Long-Only Bias
- Never went short before—felt it was un-American
- After soybean trade, realized business was height of capitalism
- Made no difference which side of market you were on
- All he could think: people who were short made money and he lost money

### Emotional Impact Duration
- Months before emotional impact subsided
- Didn't want to trade commodities anymore
- Ripped every chart off walls
- Tore up everything in house related to commodities

### Return to Trading—AMEX Stocks
- After few months, started trading **AMEX stocks**
- Found it amazingly slow
- Missed leverage of commodity markets
- Didn't think could successfully support himself trading stocks

### The Options Trader Friend—Another Lesson
- Ran into friend who was great **options trader**
- Told him about experiences
- Friend suggested joining him
- First week: told to buy **Teledyne calls** right before expiration because sure they were going up
- Followed advice—**calls completely collapsed**

### $40,000 Loss on Teledyne Calls
- Lost about $40,000
- Felt extremely hostile but didn't want to show it
- Never promised any results
- So upset walked out of office and didn't come back for two days
- Friend tried reaching him during that time—didn't return calls
- Finally got message through mutual friend

### The Practical Joke That Taught Self-Reliance
- When came back to office, friend told him he'd done exact opposite trade in another account
- Trade was Weinstein's
- So didn't really lose any money
- **Wasn't a practical joke**—was trying to teach him not to place blind trust in anyone, even him
- His way of teaching importance of **self-reliance in being a good trader**

### Learning from Phenomenal Options Trader
- Did pretty well after that
- Friend was phenomenal options trader
- Knew everything about the market
- Weinstein learned tremendous amount from him

### Trading Methodology—Technical Analysis Plus
- Traded options based on methodologies friend taught
- Combined with own **technical analysis**

### Friend Didn't Use Technical Analysis
- Friend didn't believe in it
- Was a **tape reader**

### The "Technical Analysis is a Crutch" Debate
- Friend thinks technical analysis just a crutch for Weinstein
- Real reason Weinstein makes money is **experience**
- Point at which they separated for few years
- Friend came to Weinstein's office one day and watched him trade
- Embraced him like a father: **"You finally made it"**
- Told him not only had he gained experience, but learned just about everything there was about technical analysis
- Including certain things Weinstein had created himself
- Friend said: **"You never give up, do you? It has nothing to do with technical analysis. You are trading that way because of experience"**

### Why They Eventually Separated
- Conflict in trading styles
- Friend was great trader willing to take occasional large loss
- Knew he would more than make up for it with large gains and come out way ahead in long run
- Weinstein uncomfortable trading that way
- Preferred **trading for small profits and trying to eradicate losing trades**
- Wasn't willing to take same type of risk
- Weinstein's approach purely technical
- Friend basically a tape reader
- In 1980, Weinstein decided to go off on his own
- Got together again years later

### Options Trading Contest (CBOE Floor Traders)
- Originally organized by two traders on **CBOE floor**
- Got 47 traders together
- Each put up **$5,000 in winner-take-all** contest
- Each trader opened $100,000 account with same clearing firm
- **Duration**: Three months

### Contest Results—Phenomenal Performance
- Turned $100,000 into over **$900,000**
- Without any **pyramiding** (using profits to increase leverage)

> "That's a rather phenomenal performance."

- **"Yes, but the markets were very good at that time"**

### Trading After Going Independent (1980)
- Traded everything
- Continued to trade stock options
- When **stock index futures** trading began in early 1980s, became primary market
- Also traded commodity markets
- During last two years, trading shifted to nearly **90% commodities**

### The Soybean Revenge Trade
- For long time avoided soybeans
- As began finding himself trading commodity markets effortlessly, knew deep down would eventually **get back the money lost in soybeans**
- Never forgot about it

> "It sounds like you were looking for revenge."

- **"Yes, exactly"**
- Every time looked at commodity chart book, eyes would edge over to soybean chart, then quickly flip page
- Watched market peripherally for years before doing anything
- When soybeans went down to $4.75, knew near a low, but didn't want to buy until sure couldn't lose
- Like a **Sicilian whose wife had been murdered ten years earlier**, waiting for perfect moment for revenge
- When technical analysis convinced him market had bottomed for real, **jumped in on long side**

### The Redemptive Trade Details
- Bought around **$6.18** (shortly before 1988 drought caused prices to skyrocket)
- Got out of some at **$7.25**, rest at **$9.92** (high of move was $10.46)

> "How much did you make on that trade?"

- **"Let's just say I made my money back in spades"**

> "The way you talk about it, it sounds like that trade was a great relief for you."

- **"Yes, it was a total catharsis. I realized that there was a reason why I had lost the money in the first place"**

### Why Traders Get Wiped Out
- Because inexperienced
- Don't believe anyone ever gets wiped out because of bad luck
- Always some other reason
- Either off on when did the trade, or didn't have the experience
- **Always a mistake involved**

### Worst Drawdown Since 1980
- Loses so infrequently doesn't really keep track
- **No losing months since 1980**
- Could have made more money if wasn't so cautious
- **"But that is the way I trade"**
- Haven't had any losing weeks during that time
- But have had some losing days

### Incredible Consistency—No Losing Months
- Reason sure: **remembers all his losses**
- Example: Had three losing days in last two years
- Out of thousands of trades during that time, had **17 losers**
- Nine of them because quote machine was down—when that happens just gets out of position

### Win Ratio Near 99 Percent
- Most traders happy winning on 50% of trades
- Win ratio of 75% would be spectacular
- Weinstein implying win ratio **somewhere in vicinity of 99%**
- Really hard to believe
- Can check with **Leigh** (Stevens)—told him about hundreds of trades during past few years

### Verification Sidebar
- Author couldn't verify claims by checking security statements (private partnership, confidential)
- Partners vigorously maintaining confidentiality (private firm, not open to public)
- Number of partners adamantly opposed to interview
- Only account statement Weinstein willing/able to show: independent entry in the trading contest
- Did confirm multiplied $100,000 account ninefold in three months with 100% winning trades
- Still unsatisfied—spoke to **Leigh Stevens** (mutual friend who introduced them)
- Leigh known Weinstein for years, spent many days watching him trade
- Can confidently describe him as **honest, low-keyed, and levelheaded**
- Leigh confirmed of about 100 of Weinstein's trades witnessed and discussed more, could remember only one loser
- Even if faulty memory, still believe win/loss ratio incredibly high

### How Weinstein Achieves Such High Win Percentage—Author's Analysis
- Employs own custom-designed **state-of-the-art computer systems** to monitor constantly
- **Technical indicators** designed to measure changes in market momentum
- Rather than standard values for indicators, **Weinstein uses his own values**
- Frequently adjusts for changing market conditions
- Combines intensive real-time analysis with comprehensive chart analysis
- Incorporates variety of methodologies: **cycles, Fibonacci retracements, Elliott Wave analysis**
- Finally add one last essential ingredient: **uncanny sense of market timing**
- Only when nearly everything lines up right and feels timing is virtually perfect does he put on trade
- Passes up many trades he believes have high probability of working but lacks same degree of near absolute confidence
- Because of combination of lifetime devotion to studying markets, intensive real-time analysis, innate market sense, incredibly rigorous trade selection, **virtually all Weinstein's trades at least marginally profitable at some point within twenty minutes of entry**
- All Weinstein needs to assure breakeven or better result

### Trading for Quick Profits—Covering Within Hours/Minutes
- Helps understand Weinstein usually plays for quick profits
- Covers trades within hours or even minutes
- Even on position trades, will usually take some profits quickly to assure net profitable outcome
- Also trades markets in rotation
- Quickly shifting profits from market to market
- Always seeking profit potential with lowest perceived risk
- Finally enjoys support of **floor network** that often puts him on right side of bid-asked spread

### Weinstein's Comments Sound Like Boasting
- May sound like boasting on written page
- Naiveté would be much closer description
- When talks about trades, peppered with phrases: **"It's obvious the market is going lower"**, **"This market is so easy"**
- Clear has no conception of how difficult trading is for rest of us

