## Mark Weinstein Interview

### How do you explain your ability to win such a high percentage of the time?

> "Because I have a real fear of the markets. I have found that the greatest traders are the ones who are most afraid of the markets."

- Fear of markets has forced him to hone timing with great precision
- When trading properly, **like a pool player running racks**
- If gut feel of market conditions is not right, doesn't trade
- Timing is combination of experience and nervous system
- If nervous system tells him to get out of position, it's because market action triggers something in knowledge and experience seen before

### Selective Trading—Waiting for Perfect Setup
- Also doesn't lose much because waits for exact right moment
- Most people will not wait for environment to tip itself off
- Will walk into forest when still dark, while Weinstein waits until it gets light
- **Cheetah analogy**: Although fastest animal in world and can catch any animal on plains, will wait until absolutely sure can catch prey
- May hide in bush for week, waiting for just the right moment
- Will wait for baby antelope, and not just any baby antelope, but **preferably one that is also sick or lame**
- Only then, when no chance it can lose its prey, does it attack
- **"That, to me, is the epitome of professional trading"**

### Day Trading Philosophy—Sparrow vs. Pigeon
- When trades at home, often watches sparrows in garden
- When feeds them bread, they take little piece at a time and fly away
- Keep flying back and forth, taking small bits of bread
- May have to make hundred stabs at piece of bread to get what pigeon gets at one time
- **"But that is why a pigeon is a pigeon. You will never be able to shoot a sparrow, it is just too fast"**
- That is the way he day trades
- Example: Times during day when sure S&P going up, but doesn't try to pick bottom
- Out before it tops
- Just trades **mid-range where momentum is greatest**
- **"That, to me, is trading like a sparrow eats"**

> "Am I paraphrasing you correctly? The cheetah is your analogy for position trading and the sparrow is your analogy for day trading. The common denominator is that both animals wait for can't-lose circumstances."

- **Exactly**

### How do you pick your trades?

- Uses many different types of **technical input**:
  - Charts
  - **Elliott Wave and Gann analysis**
  - **Fibonacci numbers**
  - Cycles
  - Sentiment
  - Moving averages
  - Various oscillators
- People think technical analysis unreliable because tend to pick one thing they're comfortable with
- Problem: **no single technical approach works all the time**
- Have to know when to use each method

> "How do you do that?"

- **Experience and gut feel**
- Uses all forms of technical analysis but **interprets them through gut feel**
- Does not believe in mathematical systems that always approach markets same way
- Using himself as the "system"
- Constantly changes input to achieve same output—**profit**

### Most Important Element in Deciding to Put On a Trade

> "Is there anything you can single out as the most important element in deciding to put on a trade?"

- Always looking for **market that is losing momentum**, then go the other way

### Stock vs. Commodity Markets—Different Behavior

> "Having traded both the stock and commodity markets, would you say they behave differently?"

- **Absolutely**
- In contrast to commodity markets, **stock market very rarely gives opportunity to enjoy meaningful trend**

### Why Stock Markets Don't Trend

> "Why is that?"

- Because when institutions and specialists sell out, they don't sell out at one price level
- They **scale out** as market goes up
- Similarly when buy, **scale in** as market goes down
- Leads to **choppier price action**
- Reason why many good commodity traders he knows lose every time they go into stock market

### What Weinstein Does Differently in Stock Market

> "But you win consistently in the stock market, as well. What are you doing differently?"

- Doesn't try to figure out where market is going before the action
- **Lets the market tell him where it is going**
- Also such variety of technical input in stock market (divergence, advance/decline, sentiment, put/call ratios, etc.)
- Will almost always get signal before market is about to do something

### Different Technical Analysis in Stock Market

> "Is your method of technical analysis therefore different in the stock market than in the commodity markets?"

- Looks at individual stocks—**they all have their own personalities**
- Example: **IBM and Digital Equipment (Motors)** will usually rally before major market bottom and fail to rally before major market top
- As another example, never seen real good rally without **utilities leading the market**
- Utilities go up when interest rates expected to come down
- When interest rates come down, portfolio managers jump into stocks
- Has done extremely well trading indexes
- Because before ever traded index futures, had become very experienced trader of stocks and options

### Public's Biggest Misconception About Markets

> "What do you think is the public's biggest misconception about the markets?"

- That people who trade markets gamble
- Knows floor traders that have made money for **twenty straight years**
- Can't call that gambling
- Another major misconception: people always expect market to react to news
- Example: When **John F. Kennedy** assassinated, market initially broke very sharply, then quickly rebounded to new highs
- Price action baffled many people
- Investors who sold on news only to watch market reverse blamed institutions for pushing market higher
- Failed to realize **market that is fundamentally and technically poised to move higher is not going to reverse direction because of news item—even dramatic one**
- Another misconception: way media reports reasons for market being down
- Always saying market down because of **profit taking**
- **"I think it would be wonderful if everybody was always taking profits"**
- Truth is most people lose money
- Reason markets go down: because they **take their losses**
- Knows educated people who watch news and wonder why hell they lost money when everyone else taking profits
- Media owes it to public to report market goes down not only on profit taking, but **on lot of loss taking as well**

### What are the trading rules you live by?

1. **Always do your homework**
2. **Don't be arrogant**—when get arrogant, forsake risk control; best traders are most humble
3. **Understand your limitations**—everyone has limitations, even best traders
4. **Be your own person**—think against the herd, as they must lose in time
5. **Don't trade until opportunity presents itself**—knowing when to stay out of markets as important as knowing when to be in them
6. **Your strategy has to be flexible enough to change when environment changes**—mistake most people make: keep same strategy all the time; say "Damn, market didn't behave way I thought it would." **Why should it? Life and markets just don't work that way**
7. **Don't get too complacent once you have made profits**—toughest thing in world is holding on to profits; because once attained goal, then set second goal usually same as first one: to make more money; consequently for many people, attainment of that second goal not as rewarding; may begin to question what they really want from trading and trigger self-destruct process in which wind up losing

### Any final advice for beginning trader?

> "You have to learn how to lose; it is more important than learning how to win."

- If think always going to be winner, when lose, will develop feelings of hostility
- End up blaming market instead of trying to learn why you lost
- **Limit losses quickly**
- To paraphrase from ***Reminiscences of a Stock Operator***:
  - Most traders hold on to losses too long because hope loss will not get larger
  - Take profits too soon because fear profit will diminish
  - Instead traders should **fear a larger loss and hope for a larger profit**

### Author's Concluding Thoughts

- Weinstein's most traumatic trading experience occurred when he let **material goal interfere with trading**
- Common theme surfaced in other interviews
- Invariably seems to be mistake to translate potential profit or loss of trade into material terms
- Cornerstone of Weinstein's trading approach: **wait for those trades in which everything appears to be lined up exactly right**
- Odds of winning seem overwhelming
- Even though most can never approach Weinstein's confidence in trades he selects, concept of waiting for only those trades one feels most confident about is sound advice
- Echoed by number of traders in this book
- Author long believed very short-term market fluctuations (intraday price movements) were largely random
- **Weinstein has shaken this belief**


<!-- pp. 291-310 -->

## Brian Gelber (continued)

### Early Career Path
- Graduated college 1976, backpacked around US
- Started at commodity broker in Salt Lake City—essentially a "boiler room operation"
- Got broker's license while keeping charts for a scam artist pitching charting systems
- Quit after recognizing the operation was fraudulent
- Worked odd jobs (unloading railroad cars) to pay rent
- Joined **Thomson McKinnon** for $800/month doing cold calls

### Influential Books
- **Technical Analysis of Stock Trends** by Robert D. Edwards and John Magee—most formative
- First book traders read: **Reminiscences of a Stock Operator** by Edwin Lefèvre (Jesse Livermore account, 1923)—read "at least a dozen times"

### Entry into Ginnie Mae Market
- Thomson McKinnon hired trading group for new **Ginnie Mae desk**
- Attracted to it because: newer market, seemed more manageable than conventional commodities
- First Ginnie Mae trade was a winner, but subsequent trades all lost
- "It was magnetic; I felt I could make money there, but I kept losing"—created compulsion to master it
- By May 1977, making $2,000/month in commissions—"tremendous amount" for him
- Opened nearly every mortgage banker account in Salt Lake through cold calling
- Customers didn't understand they could lose; when they did, always upset

### Time Horizon Mismatch Problem
- Customers lost not because research was wrong, but because their time horizon was day-to-day
- Research from Thomson McKinnon was longer-term
- **"Basic problem between most brokers and customers: almost impossible to get market information to your customer quickly enough for them to act on it"**
- Even if broker can beat market short-term, can't translate that to customer—"insurmountable odds"
- Advice to speculators: **must trade with longer-term perspective**

### Dual Trading Conflict
- Worked as both floor broker and trader in T-bond futures simultaneously
- Never scalped large positions to avoid 2-3 tick market moves from customer orders
- Customer orders often went opposite ways, so conflict rarely mattered
- **Got trapped about 12 times when news broke and all customer orders went against his position**—cost ~$500,000 total over years
- "Measured against the amount of money I was making, it didn't kill me"—cost of doing business
- Extremely exhausting: worked very long hours for three years
- **"You can't be a great broker and a great trader. I did a good job, but it probably took years off my life"**

### Evolution on T-bond Floor
- September 1977: moved to Chicago, became broker on T-bond floor at age 25
- Visited eight big-name companies in New York (November 1977), seven opened accounts—"right place, right time"
- Started trading own account 1979
- 1979-1981: built massive customer base, became "powerful force in the market"
- **"Probably the saddest thing I ever did was to become a trader too"**—regrets not staying pure broker for 10 years
- **"I consider trading to be an unrewarding, unglamorous game"**

### First Trading Experiences
- First trade: made money on long position
- Put on long bond/short Mae spread (almost flat)—market went down, lost all profit plus $50,000
- Making ~$50,000/month as broker, so "basically broke even that month"
- Cut position size down, started trading more actively during 1979 bear market
- Problem: **stayed bullish all the way down**

### 1979 Mistake: Listening to Big Customers
- Customers like **CitiBank and Citicorp** kept saying rates couldn't go higher—buying all the way down
- "Renowned people saying they had an opinion and backing it up with deeds"
- Now understands institutions have longer time horizon—were just reallocating assets or adjusting duration
- **"Today, I have little regard for the views of portfolio managers, because their outlook tends to cover a much longer time perspective than mine"**
- Doesn't read **Barron's** interviews of portfolio managers anymore—"never did much for me"
- **Key lesson: "An opinion isn't worth that much. It is more important to listen to the market. I became a reactive trader as opposed to an opinionated trader"**

### 1980: Solomon Brothers Lesson
- **Solomon Brothers** was bearish on bonds 65-80 (1980)
- If Gelber had listened to big customers like in 1979, would have "thrown away money all over again"
- 1979 experience taught him not to base trades on others' opinions—even intelligent, sound opinions can be "absolutely wrong"

### Success Through Reading the Tape
- Learned to read tape, developed good instincts
- He and his customers were such big players that **their trades could virtually stop the market and create support/resistance points**
- "We were actually creating some of the support and resistance points"
- Didn't take much to move market back then
- Streak of months with hardly any losing days

### First Losing Year: 1986
- From trading standpoint, never had losing year until 1986
- Did struggle in 1985 during mid-stages of bull market in bonds
- Success came from being attentive and having good instincts

### Trading as Natural Talent
- **"Either you are born to be a good trader or you are not"**—don't have to be born with it, but it helps
- **Sixth sense about the market**—gut tells you what to do
- Hard work has nothing to do with it
- Bright fellow who works hard: "This is a very frustrating business. It doesn't matter how hard I work; it has no bearing on whether I make money or not"
- **"You have to know yourself and put that knowledge to work in the market"**

### Self-Knowledge Example
- Gelber acknowledges better trader working for him—doesn't compete, just lets him perform
- **Four months hot, two months cold, six months break-even cycle**
  - Four months hot: so excited can't sleep, can't wait to get to work, "just rolling"
  - Two months cold: miserable, can't sleep, can't figure out where next trade comes from
  - Six months break-even: make and lose, trying to figure out how to make money
- **"You never sleep, because you are constantly thinking too much about trading. It is an all-consuming thing"**
- Need to know yourself to moderate emotions
- After big success, high as kite—unprepared when market brings you back to earth
- When consistently losing, might jump out window
- **Left the floor because "I know myself. I need to interact with people and that doesn't happen there"**

### Physical Toll of Floor Trading
- Very intense, physically grinds you down
- In twenties/thirties, can rebound from physical/mental stress
- As you age, don't rebound as well, have to push harder to maintain performance
- **Like professional sports: "You get to a certain age and no matter how good you were—"**
- Out of 100 people who go to floor, maybe 5 make at least $1 million within five years
- At least half will lose everything they came in with

### Success Factors
- **"The reason I have been so consistent is that I'm a great listener"**
- Talks to ~25 traders daily
- Most traders don't listen—only want to tell you their opinion
- Gelber is different: honest and truly listens to what they say and how they say it
- Example: if major local calls three days in row during rally asking opinion, knows trader has been selling and is unsure—**market will probably go higher**

### Reading Other Traders
- If 20 of 25 traders nervous about market going higher (implicitly short), should trade long side
- Knows large number of people in industry—big plus
- **"I listen to them. I go with the people who are hot"**
- Sometimes his own opinion is right, goes with it
- Sometimes knows somebody else is hot, goes with their opinion
- **"I'm not picky about how I make my money. It doesn't matter if my opinion is right or wrong. All that matters is whether I make money"**

### Handling Conflicting Views
- Talks to 25 people, sometimes 15 bullish and 10 bearish
- Since 1976, always been able to read people very well, even though no one thinks he listens
- Has one cold trader who is "cold as ice right now"—listens to him
- Last night told Gelber he wanted to be short—Gelber knew he'd be long
- **"As long as he is cold, he is cold. You can't say to a trader, 'You're cold, you can't trade.' You have to let them run their course"**

### Current Trading Edge
- **Reading other traders is key component** of his personal trading now
- Only talks to people he knows very well—pliable, can understand how to read them
- Doesn't want to hear what **Jack Schwager** says because doesn't know him

### Key Trading Principles
- **"When you don't care, you do well, and when you try too hard, you don't do well"**
- Trying too hard = pressing when there's no trade
- Sitting in interview so long during trading hours because **markets haven't traded well in weeks**—proud of not throwing money away
- Not great at laying low, but gotten better with age
- Learned lesson over last couple years

### Richard Dennis Parallel
- After **Richard Dennis** left floor: "The first year I left the floor was the most painful experience for me, and I have paid the largest tuition I ever have"
- Same experience for Gelber

### Leaving the Floor
- Industry developed to point where brokerage skills no longer needed
- Everyone wanted to know: "Where's the next tick? How can I move size?"
- Price paid for particular skills too low
- Market got too voluminous—his "swing trading" style became worthless
- Just trying to read next tick instead of next 8 ticks
- Volume too big, capitalization too big—couldn't read market from floor
- Too many players

### 1985 Performance Decline
- Made under $1 million trading for first time
- Knew something was wrong—always been consistent trader making more each year
- Looked at results: profits smaller (3-4 ticks), losses greater
- First reaction: became much more active pit trader
- Found taking tremendous positions with insane risk/reward
- **Became convinced had to make a change**

### Trading Off the Floor (1987-1988)
- Pit is "very stimulating environment"
- Off floor, have to force yourself to be motivated each day—"very difficult transition"
- Not harder to trade off floor in long run—profitability in 1987-1988 "pretty good"

### 1986 Runaway Bull Market Problem
- Main problem first year off floor: still trying to trade market as he did on floor
- Transition occurred during 1986 runaway bull market
- Bound to lose because style not based on following trends

### Current Approach
- Has changed, gotten better
- Can still countertrend trade well
- Found can also make money trend following

### Trading Systems
- **"We are discretionary traders"**—only use technical indicators and systems as tools
- Developed system based on quirks related to volatility
- **Belief: volatility offers clues to trend direction**
- Backtesting shows system gives good signals
- **Do not blindly follow trades**—use as input, not mandate

### Good System Results
- For automated, computerized system: **40-50% average annual return with maximum equity drawdowns under 10%**
- Systems will always have larger maximum drawdowns than that
- Why haven't directly traded money on them

### Can Systems Compete with Good Traders?
- **"I haven't seen one yet, although there may be one somewhere"**

### Why Traders Fail
- **Large egos—can't admit they are wrong**
- Even those willing to admit wrong early in careers can't admit it later
- Some traders fail because **too worried about losing**
- **"Successful trading is a matter of trying to avoid losses, but not being afraid of them"**
- **"I'm not afraid to lose. When you start being afraid to lose, you're finished"**

### Ability to Accept Losses
- Characteristic of winning trader
- **Tom Baldwin** example: only trades the market, doesn't trade size or equity
- Doesn't say "I am long 2,000 contracts. Oh my God, that is too many, I have to sell some"
- Sells when thinks market has gone too far or when thinks position is wrong

### Most Dramatic Trade
- 1986: long bond cornered by Japanese
- Big emotional rally Monday morning
- Thought market too high at 90.00, trading over 91.00
- Sold 1,100 contracts scale-up above that level
- Market backed down, offered 1,000 lots at 91.00
- Just as thought trade nailed, **in less than five minutes market reversed and soared to 92.00**
- **Down $1 million, market only few ticks from limit bid**
- Never lost so much money so fast—because did things differently than normal

### Trade Management Philosophy
- Usually doesn't trade big early in year
- Likes to make money gradually at first, then play with money already made
- Sold more at highs, from that point only with covering
- Waited patiently, market started coming back down
- **Ended up losing only $400,000 for day**—not bad considering earlier position
- **Big emotional impact**—flabbergasted by market action
- "I had forgotten that markets could run away like that. I couldn't believe how wrong I had been"

### Japanese Corner Explanation
- When Japanese want to buy, their priority is **market share**
- First time US got good feel for how Japanese buy securities—**"they buy them all"**
- Move drove US to highs in bond market
- Japanese not fazed by low yield for risk in long bond position
- Don't look at it in terms of yield—view as whether prices going up
- If prices going up, they buy; every time they buy, prices go up more—**would buy some more**

### Did Japanese Get Out in Time?
- Yes—US dealers who desperately needed to cover because sold on way up bought most at highs

### Japanese as Smart Traders
- No, just have a style—**cannonball traders**
- Go one way, all go together
- Story: trader at Japanese shop told about trader who bought every long bond on screen
- 15 minutes later called back: "Why is the basis [price spread between cash T-bonds and futures] going out?"
- Naively noticed cash prices went way up while futures didn't go up much
- Friend: "Well, you just bought every bond available. Of course, the basis is going to go out"
- **Didn't really understand impact of their trading**

### Japanese in 1987 Equity Market
- Did same thing in US equity market as in 1986 bonds
- Practically took control, buying because prices kept going higher
- **"I'll never forgive myself for not buying stocks and selling bonds in 1987. That was going to be my number one trade in 1987"**

### Why Didn't Execute 1987 Trade?
- Reasoning: bond market had already run way up, while stocks hadn't
- Believed two markets out of line valuewise
- Knew Japanese buying high-capitalization US stocks
- Having learned their buying style in bonds, trade even more obvious
- **S&P/T-bond spread trading between $19,000-$25,000 on one-to-one contract basis**
- Went on four-day vacation, Japanese buying pushed spread to $30,000
- **Waiting for spread to break above trading range**—wanted to buy above $26,000
- At $30,000 spread, "just couldn't pull the trigger"

### Key Trading Rules
- **"Never add to a loser"**
- **What average trader does wrong: "He overtrades and begs for tips"**

### Handling Losing Streak
- **Instinctively trade smaller, sometimes just take a break**
- **"It is a good habit to wipe the slate clean and start fresh"**

### Liquidating Good Positions During Bad Streak
- **"Absolutely. They are bound to turn against you too"**

---

## Tom Baldwin Introduction

### The T-bond Pit
- Trading pit of active futures market = imposing place
- Scores of traders push over each other, shouting buy/sell orders at top of lungs
- **T-bond ring with over 500 traders** = unchallenged giant in frenetic world of futures pits
- Pit so large one side often doesn't know what's happening on other side

### Baldwin's Scale
- **Single largest individual trader in T-bond pit**
- Trading size puts him in same league as primary institutional players
- Single trades as large as 2,000 contracts ($200 million face value T-bonds) not unusual
- Typical day: may trade over 20,000 contracts (**equivalent of $2 billion face value T-bonds**)
- In early thirties, began trading T-bonds six years ago (circa 1982)

### Entry Story
- 1982: no prior trading experience
- Left job as product manager for meat-packing firm to **lease seat on Chicago Board of Trade**
- Stake only **$25,000**
- Out of skimpy capital: had to pay over $2,000/month to lease seat, at least $1,000/month living expenses
- **Wife was pregnant at the time**

### Risk-Taking and Success
- Not one to play it safe
- Aggressive risk-taking posture = key element of success
- **Turned profit from the beginning**
- **Millionaire before first year was up**, never looked back
- $30 million appears conservative estimate—true figure could be significantly higher

### Interview Context
- Essential to project because of prominence as most successful floor trader in world's largest futures market
- Baldwin not eager to be interviewed—had done some in past, grown reluctant
- Without **Brian Gelber's** generous intervention (friends who admire each other's abilities), interview would never have happened

### Interview Setting
- Gelber warned: Baldwin could be either abrasive or gracious—be prepared for former
- Arrived at Baldwin's office minutes after end of day's trading
- Just moved to new offices, furniture not yet delivered
- **Interview conducted sitting on window sill**
- **St. Patrick's Day**—sense Tom eager to join staff at local bar
- Conducted interview completely impromptu, shooting off new question second he finished answering prior one
- Often responses quite short—"felt like photographer stalking rare bird; one false step and bird would fly off"
- Interview ended abruptly after ~40 minutes when Baldwin had to leave

### How Baldwin Got Started
- Took some classes in commodities in graduate school
- Wanted to trade but didn't have money to buy seat
- 1982: found out could lease seat—began then

### Learning to Trade
- **"One lot at a time. I always had an opinion"**
- Stood there all day, developed opinion
- As opinion proved right, was reinforced even if didn't make trade
- When did trade, knew from standing there six hours/day that **most of the time opinion was right**
- **"I would see the same scenarios develop over and over again"**

### Reading Market Patterns vs. Traders
- Both—market patterns occur over and over, or market players do same thing over and over—"you just trade it"

### Initial Profitability
- Most ever down was 19 ticks—"pretty much started out profitably"

### Edge Despite No Background
- **"I worked hard. I stood there six hours a day, all day, every day"**

### Education vs. Experience
- **"You don't need any education at all to do it. The smarter you are, the dumber you are. The more you know, the worse it is for you"**

### Scalping Approach
- When putting on trade: **"To get as much as I can get out of it"**
- Taken full points or just 1 tick out of trade—"just never know"
- **"You have to watch the market, get a feel for it, and if you are in the right position, just go with it"**
- Average 4-tick profits on big positions

### Holding Time
- **"I try to make it short"**
- Minutes or seconds—**"Just because that is less risk. The object is always: Minimize your risk"**

### Evolution from Scalper
- Evolved from pure scalper to combination of scalper and speculator
- Right now: small percentage position trades, well below 10%
- Still using same basic trading style started with

### Technical Input
- Uses charts
- No intraday charts—**bar charts covering past six months**
- Starts with opinion, but if sees something to change mind, would adjust
- **Chart-influenced trading bias = key element behind winning**

### Consistency
- Consistent success—had one or two losing months, but never two together
- Less than 20% of floor traders still around after five years
- Less than that successful to point of making/keeping at least couple million
- **Only 1% reach that level**—"very small fraction of traders"

<!-- pp. 311-330 -->

## Tony Saliba (continued)

### What Separates the 1% from the 99%

- Hard work, perseverance, love of the business
- **Total disregard for money** — can't trade for money, must trade for the challenge
- **Almost no fear** — winners have less fear than losers
- Can't translate losses into real terms ("$1 million loss = great house")

### Identifying Losing Traders

- **Don't work hard enough** — think every trade has 50/50 chance, don't concentrate
- Don't watch factors affecting the market, patterns, other traders in the pit
- **Expenses too high** — can't afford to wait for the right setup
- Not paying attention, trying to pick trades randomly instead of absorbing everything

> "Most important, losers don't work hard enough. Most people walk in and think there is a 50/50 chance on any trade. They don't think there is anything more to it than that. They don't concentrate. They don't watch the factors that affect the market. You can see it in their eyes; it is almost as if there is a wall in front of their faces."

### Loss Management Philosophy

- **Get out quickly** if possible
- But choose your time — wait for optimal exit if you know it's a losing trade
- **Never give up on a trade** — patience can turn five-yard loss into two-yard loss
- If behind in a trade, let market move in your direction before selling on strength/buying on weakness
- Key element: never abandon a losing trade in panic, but maintain risk control

> "I have a lot of patience and I wait. If I know it is a losing trade, I wait for what I think is the optimum time to bail out. Then I try and reverse."

### Career Trajectory

- Started 1978, clerked six months
- Backed by wealthy grain trader for $50,000
- First two weeks: $50,000 → $75,000 with **volatility spreads**
- Spring 1979: Market went nowhere, volatility collapsed — lost almost everything
- Down to $15,000, felt suicidal, thought "I've ruined my life"

### The Comeback

- June 1979: Stopped trading, took job at Levy brothers' restaurant
- Wealthy backer called every night, never asked for money back, just moaned
- **Gave ultimatum**: "If you lose $5,000 more, we'll pull the plug"
- Learned from experienced brokers: "Be disciplined, do your homework, make $300/day = $75,000/year"
- Switched from volatile Teledyne to tight-range Boeing
- Became **spread scalper** targeting quarter or eighth of a point
- This period taught regimentation and discipline — lives by this credo today

### Scaling Up in Teledyne

- Still had remnants of big spread position in Teledyne while trading Boeing
- After five weeks in Boeing, Teledyne started moving sharply
- Rushed into Teledyne pit, adapted Boeing scalping technique but for halves and dollars
- Trading one lot at a time — other traders wanted ten- or twenty-lot orders
- First come, first served rule: brokers must fill one-lot order before larger orders
- Market makers ignored him, floor brokers couldn't

### Harassment and the Rise

- Called "one-lot" for longest time
- **Best trader in the crowd** (a legend) made Saliba's life miserable, ribbed him constantly
- After almost a year of daily harassment, backer's advice: **"A banker makes his first loan carefully, but as he gets more comfortable, he makes his loans bigger. You need to increase your size."**
- June 1980: Introduction of puts ended harassment
- Lead trader hated puts, thought they were bad for business
- Saliba studied puts intensely, became one of first market makers trading puts
- Number one trader befriended him, they worked together on **advanced option strategies**

### Working with the Legend

- Worked out strategies by hand, no computers
- Didn't have to peg market direction with spreads that had big edge
- Example: option highly overvalued because popular among member firms
- Eventually Saliba felt he was doing more work while top trader relied on ability to muscle the market
- Top trader strayed from their strategies, even tried to hurt Saliba
- Saliba broke away: "Forget it, I'm working on my own"

### The Bull Market Explosion (1981-1982)

- Interest rates went through roof in 1981
- Early 1982: Strategy worked really well, making a lot of money
- **Bull market in 1982**: Days making $200,000
- Clearinghouse couldn't believe the sheets — "tons of paper"

### Trading Strategy: Matrix Trading

- Trades everything on screen as it interrelates to everything else
- Basic strategy: **Butterflies** (long or short position at one strike balanced by opposite positions in higher and lower strikes)
  - Example: Long one IBM 135 call, short two IBM 140 calls, long one IBM 145 call
  - Offsetting an explosion position
- **Limited risk, profits from time decay if market doesn't move widely**
- Bought butterflies cheap, chained them together for fairly wide profit zone
- Then did **explosion position** in more distant month

### Explosion Positions

- Saliba's term for option position with **limited risk and open-ended potential**
- Profits from large price move or volatility increase
- Example: Long out-of-the-money calls and long out-of-the-money puts
- As market moves, **delta increases in your favor** — betting on volatility
- Front month: butterfly (time decay works for you)
- Mid/back month: explosion position (big move bet)
- Scalping helps pay for time decay in explosion position

### Usually Delta Neutral?

- Usually offsetting positions
- Once in a while took significant net position

### First Really Big Trade: Teledyne 1984

- Stock had dropped sharply, building position in **out-of-the-money October calls**
- Pacific Coast Exchange traders leaning on his longs on the close every night
- Instead of backing down, **stepped up and bought them**: "You want to sell at 1¼, I'm 1¼ bid for fifty"
- Went on for over ten trading days
- May 9, 9:20 AM: Trading stopped — **"Teledyne Announces a Stock Repurchase Program at $200 per Share"**
- Stock at $155, owned the $180 calls
- Overnight: **made millions**
- Next four to five months were great

### Retirement at Thirty

- Goal: Become millionaire before thirty and retire
- Millionaire before twenty-five
- May 5, 1985 (thirtieth birthday): Walked off floor, said goodbye, "never going to come back"
- Up about $8-9 million

### Four-Month Retirement

- Missed the markets, missed the excitement
- Money became secondary — trading was his life, gave him reason for being

### October 1987 Stock Crash

- Expecting big move but didn't know direction
- Built same type of position as in Teledyne
- **Butterfly spread + explosion position**
- Explosion position: Long out-of-the-money puts and calls in back months
- Butterfly spreads in front month (profit from time decay)

### Reading the Crash

- Could feel it in **wild gyrations by late September**
- At first thought upside, then changed mind
- Wednesday before crash: Market fell apart
- Thursday: Didn't bounce back, just churned
- Friday: **Market cracked** — "I was sure we were going down"
- Friday at end of week + high correlation between Friday action and Monday follow-through = conviction
- Bought out-of-the-money calls Friday for protection — always has insurance

> "A trader once told me, 'Saliba, in stealing second, you never take your hand off first until your other hand is on second.' That's the way I am; I always have insurance."

### Monday Morning, October 19, 1987

- Awfully confident market going sharply lower
- **Success magazine story misleading** — made it sound like he plotted to avoid the floor
- Reality: Concerned about positions held by clearing firm
- One guy had huge position he wasn't closing — Saliba spent time on phone managing that
- Also **sold his seat** before market opened — figured someone else would hit the bid anyway (had seven seats)

### Reflections on Baldwin Interview

- Baldwin's incredible achievements made him ideal interview candidate
- Didn't expect comments to be pertinent to off-the-floor traders
- Surprisingly yielded relevant insights

### Key Insight: Don't Think About Money

- Baldwin's most important point: **Not viewing trading in terms of money**
- Money is only means of keeping score
- Most traders think of gains/losses in monetary terms — gets in the way of trading decisions
- Example: Down $2,000 on planned $5,000 risk, might liquidate because "extra $3,000 can pay for my vacation"
- **Translating risk into tangible terms causes impulsive liquidation**

### Unconventional Wisdom: Don't Exit Losing Trades Too Hastily

- Wait and choose your time rather than bailing immediately
- Seems to contradict basic tenet of cutting losses quickly
- Baldwin's point: Often worst time to bail is during violent price move against you
- **By bearing the pain a little longer, may find more favorable liquidation circumstance**
- Only for disciplined traders with ability to maintain risk control strategy

<!-- pp. 331-350 -->

## Tony Saliba (continued)

### October 1987 Crash — Risk Management Under Extreme Volatility

- **Monday seat trade**: First time trading exchange seats round-turn (sold $452,000 morning, bought back $275,000 afternoon)
- Kept 95% of massive position through Monday close despite huge profits
- Rationale: Long puts were 30 points in-the-money at $30, almost entirely **intrinsic value** with no time premium
- Given extreme volatility, waiting was rational
- Hedged Monday close by buying more insurance — covered hundreds of short calls

> "Half the world wanted puts, and half the world wanted calls. But everybody wanted volatility."

- Tuesday became massive volatility demand — "the register really started ringing"
- **Contrast with failed traders**: They assumed Monday was normal correction, bought every dip thinking bounce was coming

### Why Saliba Succeeded vs. Failed Traders

- **Clean slate approach**: Always hedged, always prepared, knows exact worst-case risk at all times
- Failed traders didn't know their position risk
- Example: **Jack** (million-dollar annual earner) froze on Tuesday morning — shell-shocked, unable to act, missed all opportunity

> "He wasn't sure what his position risk was. I always define my risk, and I don't have to worry about it. I walk into the pit every day with a clean slate."

### Trading Philosophy Core Principles

**Public misconceptions about markets:**
- Belief that market must go up to make money
- **Reality**: Can profit in any market with right strategies (futures, options, underlying markets)
- American bullish bias: Government ignored program trading during 3-year bull market, then rushed to regulate once it crashed
- People need neutral standpoint: long some categories, short others, but **limit short-side risk** (infinite downside)

**Handling losing periods:**
- Two causes: bad day trading OR bad position
- If bad position, exit immediately
- Metaphor: "When you are in a boat that springs a leak, you don't drill another hole to let the water out"
- If losses from bad decisions: take day off, "lay out in the sun and bake," let stress dissipate

**Elements of good trading:**
- **Clear thinking, focus, extreme discipline** (discipline is #1)
- Take a theory and stick with it, but be open-minded enough to switch if proven wrong
- Must say: "My method worked for this type of market, but we are not in that type of market anymore"

### Trading Rules

- **Scale in and scale out** to spread risk — don't do large orders up front
- **Respect the marketplace** — never take anything for granted
- **Do homework nightly**: Recap the day, figure out right/wrong actions, project tomorrow's scenarios ("what-ifs")
- **Anticipate and plan** rather than react

> "What do I want to happen tomorrow? What happens if the opposite occurs? What happens if nothing happens? Think through all the 'what-ifs.'"

### Personal Evolution and Goals

- Early goals: monetary (millionaire before 30 — achieved before 25)
- Now: quality of life matters more than dollar targets
- Current projects: trading company, software company, family goals
- Used to judge success like **Bruce Springsteen** in rock — being the best
- Now realizes: "All the money in the world isn't the answer"
- Money is influential (changes how people perceive you), but doesn't bring fulfillment

**Trading's impact on personal life:**
- Handles business well, but "clobbers" social life
- Doesn't allow time for women and friends
- Mind always on trading — even dinner dates end with staying up till 2 AM figuring out trades
- "It's an addiction"
- Stopped taking work on dates, but always thinking about trading

**What makes Saliba different:**
- "I think I can do anything, and I'm not afraid of hard work"
- Working with French bank on trading company deal
- Loves the challenge of training new traders with hundreds of millions in capital

---

## Part V: The Psychology of Trading

### Dr. Van K. Tharp — Introduction

**Background:**
- **Research psychologist**, Ph.D. from University of Oklahoma Health Sciences Center (1975)
- Career studying how stress affects human performance
- Developed **Investment Psychology Inventory** (1982) — test measuring winning/losing traits
- Thousands of investors/speculators have taken the test (written evaluation + 10-minute phone consultation)
- Five books on successful investing, core of investment course
- Contributing editor for *Technical Analysis of Stocks and Commodities*
- Glendale, California office — full-time trader counseling

**Research focus:**
- Interviewing/studying top traders to create success model
- Theory: Teaching winning traits (not specific methodologies) improves performance
- Recent project: turning successful clients into "super-traders" via extended semiannual process

**Interview context:**
- **Four-hour videotaped interview** of author (Schwager) by Tharp
- Tharp's probing questioning style: "What else?" repeated multiple times
- Gaze-shifting instruction to access different brain parts
- Interview yielded personal insights for Schwager

---

### Dr. Van K. Tharp Interview

#### Origins of Psychology-Trading Connection

**Early career:**
- Post-Ph.D. research: how drugs affect human performance
- Helped standardize **Field Sobriety Test Battery** (still used by police)
- Simultaneously lost money trading options — consistently, rapidly
- Concluded losses had something to do with him personally

**Prosperity class insight:**
- Church of Religious Science: "What happens in your life reflects your mindset"
- Tested concept by developing Investment Psychology Inventory
- Sent to **R.E. McMaster** (newsletter editor) → offered to subscribers
- Close to 1,000 responses → roused career interest

#### Investment Psychology Inventory — Key Findings

**Test structure:**
- Multiple success measures to rank by "success level"
- 10 areas suggested by investment literature
- Statistical analysis: significant correlation between each area and success
- **Three major clusters**: psychological factor, management/discipline factor, decision-making factor
- Refined over time but same three clusters remain
- Added 11th area: **intuition**

**Eleven areas measured:**

1. **Psychological factor** (5 areas):
   - Well-rounded personal life
   - Positive attitude
   - Motivation to make money (not significantly correlated with success, but kept because high motivation + high conflict = very significant)
   - Lack of conflict
   - Responsibility for results

2. **Decision-making factor** (3 areas):
   - Solid knowledge of technical factors (little relationship to success)
   - Aptitude for sound decisions without common biases
   - Ability to think independently

3. **Management-discipline factor** (3 areas):
   - Risk control
   - Patience
   - Intuition (no relationship found to success, but kept for interest)

#### Profile of the Losing Trader

**Composite losing trader:**
- Highly stressed, little stress protection
- Negative outlook, expects the worst
- High internal conflict, blames others when things go wrong
- No rule-based behavior, crowd follower
- Disorganized and impatient
- Wants action now

Most losing traders aren't as bad as composite — just have part of the losing profile.

#### Consulting Practice Origins

- People asked for help with specific problems after taking test
- Didn't know how to respond initially
- Decided to write **pamphlets on each of 10 areas**
- First pamphlet became a book
- After second workbook, started training in **Neuro-Linguistic Programming (NLP)**
- **NLP**: science of duplicating success
- Incorporated NLP techniques into course
- Course development naturally led to private consulting

#### Evolution of Beliefs

**Initial belief:** Test designed to predict who could win and who couldn't
**Current belief:** Anyone can win if committed to doing so — just a matter of learning how

- People get stuck by beliefs they hold, yet cling to old beliefs
- Tharp's beliefs constantly evolving, valued by utility
- Admits most beliefs probably wrong
- Example: May be people who can't succeed even if committed, but most useful belief right now is that anyone can win
- Makes Tharp much more effective at helping people become winners

#### Case Examples — Success and Failure

**Case 1: Trader unable to trade for over a year**
- 45-minute drop-in session before full consultation
- Educated guess: conflict problem
- Ten-minute exercise to mentally integrate results
- Two weeks later: trading again
- Had spent money on many solutions, none worked — ten-minute exercise solved it

**Case 2: Man in late 40s living with mother**
- Couldn't accept adult responsibilities
- Whole lifestyle supported being a child
- Only wanted to trade to continue lifestyle
- Would have required major lifestyle commitment to change — unwilling to give it

**Case 3: Reluctant follow-up consultant**
- Minor adjustments after two days of consulting
- Thought follow-up would be superfluous
- Two more days → simple exercise → totally changed person (took week to integrate)
- Two months later: made over $650,000 trading

#### Distinguishing Skill vs. Psychology Problems

**Before accepting client:**
- Need to know they have some methodology that works
- Determine evidence: Can they convince Tharp? Have they tested it?
- Testing = actual trading signals to follow (not hindsight evaluation)
- Skeptical of day trading or short time frames

**Psychology can manifest as lack of skill:**
- People don't develop systematic approach or test it due to poor judgment, lack of goals, internal conflict, etc.
- Area needing help: overcoming internal resistance to developing systematic approach
- If someone said that was their problem, Tharp would accept as client

### Primary Psychological Impediments

#### 1. Poor Risk Attitudes

**Two golden rules of speculation:**
- Cut losses short
- Let profits run

**Problem:** Most people can't deal with these rules

- If making money is important → investment games matter → trouble taking small losses
- Small losses become moderate losses (even harder to take)
- Moderate losses become big losses (forced to take because it was too hard to take small loss)
- With profits: want to take immediately ("better take this now before it gets away")
- Bigger the profit, harder to resist temptation to take it now

**Result:** Most people are **risk-aversive** with profits (prefer sure smaller gain over wise gamble for larger gain) and **risk-seeking** with losses (prefer unwise gamble over sure loss)

- Most people do opposite of what's required: **cut profits short, let losses run**

**Solution — Trading as a game:**
- Review rules at beginning of day
- Review trading at end of day
- If followed rules even while losing money: pat yourself on the back
- If didn't follow rules: mentally rehearse better choices for future
- Mistake = not following rules of the game

#### 2. Dealing with Stress

**Two forms:**
- Worry (mental preoccupation)
- Biological fight/flight response

**Limited brain capacity:**
- Worry takes up most decision space
- Not enough capacity left to perform effectively

**Fight/flight response effects:**

1. **Narrowed focus** → revert to earlier well-practiced response patterns
   - Under stress: do what did as beginner, do what broker advises, do anything simple
   - Simple solutions rarely correct
   - Also become crowd followers (others provide simple example)
   - Crowd following = sure way to lose money

2. **Increased energy expenditure** → doesn't help make more money, leads to quick irrational choices
   - Use excess energy on losing position by actively resisting closing it out
   - Result: bigger loss
   - Fight/flight response decreases performance by narrowing choices and concentrating energy on remaining alternatives

**Solutions:**
- Work on causes, develop stress protection
- Recommend stress management program for this problem
- Understand many stressful events are stressful because of how you perceive them
- Change perceptions → change the event itself

**Winners vs. losers — attitude about losses:**
- Most people become anxious about losses
- Successful speculators: learned that essential ingredient to winning is making it OK to lose
- Most people in our culture taught only winning is acceptable
- Most investors must change beliefs about losses to become successful

#### 3. Dealing with Conflict

**Parts model:**
- People have different parts with different positive intentions
- Examples: part to make money, part to protect from failure, part to feel good about self, part for family welfare, etc.
- Once parts established, they operate subconsciously
- Parts adopt new behaviors to carry out intentions
- Sometimes new behaviors produce major conflicts

**Model usefulness:**
- Not saying people actually have parts
- Very useful in helping people solve trading problems
- Must make parts aware of each other, conduct formal negotiation between parts so each is satisfied
- If possible, integrate parts to join together

**Example: Floor trader with successful father (alcoholic)**
- Developed part to protect from being like father
- Could make $75,000/year trading, but no more
- If made more, part kicked in to ensure wouldn't become too successful
- Made $650,000 in two months after complete negotiation

#### 4. Subconscious Desire to Lose

**Half of traders Tharp works with have this problem** — very common

**Are some people fulfilling positive intention by losing?**
- Yes — subconscious level fulfills some other positive intention

#### 5. Emotional Control

**Fourth major problem:** Many people allow emotions to control trading

- Most trading problems involve emotional control somehow
- Know at least 10 methods to help people control mental states
- Easy method: control posture, breathing, muscle tension
- Change those factors → probably change emotional state

#### 6. Making Decisions

**Fifth major problem:** Decision-making

- Many facets to decision-making problems
- What most people do: bring normal method of making decisions to trading markets
- Example: Buying new car — think about model, make, deal, service, cost, accessories, etc. — takes week or more
- Most people bring same method to trading — doesn't work, takes too much time

**Solution:**
- Adopt trading system that gives signals to act
- But most people with trading system continue applying normal decision method to signals
- That doesn't work

**Best method for long, ineffective decision-making problems:** Short circuit via **anchoring** process (too involved to explain in interview)

### Can Most People Become Successful Traders?

**Eliminating negative emotions:**
- Assumes negative emotions are cause of trading problems
- Tharp thinks they're just a symptom of basic problem
- In most cases, don't believe it's necessary to solve specific problems to produce success
- Simply have to teach people to do things in an effective manner
- Teaching process involves working with how people think — must deemphasize solving problems

**Current self-concept:**
- Considers himself expert modeler
- "If someone can do something well, then I can figure out how they do it and teach those skills to anyone else"
- Concentrating on modeling trading and investment excellence
- Believes can teach anyone committed to being successful trader to be one of the best

**Superior traders:**
- Better emotional control
- Both emotional control and analytical skills overemphasized

### Duplicating Successful Trading

**Three primary factors:**
- Beliefs
- Mental states
- Mental strategies

If duplicate how best traders use these three factors for every trading task aspect → can duplicate results

**Modeling example — martial arts:**
- Experts believe it takes years of practice to break board with bare hand
- Observed someone for 15 minutes, broke two ½-inch pine boards with hand
- Showed 10-year-old son how to do it
- That's the power behind modeling

**Unconscious competence:**
- Most experts do things well automatically (unconsciously competent)
- Don't even think about it when doing it
- When unconsciously competent person tries explaining to someone else, much of what's important is left out
- Tharp's focus: discover missing pieces, help people install those pieces

### First Factor: Beliefs

**Army sharpshooter modeling example:**
- Army modeled rifle skills of two best sharpshooters in U.S.
- Developed training class for recruits:
  - Reduced training time from 4 to 2 days
  - Increased qualification rate from 80% to 100%
- Used same knowledge to help top shooters improve further
- Information about shooting beliefs particularly revealing

**Top two shooters' beliefs:**
- Shooting well important for survival
- Hunting is fun
- Mental rehearsal important to successful performance
- If I miss a shot, it has something to do with my performance

**Differences between #1 and #2:**
- Best shooter: Important to rehearse entire 1,000-round match prior evening
- Second best: Mental rehearsal important in addition
- Best shooter: Important to hit center of bull's eye each shot (even though no extra points)
- Second best: Only important to hit bull's eye

Can understand why one was better than other just from beliefs.

**New Army recruits' beliefs:**
- Guns are evil; they kill people
- Shoot weapon too many times → might go deaf
- Miss target = gun is misaligned

Just on beliefs alone, can begin to understand why top shooters better than raw recruits.

**Top traders' beliefs (from Tharp's research):**
- Money is NOT important
- It is OK to lose in the markets
- Trading is a game
- Mental rehearsal is important for success
- They've won the game before they start

**Why these five beliefs are critical:**
- Most people approach trading to make a lot of money → primary reason they lose
- Because money so important: trouble taking losses and letting profits run
- When think of trading as game and play by certain rules → much easier to follow two golden rules

**Mental rehearsal and extensive planning:**
- Top traders have gone through all trial and error in mind before beginning
- Know they're going to win in long run
- Makes little setbacks much easier to deal with

#### Justified vs. Misplaced Confidence

**Question:** How does novice distinguish between justified and misplaced confidence? (Example: first week on skis, confidence about expert slope might not be great quality)

**Answer — Three major differences:**

1. **Justified confidence comes from constellation of beliefs** (like the five described)
   - If trader has confidence and nothing else: probably in trouble

2. **Justified confidence comes from extensive testing** of some model of trading
   - If don't have model properly tested: confidence probably misplaced

3. **Justified confidence comes with extensive commitment** to being successful as trader
   - Most people who want to be traders not committed — just think they are

**Commitment example:**
> "That the moment that one definitely commits oneself, then Providence moves too." — W.N. Murray, Scottish Himalayan expedition

- If really committed: not only certain you're doing right thing, but somehow events just seem to occur to help you
- If really committed to being trader: probably understand at some level what Tharp is talking about
- Probably understand that events helping you might be big losses
- If not committed: probably saying "I don't understand what Tharp is saying. I'm committed, but events certainly have not been helping me."

### Second Factor: Mental States

**If ask people to list trading/investment problems:**
- Two types: own problems and mental state control problems
- Problems don't own:
  - Blaming markets
  - Blaming floor traders/locals
  - Blaming insider trading
  - Blaming broker
  - Blaming system

**Natural tendency:** Blame something other than ourselves

**Society promotes this:**
- Recent media coverage of program trading: virtually implies investors who lost money did so because of this activity (not any fault of their own)
- When blame something other than yourself: can continue to repeat mistake (result of something beyond control)

**Best thing investor can do when things go wrong:**
- Determine how he/she produced those results
- Don't mean should blame yourself for mistakes
- Mean at some point in time, for any situation, made choice that produced those results
- Determine what that choice was
- Give yourself other options to take when encounter similar choice point in future
- Change decision at similar choice points → change results
- By imagining doing so now: can make it easy to select those alternatives in future

**When people own their own problems:**
- Discover results usually stem from some mental state
- Common examples:
  - I'm too *impatient* with markets
  - I get *angry* at markets
  - I'm *afraid* at wrong time
  - I'm too *optimistic* about what will happen

**Mental state identification:**
- Once identify mental state problem: can do something about it (within your control)
- Already mentioned how one can use body posture, breathing, muscle control to manipulate mental state

**Mental state manipulation exercise:**
- Go into shopping mall, notice how other people walk
- Duplicate dozen or so walks for yourself
- Notice how mental state changes with each one

**Controlling mental state:**
- Not magic solution to trading success
- Just part of answer
- When admit answer is within yourself: come a long way
- Realization that you are responsible for results = key to successful investing
- Winners know they're responsible for results
- Losers think they are not

#### Practical Mental State Control Example

**Simple procedure can use right away:**
1. At desk, become aware you're in mental state you'd like to change
2. Get up out of chair
3. Walk away about four feet
4. Look at how you looked in that chair (posture, breathing, facial expressions)
5. Imagine how you would look if you had the mental state you'd like
6. When can see that clearly, sit down in chair again
7. Assume position you just imagined

**Why this works:**
- Involves several important principles
- Changing body posture
- Seeing yourself from more objective viewpoint
- Imagining more resourceful state

### Third Factor: Mental Strategies

**Understanding strategies:**
- People think in same modalities as five senses: visual images, sounds, feelings, tastes, smells
- Those five modalities to mental strategies as alphabet to great novel, or as musical notes to great symphony
- It's not the elements, but the way elements are put together
- Mental strategy = specific sequence of mental representations that leads to particular outcome


<!-- pp. 351-370 -->

## Van Tharp Interview (continued)

### Mental Strategies and Trading Psychology

**Mental strategy is the sequence in which you think**—not just the content, but the order matters crucially for execution.

- Van Tharp gives example: Same trading signal, two different thought sequences
  - Strategy 1: See signal → Recognize familiar → Think what might go wrong → Feel bad about it → Probably won't trade
  - Strategy 2: See signal → Recognize familiar → Feel good about it → Probably will trade
- "If you are trading a system, you need a simple strategy like the last one in order to use it effectively"

### Mechanical vs. Intuitive Traders

**Two contrasting super-trader profiles** from Van Tharp's research:

**The Mechanical Trader:**
- Constructs models visually in imagination
- Very logical, precise language and thinking
- Models focus on how to trade successfully and how economy works
- Won't trust models until computerized—matches mental image with computer output "until they both look right"
- Slow, laborious process but removes him from daily trading decisions
- Computer does everything once models validated—decision making becomes easy

**The Intuitive Trader:**
- Developed model of how markets operate, not how to trade them
- Believes markets constantly evolving—more important to track changes than test models
- Trades from expectations (visualizations), converts these into feelings
- "Feelings actually are a mode of thinking, but they are difficult to communicate to others or to computerize"
- Believes computerizing trading system is waste of time
- Makes day-to-day decisions easily through intuition—calls it intuitive
- Uncomfortable until proven by computerization (mechanical trader), or makes decisions instantly based on feel (intuitive trader)

**Similarities between both types:**
- Both developed models and did extensive testing research
- Both share common beliefs about successful trading
- Both very aware of their purpose in life and as traders
- Both believe they are "part of a bigger picture" and go with the flow

### Most Difficult Problems to Solve

**Only two difficult problems:**

1. **Lack of commitment**—people won't do what Van Tharp tells them unless truly committed to becoming good traders
   - Example: man who wanted to remain a little boy, using trading to accomplish that
   - Van Tharp doesn't see noncommitted traders often

2. **Traders who don't own their problems**—can't get at source, keep repeating mistakes
   - Van Tharp usually doesn't see these people either

**Most difficult client type: compulsive gambler**
- Crave market action, won't seek help until heavily in debt
- Usually refers to Gamblers Anonymous or local help
- Exception: one compulsive trader now in super-trader program
- "I've simply channeled his compulsiveness from the markets into working on himself"

### Teaching Trading—The Right Approach

Van Tharp debates two approaches to teaching trading:

**Approach 1 (Traditional):**
- Session 1: Give fundamentals
- Session 2: Give simple trading system
- Remaining sessions: Deal with their problems trading that system
- "That would probably be a very effective class"

**Approach 2 (Van Tharp's preferred):**
- Give fundamentals
- Give beliefs, mental states, and mental strategies necessary to trade the system
- Then give them the system
- "I'm willing to bet that the second method would be more effective than the first. At least that is the direction I'm heading."

### The Super-Trader Program

**Origin story:**
- Started Christmas Eve when client called—made $650,000 in two months since finishing work together
- Van Tharp thought: "What if we pushed this to the limits? What is he capable of accomplishing?"
- Called client, suggested the idea—"Naturally, he was all for it"

**Current status:**
- About four clients graduated to super-trader program
- Continues working with them regularly (usually semiannually)
- Goal: stretch performance to the limits
- "Many people aren't ready for that, but I have enough among my clients who are"
- In 3-4 years, might have about 50 top traders on continual basis
- "Incidentally, I find that my best clients now make excellent models to use to study top traders"

### Dreams and Market Direction

**Van Tharp sometimes has dreams about impending market direction—they prove right at high percentage**

- Common phenomenon among top traders—both mechanical and intuitive super-traders had amazingly accurate market dreams
- Most traders say dreams too infrequent to trade on regularly
- May occur more frequently than imagined in symbolic form—but people don't interpret, so miss symbolic predictions

**Famous examples of creativity from dreams:**
- **Michael Jackson**—claims doesn't write songs, they just come to him
- **Paul McCartney**—heard "Yesterday" in a dream
- **Einstein**—essentially dreamed theory of relativity
- "It all boils to what intuition really is, but don't ask me to explain it. I don't understand it—YET!"

### Why Van Tharp Doesn't Trade

**Two reasons for not trading:**

1. **Objectivity with clients**—if trading with conflicting positions, may not be objective about what clients are doing

2. **Fully committed to current work**—loves helping others, writing, giving talks
   - Already 60-hour per week job
   - To start trading would require nearly as much time initially
   - "Why should I do that and give up what I already know I love doing?"
   - Analogy: "Player coaches, in the history of most sports, usually are not that effective at either coaching or playing"

**No conflict about commitment to trading:**
- As he gets more into helping others succeed, has less interest in trading himself
- Currently investing in himself and business—that's paying off
- "Constantly work at improving my skills and knowledge, and that is paying off for me"
- Future possibilities: might decide done everything possible, want change, or want break
- "For example, three to four years from now I might just be working with fifty or more top quality traders. If that happens, then maybe I'll also trade. But for the near future, it doesn't seem very likely."

## The Trade: A Personal Experience

**Jack Schwager's personal trading story**—motivated by quest for self-discovery.

### Background and Motivation

- Net profitable trader over the years (substantially multiplied small initial stake twice)
- Had definite sense of failure about trading despite profits
- Given knowledge and experience, felt winnings were "small potatoes compared to what I should have made"
- Correctly anticipated major price moves on numerous occasions but didn't capitalize fully

**Catalyzing conversations:**
- One evening: interviewed by **Dr. Van Tharp** at length about trading
- Very next evening: probing conversation with **Ed Seykota** about trading
- Back-to-back experience caused intense focus on flaws preventing reaching true potential

### The Pattern: Initial Positions Too Small

**Schwager's great error: failing to exploit major price moves he had correctly anticipated**

- Invariably, initial position far too small given perceived potential
- Compounded by premature liquidation of position
- Typically took profits on first leg, intended to reenter on correction
- Problem: subsequent corrections fell short of reentry points
- Result: watched rest of price move unfold from sidelines
- Vowed next time to come closer to realizing true potential of trade

### The Silver/Swiss Franc Trade

**Setup (on plane to Chicago two weeks later):**
- Reviewing charts from previous evening
- Distinct impression: precious metal prices ready to move higher
- Foreign currency markets appeared vulnerable to further erosion
- Suddenly crystallized: should trade long precious metals/short foreign currencies

**Analysis and implementation:**
- Next morning found quote machine
- Evaluated price relationships between silver, gold, platinum
- Decided silver was preferred metal among precious metals
- Reviewed interrelationships between foreign currencies
- Decided Swiss franc weakest currency
- Reviewed silver/Swiss franc ratio charts (ten years to one month)
- Conclusion: "at the brink of a possible multiyear advance of silver relative to the Swiss franc"

**Trade mechanics:**
- Traveling prevented paying attention to markets—needed base position minimum
- Ratio trade requires approximately equal dollar positions in each market
- Calculation: three long silver contracts to balance one short Swiss franc contract at prevailing prices

**Execution and immediate aftermath:**
- Short-term chart showed price ratio already moved sharply in intended direction since previous morning's realization
- Even on opening, could have implemented at much more favorable levels
- Ratio continued moving higher and higher as Schwager decided what to do
- "I decided that I had to act to prevent the possibility of missing this trade altogether"
- Called in order: minimum position of long three silver/short one Swiss franc
- No sooner placed order than ratio peaked and began retreating
- "As it turned out, I had managed to implement the trade at the exact worst possible moment in time since the inception of my idea"
- Ratio pulled back further during next two days
- Silver/Swiss franc ratio quickly recovered—few days later well ahead

### Position Management and Doubling Down

**Week one reflection:**
- Thought about recent realization regarding continued failure to profit adequately from major price moves
- Decided to maintain position and selected reaction point for doubling up
- Correction came about week later—followed game plan
- Timing proved good—trade rebounded in favor immediately
- Doubled initial position with double initial position

**Position size:**
- Given account size (approximately $70,000), long six silver/short two Swiss franc about twice normal size
- "My efforts to correct my aforementioned trading flaw seemed to be paying off, as the trade raced in my favor during the following two weeks"
- Within month of putting on trade, account up over 30%

### The Dilemma and Dream

**Faced dilemma:**
- New-found realization suggested hang on for long run
- But another rule: if lucky enough to realize very large profit very quickly, take it—usually get opportunity to reenter at considerably more favorable levels
- Silver/Swiss franc price ratio began falling

**Cursory chart examination suggested might be prudent to take at least partial profits**

- But combination of new job plus writing book left very little time and energy
- Instead of necessary analysis, made snap judgment to stay with trade
- Trade moved swiftly against him—within week given back significant portion of earlier gains

**The dream:**
- That night had a dream
- Talking to friend (developer of software for futures/options markets analysis, not a trader)
- In dream, friend had begun trading, talking about current dilemma regarding silver/Swiss franc position
- Friend commented: "Everybody gets what they want out of the markets"
- Schwager replied: "You sound just like Ed Seykota"
- To surprise: "I have been talking to Ed Seykota for a while and I have been winning in my trading ever since"

### Dream Analysis and Message

**Friend's response revealed Schwager's trading flaw:**
- Had sheet showing month-to-month ending equity
- Last figure exceeded $18 million
- Schwager: "Bert, you have made $18 million in the market! I hope you plan to take a few million out for safekeeping"
- Friend: "No, I need all the money for trading"
- Schwager: "But that is crazy. Take $3 or $4 million out, and that way you will be sure then that no matter what happens, you will come out way ahead"
- Friend: "I know what I am doing, and as long as I do my homework on the markets every day, I am not concerned"

**Schwager's implied realization:**
- His answer had implied, quite correctly, that he did not diligently do homework on markets every day
- Friend's point, though unstated, quite clear: If did work on markets every day, wouldn't have trouble understanding why didn't need to pull out several million dollars in profits to feel confident wouldn't lose back all profits in trading

**The $18.50 per hour calculation:**
- Friend showed assumptions regarding book sales, royalties per copy, total hours spent writing
- Scribbled calculations on yellow pad
- Arrived at $18.50 per hour
- "Here, this is what you are making on your book"
- Tone implied Schwager was crazy to jeopardize tens of thousands of dollars in trading for such paltry sum
- (Actually, $18.50 estimate probably wildly overinflated, but dream)

**Timing of dream:**
- No coincidence—occurred night after editing Marty Schwartz interview section dealing with his diligence in daily homework
- Realized: no shortcuts to being good trader
- Must do work on markets every day
- If not enough time, have to make time
- Costs of straying from daily discipline very substantial in lost profit opportunities and losses
- "The message my subconscious seemed to be crying out was: If you are going to be serious about trading, you have to reestablish your time priorities"

## Postscript: Dreams and Trading

### Anonymous Trader Dream Story (1980 corn)

**Setup:**
- 1980, year corn set record high, trader was long position limit
- Dream: "Hey Jerry, where is corn going to?" "To $4.15." "Where is corn now?" "$4.07." "You mean you are taking all that risk for an extra eight cents? Are you crazy?"
- Woke up in flash, knew had to get out of entire corn position as soon as market opened next day

**Execution:**
- Next morning, market opened up little higher, started selling
- Market moved little higher, sold more heavily
- Market moved up some more
- For minute, thought floor broker executed order backwards—he hadn't

**Exit:**
- Few minutes later, completely out of position and phone rings
- Friend Carl, another trader who had also been long corn
- "Jerry, is that you doing all the selling?" "Yes, I just got out of my entire position"
- "What are you doing?" he shouts
- "Carl, where is corn going to?" "About $4.15–4.20"
- "Where is corn now?" ask him
- Hear immediate click over phone—didn't even waste time saying good-bye

> "And was that the top of the corn market?"
>
> It might have gone up another day, but that was just about the high. Once it started falling, I could never have unloaded a position of my size.

### Schwager's Interpretation

**Found trader's dream narration particularly fascinating—has occasionally had similar experiences**

- Usually, found when feel strongly enough about trade (either getting in or getting out) to dream about it, message should be heeded
- Of course, doesn't work all the time, but believes it places odds more in favor

**How dreams work:**
- Dream is means by which subconscious penetrates barriers we sometimes erect in accepting true analysis of market
- Example: if bullish and not in market, might rationalize prudent to wait for reaction before entering—even if realistic assessment suggests such development unlikely
- This is confirmation that, to some extent, have already failed by not buying sooner—distasteful acknowledgment
- In such case, dream that market was going to run away on upside might be subconscious' way of breaking through mental impediments

## Final Word

**Common denominators among market wizards:**

1. **Driving desire to become successful traders**—in many cases, overcoming significant obstacles to reach goal

2. **Reflected confidence** they could continue to win over long run—almost invariably considered own trading as best and safest investment of their money

3. **Each trader had found methodology that worked** and remained true to that approach—discipline was word most frequently mentioned

4. **Top traders take trading very seriously**—most devote substantial amount of waking hours to market analysis and trading strategy

5. **Rigid risk control** one of key elements in trading strategy of virtually all those interviewed

6. **Importance of patience** to wait for right trading opportunity to present itself—stressed in variety of ways by many traders

7. **Importance of acting independent of the crowd** was frequently emphasized point

8. **All top traders understand that losing is part of the game**

9. **They all love what they are doing**

## What I Believe 22 Years Later

**Schwager's 2010 reflections on trading lessons:**

### Good Trades and Bad Trades

**Common error: judging trading decision by outcome**

- 2:1 odds on fair coin toss—if take bet and lose, still correct bet (making same decision repeatedly will be very profitable)
- Similarly, losing trade adhering to profitable strategy still good trade
- "A losing trade that adheres to a profitable strategy is still a good trade because if repeated many times it will win on balance"
- No way trader can know a priori which individual trade likely to be winner

**Flip side: winning trade can still be poor trading decision**
- Example: going long Internet stocks beginning January 2000, liquidating end February 2000
- In terms of outcome, brilliant trade
- But horrible trade in terms of making same decision over and over under similar circumstances
- Market happened to top early March, but could have easily topped early January
- "Even though the specific trade would have been profitable, if the same trading decision were made over and over again under similar circumstances, the net outcome would likely be very poor"

> "Trading is a matter of probabilities. Any trading strategy, no matter how effective, will be wrong a certain percentage of the time."

**Good vs. bad trades distinction:**
- Good trade follows process profitable if repeated multiple times (at acceptable risk), though can lose money on any individual trade
- Bad trade follows process that will lose money if repeated multiple times, but may make money on any individual trade
- Example: winning slot machine wager still bad bet—if repeated multiple times has high probability of losing money

### Implementation Is as Important as Direction

**Getting direction right only part of successful trade—putting trade on in right way is critical**

- One recently interviewed Market Wizard believes how trade implemented even more important than trade idea itself
- Seeks to implement providing best return-to-risk ratio and limiting losses if trade wrong

**NASDAQ bubble example (March 2000):**
- After break from March 2000 peak, felt fairly certain bubble had burst
- Yet didn't consider implementing short positions in NASDAQ
- Believed market had formed major bubble top
- But recognized trading short side was treacherous
- Even though market ultimately went sharply lower, summer 2000 witnessed approximate 40% rebound
- Move of this magnitude would have resulted in short position being stopped out
- Reasoned NASDAQ top implied most assets would recede from inflated levels, leading to economic slowdown and lower interest rates
- Long bond position provided much easier and more comfortable way to trade same idea
- Bonds subsequently witnessed fairly smooth uptrend, contrast to highly erratic downtrend in NASDAQ

### You Don't Get Paid for Being Right

**Insightful point: many traders fail not because of trades they make when wrong, but trades they don't make when right**

- Quite common for traders to be right on market call but fail to implement position and profit from market assessment
- Not enough being right—have to make sure make money when you are right
- Often requires doing trade that feels uncomfortable

**Example: waiting for pullback to buy after 2009 bottom**
- Traders who waited for significant pullback would have missed entire bull market of next two years

**How to make money when right:**
- Answer depends on circumstances—even then may not be any single correct answer
- Illustration: bullish on market but uncomfortable buying without pullback
- Alternative 1: Use buy order well below market (risks missing move entirely)
- Alternative 2: Place partial position at market, looking to scale into full position below market
  - If market keeps going up, at least will profit on partial position
- Alternative 3: Go long within consolidation, using protective stop meaningfully below consolidation
- No single correct answer
- Point: traders need to design trade entry and exit strategy to minimize chances of failing to profit when right on market

### Sometimes It Is What You Don't Do That Counts

> "Music is the space between the notes." —Claude Debussy

**Analogously, space between investments—times one is out of market—can be critical to successful investing**

- One manager recently interviewed (primarily net long equity investor) achieved cumulative gross returns in excess of 800% during 12-year period when broad equity market indexes essentially flat
- Superior stock selection important component, but not entire answer
- Not being invested (being primarily in cash) during negative environments is other part
- By not participating in market at wrong times, sidestepped most large drawdowns in equities during two major bear markets
- "Sometimes, being out of the market may be nearly as important to success as the investments made"
- Critical lesson: important not to be involved in market when opportunities are not there

**Corollary: importance of patience to successful investing**
- Need patience to stay on sidelines when environment adverse to approach or when opportunities lacking or suboptimal

### Risk Control of Course

**Risk control even more important than methodology for many Market Wizards**

- One recently interviewed manager goes so far as to limit risk to mere 0.1% on each trade from point of entry
- Once ahead on trade, will allow for more risk latitude
- Approach all but assures losses on new trades likely to be quite modest
- Only time vulnerable to significant monthly loss: when large open profits from winning trades

**General concept effectiveness:**
- Using 0.1% stop point from entry probably too extreme (or perhaps not even advisable) for most traders
- But general concept of using relatively close stop on new trades and allowing wider stop after profit margin has been created is effective risk management approach that could work well for many traders

> "If you are going to control your losses, there will be times when you will get out just before the market turns around in your favor. Get used to it."

- Frustrating experience is unavoidable consequence of effective risk management
- Keeping equity drawdowns moderate requires accepting fact sometimes end up liquidating losing positions right before they reverse dramatically

### Trade Size Can Be More Important Than Entry Point

**Traders focus almost entirely on where to enter trade—in reality, entry size often more important than entry price**

- If size too large, trader more likely to exit good trade on meaningless adverse price move
- Common mistake: letting greed influence position sizing beyond comfort level
- Danger: larger position, greater danger trading decisions driven by fear rather than judgment and experience
- Trading size needs kept small enough so fear doesn't become prevailing instinct guiding judgment

**Good trades can go wrong because of bad luck**
- Sometimes unforeseeable events can sabotage good trade
- By definition, losses due to events that cannot be anticipated are unavoidable
- But what trader can do: control magnitude of damage of adverse surprises by managing position size

**Not all trades created equal**
- One characteristic of Market Wizards: when perceive exceptional trade opportunities (e.g., high-probability trades, trades with large return potential relative to risk), will take larger-than-normal position

### Don't Try to Be 100 Percent Right

**Common dilemma faced by traders:**
- Market moving against position
- Well aware of dangers of unconstrained loss
- But also still believe in position, worried about throwing in towel just before market turns
- Frozen in indecision

**Solution: don't have to make all-or-nothing decision**
- Can liquidate part of position
- Taking partial loss much easier than liquidating entire position
- Allows trader to act rather than procrastinate
- Process can be repeated if market continues to move against position

**Why many traders resist partial liquidation:**
- Partially liquidate position, guaranteeing making wrong decision
  - Either on liquidated portion if market reverses
  - Or on retained portion if market move continues
- Need to be right prevents many traders from considering partial liquidation
- Next time undecided between liquidating losing position and gritting teeth and riding it out, remember third alternative: partial liquidation

### Trading Around a Position

**Many Market Wizards use dynamic rather than static approach to individual trades**

- Instead of simply one entry and one exit transaction, adjust position size on trades in response to market moves
- Taking partial profits on favorable price moves and replacing liquidated portion of positions on pullbacks
- Trading around position this way may improve performance and make easier to hold on to winning trades

**Example: long stock at 50, long-term objective 76, expecting near-term resistance vicinity of 62**
- Given assumptions, might choose to reduce long exposure on advance to 61-63 zone
- Looking to reinstate full position on pullback
- Potential drawback: retracement to reentry level may fail to occur—profits realized on smaller position
- Positive side: if liquidated portion of position reentered at better price, total profits enhanced
- Perhaps even more importantly, ability to hold position will be improved

**Whether trading around positions net beneficial or detrimental highly contingent on individual trader**
- Will not necessarily be good fit for all traders
- But some traders may find it highly useful approach

### Flexibility Is a Critical Trait

**Flexibility essential quality to successful trading**

- Important not to get attached to idea and always be willing to get out of trade if price action inconsistent with trade hypothesis
- One manager recently interviewed: "Really good traders are also capable of changing their mind in an instant. They can be dogmatic in their opinion and then immediately change it. *This market is going higher. It's absolutely going up. No, it's definitely going down.* If you can't do that, you will get caught in a position and be wiped out."

**Great traders have flexibility to completely change opinions if necessitated by facts**
- Don't hope they will be right
- Reevaluate why they might be wrong
- Importance of having flexibility to change applies not merely at trade level, but even to entire trading methodology

### The Best Remedy for a Losing Streak

**Virtually all traders experience periods when out of sync with markets**

- When in losing streak, can't turn situation around by trying harder
- When trading going badly, often best solution: liquidate all positions (or protect with stops that don't require decisions) and stop trading
- Take break for few days or longer
- Liquidating positions allows regaining objectivity—can't be objective if in market
- Taking physical break will interrupt negative downward spiral that can develop in losing streak
- Each loss further diminishes confidence
- When restart trading, trade smaller until regained confidence

### Volatility and Risk Are Not the Same

**Great misconception of investing public: equating risk with volatility (wrongheaded on multiple grounds)**

- First, frequently most important risks don't show up in track record and hence not reflected in volatility
- Example: portfolio of illiquid positions held during "risk on" period may have low volatility, but large risk if market sentiment shifts to "risk off"
- Other side: sometimes can have high volatility because of abrupt, large gains, but theoretical risk of investment is limited

**Some Market Wizards pursue highly asymmetrical strategies:**
- Maximum risk on trades well defined and contained
- While upside potential can be very large (e.g., long option strategies)
- More successful positive asymmetrical approach, greater volatility because of large gains
- Not characteristic most investors would associate with risk or consider undesirable

### Intuition—There Is Nothing Mystical about It

**Intuition is Rodney Dangerfield of trading skills—gets no respect**

- Frequently, intuition confused with lucky guesses
- Truth: intuition is experience based
- For many traders, intuition lies at very core of their success
- Nothing magical about intuition—simply subconscious experience

**How intuition works:**
- Trader who has strong bullish or bearish sense without knowing exactly why may simply be responding to subconscious recognition of similarity between current situation and past markets
- If find that intuition more right than wrong, trust it

### When Everything Is Going Great, Watch Out!

**Worst drawdowns often come suddenly right on heels of periods when just about everything seems to be working as well as if had been optimistically scripted**

**Why tendency for worst losses to follow best performance:**

1. When everything seems going perfectly, trader most susceptible to being lulled into complacency
2. Time when trader most likely to fail to consider what might go wrong, especially worst-case scenarios
3. Periods of excellent performance also likely to be times of high exposure

**Moral: Whenever portfolio sailing in new high ground and virtually all trades working as planned, guard against complacency and be extra cautious**

### Corollary: When You Are on the Right Side of Market Panic, Consider Getting Out

**If on right side of market that accelerates into parabolic move, may well make sense to take partial or total profits while market in panic state**

- Rather than waiting for reversal
- Which in these types of markets can be both abrupt and extreme when it does come
- In short: if long market that would be petrified to sell, it may
<!-- pp. 371-379 -->

### The Market Doesn't Care Where You Entered a Trade

- Don't make trading decisions based on entry price — the market doesn't care where you bought or sold
- Common error: waiting to "get out even" after realizing you're in a bad trade
- **Ego linkage** — if you can get out at even, you can say "I was not wrong, I did not make a mistake"
- The need to not be wrong is the very reason most people lose money in the markets
- Getting out even is psychologically important because it allows traders to avoid admitting error
- Linking liquidation to entry level is one of the major causes of turning small losses into large ones

> "The relevant question is: What would you do if you were not in the market?"

### Why Annual Targets May Be Counterproductive

- Avoid setting **annual return targets** — trades should be determined by opportunities, not artificial goals
- Annual expectations lead traders to:
  - Trade too small when opportunities are exceptionally favorable
  - Trade too large when opportunities are absent
- Pushing to reach a minimum annual target encourages taking marginal trades that wouldn't otherwise be made
- This can easily result in falling further short of the target
- Trading out of a desire to make money (rather than following opportunities) is dangerous

### The Path to Trading Success

- **No single true path** to trading success — Market Wizards use extraordinarily varied methodologies
- Trading approaches are not merely different but sometimes mirror opposites of each other
- The quest is not finding one approach that unlocks the secrets of market success
- **Success requires finding an approach that fits your personality**
- All Market Wizards found an approach that worked for them because it fit their personality
- What works for one Market Wizard can be disastrous for traders with different comfort levels

#### The Apprenticeship Fallacy

- Schwager receives inquiries like: "I wonder whether you know of any traders who are looking for apprentices. I'm willing to work long hours without pay to be able to learn from one of the Market Wizards"
- This type of query reflects a **misdirected quest**
- You cannot succeed by copying someone else's approach
- The odds are remote that their method will fit your personality
- **The answer lies not in copying someone else's method, but in finding your own**

> "The remainder of this chapter is adapted from *Market Wizards in the Hedge Fund Era*, a work in progress by the author."

## Appendix 1: Program Trading and Portfolio Insurance

### Program Trading Defined

- **Program trading** has received widespread publicity but is poorly understood
- Less than one out of ten people opposed to program trading even know its definition
- Source of confusion: term used interchangeably to describe both:
  - The original activity (classic arbitrage)
  - A more general term encompassing various computer-supported trading strategies (e.g., **portfolio insurance**)

### Classic Program Trading Mechanics

- Program trading represents a **classic arbitrage activity**
- One market is bought against an equal short sale in a closely related market
- Goal: realize small, **risk-free profits** from short-lived distortions in price relationships
- Program traders buy or sell a basket of stocks against an equal dollar value position in stock index futures
- They perceive actual stocks to be underpriced or overpriced relative to futures
- Program trading tends to keep actual stock and stock index futures prices in line

### Program Trading and Market Crashes

- Every program-related sale of actual stocks is offset by a purchase at another time
- Most program trades are first initiated as long stock/short futures positions (due to uptick requirement in shorting actual stocks)
- Arguments that program trading is responsible for stock market declines are **highly tenuous**
- Economic evidence indicates that arbitrage between related markets tends to reduce volatility
- The relationship between increased volatility and program trading is **questionable at best**

### Portfolio Insurance Explained

- **Portfolio insurance** refers to systematic sale of stock index futures as stock portfolio value declines
- Designed to reduce risk exposure
- Once reduced, the net long exposure is increased back toward a full position as the representative stock index price increases
- Theory presumes that market prices move smoothly
- When prices witness an abrupt, huge move, the results may differ substantially from theory

### October 19, 1987 — Portfolio Insurance's Role

- On **October 19, 1987**, prices gapped beyond threshold portfolio insurance sell levels
- Triggered an avalanche of sell orders executed far below theoretical levels
- Although portfolio insurance may have accelerated the decline on October 19, underlying forces would likely have resulted in a similar price decline over more days
- This is a question that can never be answered
- Doubtful that program trading (as defined above) played much of a role in the crash
- Severely delayed openings of individual stocks, confusion related to prevailing price levels, and exchange restrictions on automated order entry systems severely impeded classic arbitrage activity

## Appendix 2: Options—Understanding the Basics

### Call and Put Options Defined

- Two basic types: **calls** and **puts**
- **Call option**: buyer has right (not obligation) to purchase underlying item at a specified **strike price** (or **exercise price**) at any time up to and including the **expiration date**
- **Put option**: buyer has right (not obligation) to sell underlying item at strike price any time prior to expiration
- Buying a put is a **bearish** trade; selling a put is a **bullish** trade
- Price of an option is called a **premium**
- Example: IBM April 130 call gives purchaser right to buy 100 shares of IBM at $130 per share at any time during option life

### Call Buyer Mechanics

- Call buyer seeks to profit from anticipated price rise by locking in a specified purchase price
- Maximum possible loss = premium paid for the option
- Maximum loss occurs if option held until expiration and strike price is above prevailing market price
- For call buyer to realize net profit, difference between market price and strike price must exceed premium paid (after adjusting for commission cost)
- Higher the market price, greater the resulting profit

### Put Buyer Mechanics

- Put buyer seeks to profit from anticipated price decline by locking in a sales price
- Maximum possible loss limited to premium paid
- For a put held until expiration, trade shows net profit if strike price exceeds market price by amount greater than premium (after adjusting for commission cost)

### Option Seller Risk Profile

- Option buyer has limited risk and unlimited potential gain
- Reverse is true for the **seller** (often called the **writer**)
- Option seller receives dollar value of premium in return for undertaking obligation to assume opposite position **at the strike price** if option is exercised
- Example: if a call is exercised, seller must assume short position in underlying market at strike price

### Call and Put Seller Strategies

- **Call seller** seeks to profit from anticipated sideways to modestly declining market
- In such situations, premium earned by selling a call provides most attractive trading opportunity
- If trader expected large price decline, usually better off going short the underlying market or buying a put (trades with open-ended profit potential)
- **Put seller** seeks to profit from anticipated sideways to modestly rising market

### Probability and Option Trading

- Novices have trouble understanding why trader wouldn't always prefer buy side (unlimited potential, limited risk)
- Such confusion reflects failure to take **probability** into account
- Although option seller's theoretical risk is unlimited, price levels with greatest probability of occurrence (prices near market price when option trade occurs) would result in net gain to option seller
- Option buyer accepts large probability of small loss in return for small probability of large gain
- Option seller accepts small probability of large loss in exchange for large probability of small gain
- In an efficient market, neither consistent option buyer nor consistent option seller should have significant advantage over the long run

### Option Premium Components

- Option premium consists of two components: **intrinsic value** plus **time value**
- **Intrinsic value** of a call option = amount by which current market price is above strike price
- Intrinsic value of a put option = amount by which current market price is below strike price
- Intrinsic value is that part of premium that could be realized if option were exercised at current market price
- Intrinsic value serves as a **floor price** for an option
- Why? If premium were less than intrinsic value, trader could buy and exercise option and immediately offset resulting market position, realizing net gain (assuming trader covers at least transaction costs)

### In-the-Money, Out-of-the-Money, At-the-Money

- Options with intrinsic value (calls with strike prices below market price; puts with strike prices above market price) are **in-the-money**
- Options with no intrinsic value are **out-of-the-money**
- Options with strike price closest to market price are **at-the-money**

### Time Value Explained

- Out-of-the-money option (intrinsic value = zero) still has value because of possibility market price will move beyond strike price prior to expiration
- In-the-money option will have value greater than intrinsic value
- Why? Position in option preferred to position in underlying market because both option and market position gain equally in event of favorable price movement, but option's maximum loss is limited
- Portion of premium exceeding intrinsic value is called the **time value**

### Three Factors Influencing Option Time Value

**(1) Relationship between strike and market price**
- Deeply out-of-the-money options have little time value — unlikely market price will move to strike price (or beyond) prior to expiration
- Deeply in-the-money options have little time value — these options offer positions very similar to underlying market (both gain and lose equivalent amounts for all but extremely adverse price move)
- For deeply in-the-money option, fact that risk is limited is not worth very much because strike price is so far from prevailing market price

**(2) Time remaining until expiration**
- The more time remaining, the greater the value of the option
- Longer life span increases probability of intrinsic value increasing by any specified amount prior to expiration

**(3) Volatility**
- Time value varies directly with estimated **volatility** [measure of degree of price variability] of underlying market for remaining life span of option
- Greater volatility raises probability of intrinsic value increasing by any specified amount prior to expiration
- In other words, the greater the volatility, the greater the probable price range of the market

### Historical vs. Implied Volatility

- Volatility is extremely important factor in determination of option premium values
- Future volatility of a market is never precisely known until after the fact
- (Time remaining until expiration and relationship between current market price and strike price can be exactly specified at any juncture)
- Volatility must always be estimated on basis of **historical volatility** data
- Future volatility estimate implied by market prices (option premiums), which may be higher or lower than historical volatility, is called the **implied volatility**

> "Adapted from Jack D. Schwager, *A Complete Guide to the Futures Market* (New York: John Wiley & Sons, 1984)."

